<FIRST>r a AM-HanfordLeaks     01-27 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hanford Leaks,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>At Least 9,500 Gallons Of Radioactive Nuclear Wastes Leaked In 1988</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 9,500 gallons of highly
radioactive nuclear waste leaked from aging storage tanks on the
Hanford nuclear reservation in 1988, according to Department of
Energy documents.
   Seven of the 149 aging, single-walled storage tanks on the Energy
department's plutonium production site were suspected of leaking
last year, the documents said.
   More than 500,000 gallons have spilled into soil around the 1
million gallon-capacity tanks since the late 1970s, but the Energy
Department contends the wastes do not enter groundwater, posing no
environmental or health risks.
   ``It's a drop in the bucket when you consider ... leaks of
500,000 gallons,'' said Jim Thomas of the Spokane-based Hanford
Education Action League, on Thursday. ``But environmental
contamination is still happening.''
   The wastes are byproducts of more than 40 years of plutonium
production for nuclear weapons at the south-central Washington site
generally considered the most contaminated of the DOE's production
sites.
   Estimates for cleaning up the site run to $57 billion over the
next 50 years.
   Bill Klink, a spokesman for Westinghouse Hanford Co., the
contractor that handles the storage tanks, said there is little that
can be done to prevent the leaks.
   Klink said 115,000 gallons that leaked from a tank in 1973 have
stayed within 165 feet of that tank. The tanks are no longer used,
and liquids from at least 95 of them have been into 28 newer,
double-walled tanks on the site.
   However, a large volume of highly concentrated, non-pumpable but
moist ``salt cake'' remains at the bottom of the tanks. DOE
officials concede they are unsure how to permanently dispose of
those wastes.
   Reports on file at the Energy Department's reading room in
Richland, along with its news eleases, show at least seven suspected
leaks during 1988.
   A May news release said that four tanks previously considered
stabilized showed signs of declining liquid levels, and estimated
about 1,500 gallons had leaked.
   The reports say that in July, the level of liquid wastes two
storage tanks was found to have dropped.
   One leak was estimated at 3,000 gallons, the report said. The
other lost about 5,000 gallons.
   Another tank, also showed a gradual decrease in the waste level
``indicating a possible leak or evaporation of residual liquids,''
according to an October ``unusual occurence'' report.
</TEXT>
