<FIRST>r a PM-UglyTie     01-27 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ugly Tie,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ugliest Tie Contest Winners: Wide, Colorful And Repulsive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH J. HARPAZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What's black and white and red all over, made
from puckered polyester stretch fabric, and covered with starfish?
   The winner of the ``Ugliest Tie in America'' contest, of course.
   This revolting piece of neckwear and 1,400 other contest entries
were on display Thursday evening at the Italian Trade Commission in
New York, which advertised the competition in Esquire magazine as a
way to promote a tasteful alternative _ silk designer ties in
subdued colors, imported from Italy.
   Among the top 10 ugly ties, brightly colored nylon and large
geometric shapes were common. The grand prize-winning black, white
and red number was submitted by 18-year-old Asim Siddique of Dallas,
who said he had a hard time choosing from his father's large
assortment of hideous neckwear.
   ``I thought I had a pretty good shot at winning,'' said Siddique,
a freshman at Collin County Junior College, reached at home by
telephone. ``Once you see the collection, you would think the odds
are on your side.''
   Siddique won 50 Italian designer silk ties as grand prize, and he
plans to stick a few in his dad's closet ``when he's not looking.''
   Each of the 10 runners-up won 25 designer ties.
   One of the runners-up, Geraldine Friedman of Upper Montclair,
N.J., sent in a brown, gold and silver tie bearing a design of
medallions, diamonds and black and white checks.
   She said her husband wore it to their son's bar mitzvah 15 years
ago but ``I doubt he's worn it since. ... My husband has so many of
these ugly ties that you can't believe.''
   Among the other runners-up were a velour tie covered with
multicolored hexagons submitted by Kevin Shippy of Akron, Ohio, and
a green-and-yellow number with large flowers of which the owner,
Colin Mackenzie of Vancouver, Canada, wrote: ``I wore it with a pink
shirt and love beads.''
   The neckwear that didn't win included ties bearing smile faces,
sailboats, American flags, pieces of a patchwork quilt, peace signs,
and even a naked woman.
   Most of the ugly ties were also very wide, five to six inches and
more. The ideal width for a tie these days, according to the
February issue of Gentlemen's Quarterly, is 3{ to 3} inches.
   Italian Trade Commissioner Mario Costagna said that when he saw
the winners, ``I was about to faint.'' He said he doubted there
would be quite so many klunkers were the same contest held in Italy.
   Costagna said Americans bought more than $62 million worth of
Italian ties last year.
   Esquire's editor-in-chief, Lee Eisenberg, said he made sure to
wear a ``perfectly boring'' black-and-white tie to the party
announcing the winners. He blamed the profusion of ugly ties not on
their owners but on gift-givers.
   Looking at the hundreds of fashion disasters on display, he said:
``I find it kind of melancholy. To me it represents 1,200 sad
Father's Day mornings.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
