<FIRST>r a PM-MagneticAttraction     01-27 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Magnetic Attraction,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Medical Magnet Irresistible, Janitor Finds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hospital officials say a janitor should have
known better than to take a vacuum cleaner into a room where even
jewelry and credit cards are prohibited because of a powerful magnet
inside a diagnostic machine.
   The janitor, whom Allegheny General Hospital officials declined
to identify Thursday, was struck Monday by the vacuum as it was
whisked several feet toward the Magnetic Resonance Imaging unit,
which uses a magnetic field to record images from inside the body.
   The janitor, part of a crew stripping wax from the floor, escaped
with bruises and a cut.
   ``We take great pains to tell and show our housekeeping staff
what they should and should not take in there,'' said Shawn Haag,
the hospital's vice president of operations.
   Employees are told to remove any metal, including jewelry, before
entering the room. They are warned that even information coded into
the black magnetic strip on the back of credit cards can be
scrambled by the magnet, which is 10 feet by 10 feet by 6 feet.
   The MRI unit ``has a few scratches, but we expect it has only
minor damage,'' Haag said.
</TEXT>
