<DOCNO> AP890127-0009 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 0150EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-OilWar-Glance     01-27 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil War-Glance,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Fats Behind The `Oil War'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Oil War</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The debate over the use of tropical oils in foods centers on the
role fat plays in the diet. Research shows that eating a diet high
in fat, particularly saturated fats, causes elevated blood
cholesterol levels in many people. High cholesterol levels increase
the risk of heart disease.
   Despite the war of words between producers of the various oils,
nutritionists say one can still be at risk if the total percentage
of fat consumed, whether so-called ``good'' fat or not, is too high.
   Here is a brief explanation of fats:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>FAT BASICS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   All dietary fats are mixtures of three kinds of fatty acids:
saturated, mono-saturated, and polyunsaturated.
   According to some studies, the relative health merits of
different oils and fats are determined by the proportions of each of
the three different kinds of fatty acids in the individual oil or
fat.
   However, all fats, no matter what the proportion of the three
fatty acids they contain, provide the same number of calories, 9 per
gram.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>SATURATED FATTY ACIDS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Fats with a higher proportion of saturated fatty acids are
generally solid at room temperature. Research indicates they
increase blood cholesterol.
   ANIMAL FATS have a higher proportion of saturated fatty acids
than most fats from plants. Animal fats also contain cholesterol.
Examples of animal fat are: chicken fat, lard, precreamed or animal
fat shortening, beef fat, and butter.
   TROPICAL OILS are derived from plants, and therefore contain no
cholesterol. However, they are high in saturated fatty acids. Some
tropical oils actually have more saturated fatty acids than the
animal fats. Examples of tropical oils are: palm oil, coconut oil,
and palm kernel oil.
   HYDROGENATED FATS are other fats of plant origin that have been
processed, or hydrogenated, and have become saturated fats. The
degree of saturation is dependent on the processing, but generally
the harder the product is at room temperature, the more saturated it
is. Examples of hydrogenated products are: hard shortenings, hard or
stick margarines, and some kinds of peanut butter.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MONO-SATURATED FATTY ACIDS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Fats with a high proportion of monosaturated fatty acids do not
increase blood cholesterol. Studies suggest the monosaturates,
particularly olive oil, actually reduce levels of cholesterol in the
blood. Examples of monosaturated fats are: olive oil, peanut oil and
avocado oil.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>POLYUNSATURATED FATTY ACIDS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Fats with a high proportion of polyunsaturated fatty acids are
found primarily in plants and in some kinds of fish. Polyunsaturates
reduce the risk of heart disease by lowering cholesterol levels in
the blood. Examples of polyunsaturates are: sunflower oil, corn oil,
soybean oil, cottonseed oil, safflower oil and some fish oils.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sources:
   Dietary Guidelines for Americans, Home and Garden Bulletin Number
232-3, April 1986, United States Department of Agriculture.
   and
   ``The New American Diet'' by Sonja L. Conner and William E.
Conner, M.D., Fireside, 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890127-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 0153EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-APArts:TheStars     01-27 0783</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: The Stars,0799</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Artists Reunite 10 Years After Unprecedented Exhibit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A decade after their avant-garde exhibition in a
Beijing park shook up the moribund Chinese art world, a group of
pioneering artists has reunited in this British colony for their
first retrospective.
   The youthful Chinese artists, known as ``The Stars,'' shot to
prominence in 1979 when they marched through Beijing to protest
police interference in a show they had set up without official
approval.
   The authorities gave in and allowed the artists to stage the
exhibition, unprecedented in Communist China, that featured
once-forbidden topics such as nudes, abstracts and works of
aesthetic rather than political content.
   After another show in 1980, however, the 30-member group
disbanded. While some remained active in Beijing, others scattered
around the globe, settling in Europe, Japan and the United States.
   Six of the artists were recently in Hong Kong for a retrospective
featuring the work of 12 group members. The exhibition opened
earlier this month in the basement gallery of a posh residential
neighborhood and is scheduled to run for five weeks before moving to
Taipei, Taiwan and Paris.
   Sculptor Wang Keping said The Stars were significant by showing
that artistic activity in China need not be organized or approved by
the ruling party. ``Earlier art was all the same,'' he said.
   Individuality was the driving force behind the group, agrees
Chang Tsong-zung, the owner of Hanart Gallery who organized the
retrospective. ``The only common aim of the artists when they first
started was that they wanted to be different from each other.''
   Bo Yun, a teacher at the Academy of Arts and Design in Beijing
whose abstract scroll paintings are part of the retrospective, said
artistic freedom in China has advanced since the group's landmark
1979 exhibition but limitations remain.
   There is no problem, he said, ``if you use a work of art to
satirize an opponent of the government. But if you mock the
government, I'm afraid that will pose a problem.''
   Members of The Stars also say Beijing no longer allows them to
exhibit as a group, thwarting two attempts in 1983 and 1986. The
reason, believes Bo, is that the group's name has become a symbol of
the democracy movement.
   The retrospective includes works that date from the group's
heyday, including Wang's Buddha-like bust of Chairman Mao Tse-tung
signifying the deification of the Communist leader during the
ultraleftist 1966-76 Cultural Revolution. It is called ``The Idol.''
   Other pieces adopt obviously current themes, including the
mixed-media work ``Safe Sex'' by Ai Weiwei that features a
prophylactic attached to a rain coat. Prices run from hundreds to
thousands of dollars.
   The works are as different as the paths the artists have taken
since they disbanded after their Beijing exhibitions.
   Wang, 39, a soft-spoken man with a wisp of a goatee who joined
the fanatical Red Guard during the Cultural Revolution, moved to
Paris in 1984, convinced he could not develop further in China
largely because of political pressure. ``Art freedom is only
possible in a democratic country with human rights,'' he said.
   The sculptor lives and works out of a workshop he rents from the
French government and has been featured at the Museum of
Contemporary Art in Paris and the Olympic Sculpture Park in Seoul,
South Korea.
   Wang recently wrote a political play titled, ``The Retrial of Wei
Jingsheng,'' a contemporary of The Stars who led a fledgling
pro-democracy movement in China before being jailed for 15 years in
1979. Wang said the play will be performed in Paris this March.
   Bo, 40, has remained in Beijing although he is considering a move
overseas. He supplements his 150 yuan ($40) a month salary by
selling his paintings to foreigners in China and at overseas
exhibits. He owns a tiny Fiat, a sign of financial well-being in a
country where private cars remain rare.
   Other Stars on display in the retrospective include Huang Rui and
Ma Desheng, the two leaders of the group, and Li Shuang, who was
arrested in 1981 and sentenced to two years of labor re-education
for ``incitement to debauchery.'' When she was arrested, she was
living with a French diplomat but had not yet married him.
   The exhibition includes caligraphy by Zhong Ahcheng, also known
as Ah Cheng, whose fictional work ``The King of Children'' was
translated to film and premiered at the Cannes Film Festival last
year.
   Although The Stars have spread throughout the world they have
stayed in touch with one another. From the heady days of 1979-80 was
forged ``a feeling of brotherhood'' that has not diminished, Bo said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
