<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Sausage     01-27 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Sausage,0611</SECOND>
<HEAD>Furry Jury Sniffs At Soviet Sausage</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angry meatpackers are suing a newspaper for an
article that said their sausage was so bad that even cats can't
stomach it, but editors said they turned to a furry, four-legged
jury that proved their point.
   ``Twenty-four sausage experts don't eat it at all; five only eat
high quality sausage or out of extreme hunger. Only one, the
2-month-old kitten Mura, you can say actually sits down to the
sausage,'' the weekly Literaturnaya Gazeta said in announcing the
feline findings.
   The dispute started with the literary weekly's story on June 15
titled ``The Cat Doesn't Know ... '' and was brought up recently in
the Dzerzhinsky regional people's court.
   In a complaint signed by Yu. M. Luzhkov, chairman of the Moscow
agroindustrial complex, officials demanded a retraction of the
newspaper's report that producers were breaking the law by putting
protein additives in the sausage, known in Russian as ``kolbasa.''
   Because of a shortage of meat in many Soviet stores, finding good
quality sausage has become a fixation for many people. A cartoon in
an October edition of the satire magazine Krokodil showed a line of
shoppers standing outside a theater, not to buy tickets, but to buy
the sausage for sale in the theater's buffet.
   The case also shows that the more aggressive style of reporting
by the Soviet press under President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
encouragement of greater openness is likely to get it into
occasional legal trouble. The Tass news agency said this week a
court had dismissed a lawsuit against a film producer by a
biochemical plant near Leningrad that objected to his documentary
about pollution.
   Literaturnaya Gazeta reported about its dispute with the sausage
manufacturers in an article in this week's edition titled, ``May the
Cats Judge Us.'' It gave no indication that the case had gone any
further than the initial complaint.
   It said that using the permission of state quality control
officials to add protein additives, the factories were grinding up
the skin and bones of cattle and throwing them into the sausage.
   Animal blood, protein paste, blood plasma, starch, flour, and
emulsions of protein and fat also were part of the gray,
unappetizing mixtures churned out by the factories, Literaturnaya
Gazeta said.
   ``Blocks of frozen meat weren't unfrozen or washed before being
chopped, and were happily thrown in with knots of wool and even the
trademarks of the factories that produced these blocks. Nails, sand
and glass have fallen into the sausage,'' it said.
   To judge the validity of its first story, the newspaper said it
sought out the Fauna Cat Lovers' Club in the Dzerzhinsky region,
where it is being sued.
   Boris Berenshtein fed some sausage to Kuzya, his 2{-year-old cat,
``but Kuzya didn't find any joy in it. Just the opposite, he gave a
look like a person saying, `What's that for? What did I do that was
so bad, master?' ''
   It said another cat, Gavrila, tests the sausage for the whole
family of Maria Klyueva. If Gavrila eats it, the whole family will.
If she turns up her nose, so does the family.
   In the end, out of 30 cats, only Mura the kitten eats the sausage
regularly, Literaturnaya Gazeta said.
   ``All kitties, like Mura, must loyally love sausage! That's the
way it always has been since man thought up sausage. But why, the
devil take them, won't they eat it?'' the newspaper asked. ``And why
do we continue to eat it?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890127-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 0209EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Fashion     01-27 0780</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fashion,0802</SECOND>
<HEAD>Valentino Debuts In French Haute Couture</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARILYN AUGUST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The French haute couture world rolled out the red
carpet for Valentino, the king of Italian couture who showed a new
spring-summer high fashion collection that was sensuous and pretty.
   Valentino ruffled feathers in Rome when he announced he was
taking his collection to Paris. Then his business manager Giancarlo
Giametti made matters worse by saying that Valentino could no longer
afford to show for ``down-and-out women and second-rate actresses''
in Rome.
   On Thursday, the Italian master closed a week of French shows on
a high note, flattering the female form with generous draping, front
and back.
   Not all the designs were sexy. Some daytime wear was so strict it
made the models look like tea room waitresses or high-class nannies.
Stiff and proper white collars popped out of impeccable navy blue
suits, and for the cocktail hour, they reappeared in black and white
with dainty lace bibs, aprons and cuffs.
   There were lots of fabulous high-waisted pants. Ending above the
ankle and worn with high heels, they were perfect with suit jackets
and belted tunics.
   ``The collection is beautiful, just beautiful,'' Italian actress
Ornella Muti said after the show. ``There's nothing for me for the
day, because I don't dress up. The evening dresses were wonderful.
Especially the long black dresses.''
   Miss Muti said she was sorry Valentino's clothes can't be worn
more often.
   ``In Rome, you just don't have occasions to wear things like
that,'' she said.
   The Golden Thimble award for the season's most beautiful
collection went to Guy Laroche for spring and summer designs that
some fashion insiders say may be his last. Laroche has been ill for
some time, and he looked gaunt at the Wednesday showing of classic
designs in luscious colors.
   The two-time winner of the Golden Thimble, Laroche said
``eccentricity was not the synonym for elegance.''
   The shirtwaist classic was the story at Givenchy on Thursday,
with high fashion clothes modeled to the romantic crooning of Frank
Sinatra and Yves Montand.
   Classic daytime dresses in gabardine, silk shantung and linen,
skimmed the knee, flared in gentle pleats at the hips, belted at the
waist and tied up at the neck in time for a business lunch.
   There were lots of pantsuits for daytime wear. Full-cut to
camouflage the bumps and adorned with flat, horizontal pockets,
trousers ended just above the ankle, giving a nice, balanced line.
   Givenchy's suits in buttery leather melted in the mouth. Striking
in bright blue and juicy red and stunning in black and white, the
classic blazer softened into new shades of honey, cognac and
mustard. Simple cotton tank tops and silk tie blouses were worn
underneath to give that beautiful, pared-down look Givenchy was
looking for.
   Spring was in the air with go-anywhere, broad-shouldered suits in
creamy whites and pastels, often decorated with round gold buttons
and nipped slightly at the waist.
   Cocktail dresses were a little sexier, with belted or draped
waists, side slits and plunging necklines. Again, the shirtwaist
style, but updated with gold metal braiding and appliques outlining
hems and lower sleeves.
   There were plenty of dresses for hot summer nights and the
schoolmarm daytime look loosened up with pretty floral motifs and
geometric patterns in gauze, crepe and chiffon.
   Givenchy excelled at evening wear, serving up a myriad of colors
and styles. There were organza sheaths and chiffon dresses with
embroidery recalling sea grottoes, along with bustiers of pearl and
porcelaine. One mousseline bustier dress looked like an Indian sari.
   Per Spook also showed on Thursday, presenting a collection based
on the comfort and versatility of wide-legged pajama pants that
covered the foot and brushed the floor.
   His models, in tie-up or sling-back flats most of the time, wore
pants under everything from layers of silk jackets to
off-the-shoulder, ruffled shirts.
   Muted greens, sandy beiges, khaki and camel and burnished oranges
dominated Spook's color palette for daytime wear, but they exploded
into shimmering blues, reds, greens and oranges for evening. Silk
crepe jackets and tuniques, topping orange and yellow silk pants,
were embroidered with sequins and tiny mirrors and emblazoned with
dragons.
   Spook also presented an array of skirts, conventional and
wrap-around, with asymetrical hemlines. Most hit the knee but some
dropped to the less seen midcalf.
   Spook's wedding dress in blue, white and red was a salute to this
year's bicentennial celebrations of the French Revolution. Inspired
by the low-necked, corseted look popular two centuries ago, the
dress _ in silk taffeta _ was puffed up by tricolor petticoats and
set off with ruffles and a big bustle.
</TEXT>
