<FIRST>r a PM-PlayboyPinball     01-27 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Playboy Pinball,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Playing the Pins Playboy Style, with Sighs, Wolf Whistles _ and Hef</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new pinball game takes players on a sumptuous
romp through the Playboy mansion, packed with playmates and pleasure
in the hedonistic style that made Hugh Hefner famous.
   ``Ciao, babe. You look beautiful,'' says Hef, the game's amiable
host, whose tape-recorded voice comes over a digital stereo system
on the computerized, bi-level playfield.
   Wolf whistles and sighs are heard as players rack up points on
the state-of-the-art pinball machine, which is being built to
commemorate Playboy magazine's 35th anniversary.
   ``This will be the pinnacle of pinball for the 80's,'' said Joe
Kaminkow, designer of the machine for Data East Pinball Inc. of
suburban Melrose Park.
   ``There are ramp shots that take you through the mansion and its
grotto. There are cooing birds and cooing girls. The mansion's zoo
is in there, too.''
   The backglass, which combines color photography and animation,
features Playboy founder Hefner and his bride-to-be, Kimberley
Conrad, playing host to a party of playmates by the swimming pool
with its cascading waterfall.
   Hefner's voice accompanies players throughout the game, at one
point asking whether anybody wants more champagne.
   ``I've been playing it for nine months,'' Kaminkow said. ``I love
it.''
   The machine, the second marketed by Chicago-based Playboy, will
be officially unveiled May 11 at a party at the mansion in Holmby
Hill, Calif., with Hefner and Ms. Conrad on hand.
</TEXT>
