<FIRST>r a AM-Gates     01-27 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gates,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Los Angeles Police Chief First in GOP Race for Governor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Daryl Gates, a 40-year veteran of the Los
Angeles Police Department and chief of the 7,000-member force since
1978, filed papers Thursday to become the first Republican in the
1990 race for governor.
   Gates, 62, said his announcement was only of the formation of an
exploratory committee, and that he would not be campaigning actively
in the immediate future or stepping down from the chief's post.
   The chief was required by a new state law, Proposition 73 of last
June, to sign a formal ``Statement of Intent'' which declares that
he is seeking funds for use in a campaign for the office of governor.
   He didn't say when he would make a final decision on whether to
launch an active campaign, but he said if he did do so, he would
resign as police chief.
   Republican Gov. George Deukmejian announced three weeks ago that
he intends to retire from public life when he completes his second
term in 1991, opening the way for a free-for-all for the GOP
nomination in the June 1990 primary.
   U.S. Sen. Pete Wilson and Baseball Commissioner Peter Ueberroth,
also are considering the GOP race.
   On the Democratic side, Attorney General John Van de Kamp, a
former Los Angeles district attorney, is the early favorite for the
Democratic nomination in a possible race with former San Francisco
Mayor Dianne Feinstein and Controller Gray Davis.
   The muscular, athletic Gates has spent his entire career in the
Los Angeles Police Department, joining the force as a 22-year-old
rookie in 1949 following his graduation from the University of
Southern California.
   He is credited for the inconspicuous security his department
provided during the 1984 Summer Olympics, but was criticized after
remarking that blacks reacted differently than ``normal people'' to
a controversial police chokehold.
</TEXT>
