<DOCNO> AP890127-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 0722EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-InfantDeaths     01-27 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Infant Deaths,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coroner Finds No Sign Of Crime In Death Of Three Infants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FOREST PARK, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There is no sign of foul play in the
simultaneous deaths of three of four quadruplets on Jan. 13, the
Fulton County medical examiner said Thursday.
   The infants, Kia, Mia and DeAnthony, were found by their mother,
Tonja L. Walker, at about 5 a.m. on Jan. 13. The fourth infant,
DeAndrea, was hospitalized but now is in good health.
   ``I'm not telling you it's a matter of black and white _ it's
not,'' said Dr. Joseph Burton. ``The scales just tip away from the
direction of foul play at this time.''
   Burton said the simultaneous, unexplained deaths may be unique in
forensic science. He said autopsies revealed that two of the three
had respiratory problems that could have contributed to death.
   The cause, he said, will be listed as ``sudden unexplained death
in infancy.'' He said he probably always will have ``haunting
suspicions'' about the case.
   He said autopsies ruled out meningitis, which doctors suspected
at first as the cause of death.
   There were no signs of strangulation or suffocation. ``We tested
for sedatives, tranquilizers, pesticides, arsenic, strychnine,
cocaine, marijuana, the whole shooting match,'' he said. ``We tested
blood, tissues, stomach contents.''
   Neuro-forensic experts reported finding an unusual change in a
brain cell in the base of one infant's brain. The brain stem
controls breathing.
   Investigators initially suspected foul play because of deaths
happened together and because of contradictory statements made by
adults in the house.
   Maj. L. Dwayne Hobbs of the Forest Park Police Department said
the case remains open but inactive.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
