<DOCNO> AP890127-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 0226EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a BC-DuPontAwards     01-27 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-DuPont Awards,0637</SECOND>
<HEAD>`60 Minutes' Captures Gold Baton Award For Two Decades Of Reporting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The CBS News program ``60 Minutes'' on Thursday
received the Alfred I. duPont-Columbia University Gold Baton Award
for two decades of reporting that ``changed the nature of television
news,'' the school announced.
   The Gold Baton, the highest honor of the prestigious broadcast
journalism awards, was formally presented at a ceremony hosted by
Charles Kuralt, anchor of CBS-TV's ``Sunday Morning'' program.
   Other network television winners among the 13 news programs to
capture Silver Batons at the 47th annual awards were CBS News for
coverage of the Persian Gulf by Allen Pizzey, NBC News for ``A
Conversation with Mikhail Gorbachev'' and ABC News for ``Nightline:
In The Holy Land,'' the university said in a release.
   The ``60 Minutes'' program was cited by the awards jurors for
doing ``more than just establish the news magazine format for
television.''
   ``In its 20-year existence it has given more time in prime time
to investigative pieces, captivating features, fascinating profiles
and historic interviews than any other program in the history of
television news,'' the release said.
   In major television markets, Silver Baton award winners included
WCVB-TV in Boston for ``We the Jury,'' in which producer-reporter
David Ropeik found a judge, lawyers and a defendant who let him
follow a trial through the eyes and experiences of the sequestered
jurors.
   Other winners were WWOR-TV of Secaucus, N.J., for tough reports
on the health and safety of children in Jersey City schools and
patronage in that city's school administration, and WUSA-TV of
Washington for ``Thurgood Marshall: The Man,'' in which Marshall
speaks bluntly about a variety of subjects.
   In medium television markets, winners were Erin Hayes and WSMV of
Nashville, Tenn., and KING-TV of Seattle for ``Looking for Lincoln.''
   Columbia University said Ms. Hayes ``consistently demonstrates
her ability to tackle stories other journalists shy away from.'' For
example, it said, she pursued subjects such as sewage overflow as a
potentially serious problem and used an unusual style of
understatement in an investigative report on restaurant inspections.
   According to the release, even before the presidential primaries
KING-TV ``recognized the importance of examining the character of
the 13 major candidates and resourcefully formed a team of seven
local stations around the nation to produce revealing portraits of
each candidate.''
   In small television markets, winners were WCAX-TV of Burlington,
Vt., for ``The Politics of Pollution,'' and John Camp and WBRZ of
Baton Rouge, La., for investigative reporting.
   WCAX-TV used ``extremely effective pictures and natural sound''
to describe the impact of acid rain on New England and the economic
impact of cleaning up industrial pollution, Columbia said.
   Camp demonstrated a ``consistently high level of investigative
reporting'' by documenting mismanagement, bribery and patronage in
the practices of Louisiana's Office of Alcohol Beverage Control, and
by exposing how accident victims sometimes collect huge damage
claims because attorneys fail to challenge the claims in court,
Columbia said.
   For independent television production, Public Affairs Television
and Alvin H. Perlmutter Inc. received an award for ``Joseph Campbell
and the Power of Myth, with Bill Moyers,'' six hourlong
conversations with Campbell, a leading scholar and teacher of
mythology, the release said.
   In radio, Nina Totenberg and National Public Radio was honored
for coverage of the Supreme Court nominations.
   The university noted that Ms. Totenberg broke the story of Judge
Douglas Ginsburg's use of marijuana, ``raising issues of changing
social values and credibility with careful perspective under
deadline pressure.''
   The Alfred I. duPont-Columbia University Awards were established
in 1942 by the late Jessie Ball duPont in memory of her husband,
Alfred I. duPont.
   Winners were selected from more than 600 submissions made by
radio and television news directors and producers nationwide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890127-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 0312EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Poland-Priest     01-27 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Priest,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Primate Joins Thousands Of Mourners At Priest's Funeral</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal Jozef Glemp told several thousand
mourners at a funeral service for a priest found in his rectory last
weekend that the clergyman had apparently been murdered.
   The body of Rev. Stefan Niedzielak, provost of the Powazki
cemetery, was found Saturday. He was buried at the cemetery
Thursday. Officials say he died of a broken neck, but have yet to
determine the circumstances of his death.
   ``He died a violent death,'' Glemp said Thursday in brief remarks
to the crowd in front of the Charles Borromeo Roman Catholic church
in northwestern Warsaw.
   Poles have been particularly sensitive to the safety of clergymen
since the 1984 murder of the Rev. Jerzy Popieluszko, a supporter of
the Solidarity trade union movement who was killed by security
police.
   Niedzielak, 74, maintained a shrine to Poles killed in the Soviet
Union and speakers at the service said he served as a chaplain to
soldiers in the underground Home Army during the World War II.
   Many elderly Poles attended the funeral. Some of the men wore
red-and-white armbands lettered with the initials of the underground
Home Army, which fought against the Germans during the war.
   One woman held up a banner decorated with red-and-white
carnations saying, ``To the chaplain of Independence.''
   Police blocked the road leading to the cemetery and dozens of
passengers in buses patiently waited for the two-hour service to
conclude.
   The Rev. Zdiszlaw Krol, chancellor of the Warsaw Curia, called
Niedzielak a ``great patriot.''
   Other speakers praised Niedzielak's role in preserving the memory
of those Poles who died at the hands of the Russians during World
War II.
   Several speakers referred to the circumstances surrounding the
priest's death.
   Wojciech Ziembinski, a friend of the dead priest, said: ``And
you, Father Stefan, did not fall off any chair.'' Some had suggested
he died in a fall from a chair.
   Krol dismissed robbery as a motive, saying Niedzielak kept no
valuables in his apartment, which was across from the church.
   The government said an investigation is continuing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890127-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 0317EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Truckers     01-27 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Truckers,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trucking Industry Hopes to Qualify More Trained Drivers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A truck industry group says it hopes to put
thousands of professionally trained new drivers on the highway under
a new certification program for driver-training schools aimed at
countering an impending shortage of drivers and weeding out the bad
institutions.
   The Professional Truck Driver Institute of Amrica announced
Thursday that it was certifying eight schools with facilities in 14
states to train drivers, and it hopes more schools will qualify.
   Prospective drivers pay up to $4,000 for six- to eight-week
courses that generally include two weeks in the classroom and the
rest of the time driving trucks on special roadways.
   Jim Johnston, an institute board member and president of the
Owner-Operators Independent Drivers Association, said the
certification program offers ``a good chance to get rid of some of
the bad apples'' among training schools.
   He said some of the more than 300 driver-training institutions
around the country rip off students and don't prepare them for the
road.
   Schools had to meet 107 standards, ranging from a minimum number
of hours of training to maintenance of up-to-date equipment.
   Institute president Edward E. Kynaston told a news conference
that about 50 schools applied for certification and even those that
got it had to upgrade their programs to qualify.
   The certifications, recommended by a three-member independent
panel that visited the schools, are good for 18 months. The first
graduates from the certified courses would be qualifying in a few
weeks, Kynaston said.
   The newly certified schools can train about 15,000 drivers a
year, he said. More than 300,000 new truck drivers hit the nation's
highways each year, with drivers currently numbering about 3 million.
   The schools are American Truck Driving School of Elm Mott, Texas;
Chicago Truck Driving School; Diesel Driving Academy of Shreveport,
La.; Crete Carrier Corp. of Lincoln, Neb.; United States Truck
Driving School of Wheat Ridge, Colo.; American Transportation
Education Centers of Crystal City, Mo.; Cummins Professional
Training Center of Indianapolis; and Commercial Training Services of
Portland, Ore.
   George Beaulieu, president of the American Truck Driving School,
said his institution trains about 5,000 drivers a year using more
than 200 tractor-trailer trucks on campuses in Texas and Michigan.
   He said more women, government retirees and recent immigrants are
applying to be truck drivers as the industry faces a shortage of
trained drivers.
   Joseph Passananti of the Chicago school, which trains about 750
drivers a year with 10 trucks, said truck drivers ``who used to be
the knights of the road'' have been suffering from a poor image in
recent years.
   But he said better equipment, better pay and better working
conditions, including sometimes telephones in the truck cab, are
making the job more attractive.
   Truck drivers' earnings range from $25,000 and $60,000 a year,
said Thomas J. Donohue, president of the American Trucking
Associations, Inc. He said tougher standards for drivers, increased
shipping demands and slower growth in the 25-35 age group, which is
the most likely group from which drivers come, are causing the
driver shortage.
   The Professional Truck Driver Institute is an organization set up
by the trucking industry in 1985 to promote driver training and
safety.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
