<FIRST>r a PM-PoliceShooting     01-27 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Police Shooting,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coroner Says Officer Killed By Shotgun Blast, Not Gunman's Pistol</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES O. CLIFFORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of two policemen killed in a shootout
with a transient who grabbed an officer's pistol was fatally wounded
by a shotgun blast, not the pistol, said a coroner's report that
apparently contradicted the police account.
   The report raised the possibility that the officer was caught in
crossfire during last Friday's shootout in which other police
officers, some armed with shotguns, killed the gunman.
   Thousands of police officers attended a memorial service Thursday
for the two slain officers, Gordon Silva, 39, and Gene Simpson, 45.
Afterward, police spokesman Officer Don Tietgens said Police Chief
Joseph McNamara would have no immediate comment on the coroner's
report.
   ``The chief thinks it is inappropriate to comment because of the
fact that we just buried fellow officers,'' he said. ``Until the
results of lab tests and ballistics tests are turned in and our own
investigations are complete, we will have no comment.''
   Police had reported that Silva and Simpson were both fatally shot
by Dale Randy Connors, who had wrestled away Simpson's .357-caliber
Magnum pistol during a brief struggle near a downtown doughnut shop.
Connors was later identified as a transient and petty criminal who
associated with the homeless.
   Simpson was shot in the head with his service revolver, but
Silva's death certificate conflicts with the initial police version
of how he was killed. Connors only carried the pistol during the
shootout and apparently did not have access to a shotgun.
   Silva's death certificate listed shotgun pellet wounds to the
abdomen as the cause of death, John Manok, chief investigator for
the Santa Clara County Coroner, said Thursday.
   He added that his office has not issued its complete report in
the case. ``We are looking at the middle of next week for that,''
Mank said.
   Two other wounds to Silva's legs were superficial, said Manok,
adding it could not be determined whether the superficial wounds
were from a pistol.
   Part of the shooting was filmed by Santa Clara University
students who were in the area taping a documentary for a class.
   The blurred, jumpy videotape's audio track recorded 26 shots in
3{ minutes, with 21 of those coming during the final 30-second
volley that killed Connors.
   The shooting began with a noontime call of a disturbance at
Winchell's Donut House in downtown San Jose, where Connors was
reportedly threatening people and went into the street to direct
traffic.
</TEXT>
