<FIRST>r w PM-TowerConfirmation     01-27 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tower Confirmation,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tower Expresses Doubts About SDI</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Confirmation Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Tower told senators it would be
``unrealistic'' to think Star Wars could shield everyone in the
country from a nuclear holocaust, an outlook that differs from
former President Reagan's optimism about the space-based missile
defense system.
   Cautioning that he didn't want to get ``out in front'' of
President Bush's statements on the Strategic Defense Initiative, the
defense secretary-designate said that SDI was part of an effort to
move nuclear strategy from an offensive to a defensive focus.
   But, he cautioned, ``it remains to be seen whether that is a
realistic objective.''
   On the second day of confirmation hearings Thursday before the
Senate Armed Services Committee, Tower also said he will be
impartial despite having received more than $1 million in consulting
fees from seven defense contractors.
   ``I intend to be very, very objective,'' the former Texas senator
told the panel he once chaired. ``There will always be people who
will be skeptical. I learned during the past two months that not
everybody loves me.''
   Tower made his remarks about SDI under questioning from Sen. Al
Gore Jr., D-Tenn., who said Tower's pessimism ``represents a view
markedly different from the public's perception of President
Reagan's advocacy of a perfect defensive umbrella.''
   Reagan launched the program five years ago and said it should be
aimed at building a ballistic missile defense (BMD) that would
protect Americans from Soviet nuclear attack.
   Bush said during last fall's campaign that he favored deployment
of a limited SDI system as soon as possible.
   Tower told the committee: ``To begin with, I don't believe that
we can devise a BMD umbrella that can protect the entire American
population from nuclear incineration. I think that's unrealistic.''
   Discussing his consulting work, Tower testified that over a
three-year period he received $1,028,777 in fees from defense
contractors, including such industry giants as Rockwell
International, Martin-Marietta and LTV.
   Other companies were British Aerospace, Hicks &amp; Associates,
Jeford-McManus International Inc., and Textron Inc.
   Tower said he broke his ties with defense companies on Dec. 1
last year, one day after learning from Bush's transition staff that
he was under serious consideration for the defense post.
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the committee, expressed his
concern about Tower's former ties, saying, ``the difficulty here is
not that you have worked for a contractor as a consultant, but a
number of them, five or six or seven of the major corporations.''
   ``If you were to recuse (not involve) yourself on all of them,
you couldn't be secretary of defense,'' he said.
   In his testimony, Tower also urged Congress to tighten
``revolving-door'' laws to prevent officials ``from profiting
unfairly, unethically or illegally or inordinately'' if they move
between Pentagon and industry jobs.
   But he cautioned Congress that it should write such laws
``carefully enough so that honest, hardworking people who might want
to engage in public service are not summarily proscribed'' from
working at the Pentagon.
   Under questioning from Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., about the Soviet
Union's military superiority, Tower acknowledged that ``at this
moment, they have the capability to prevail in an invasion of
western Europe.''
   Hearings on Tower's nomination resume on Tuesday when
conservative Paul Weyrich, chairman of Coalitions for America, and
William G. Phillips, president of the National Council for
Industrial Defense, are scheduled to testify against the nomination.
</TEXT>
