<FIRST>r w PM-Jackson-Thornburgh     01-27 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jackson-Thornburgh,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jackson Makes Recommendations to Head Civil Rights Division</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX11</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson broke bread with Attorney General
Dick Thornburgh and emerged saying he had great respect for his
integrity and for his commitment to enforcing civil rights laws.
   Jackson contrasted the Justice Department under Thornburgh, a
longtime member of the NAACP, to the department under former
President Reagan's earlier appointees that ``sometimes attempted to
sabotage'' civil rights by failing to enforce laws protecting
minorities.
   ``In some sense for the first time in eight years, the lights
have been turned back on in the Justice Department and hopefully the
dust will be cleared from the books,'' said Jackson.
   The civil rights activist said Thornburgh asked him during the
lunch Thursday to submit a list of people he would recommend to head
the Justice Department's civil rights division.
   He said he urged Thornburgh to appoint ``someone who is credible
and reputable with a commitment to fulfill the laws passed in 1965,
earned with the blood of modest people.''
   ``There must be a facing up to the fact that the jugular vein of
our democracy is justice,'' Jackson said.
   Jackson said that Thornburgh is committed to enforcing civil
rights law, unlike William Bradford Reynolds, who headed the
division under the Reagan administration.
   ``There is a considerable gap between the positions of Mr.
Reynolds and Attorney General Thornburgh and their life history and
their commitment to social justice,'' said Jackson, who was an
unsuccessful candidate for the Democratic presidential nomination
last year.
   ``I have happened to know Attorney General Thornburgh for some
time,'' Jackson told reporters. ``I have great regard for his
integrity, for his intelligence, and for his courage, and for his
commitment.''
   Thornburgh, standing next to Jackson at a news conference after
the lunch, said, ``This department is committed, as is the
president, to the full enforcement of the civil rights laws of the
United States and the full enjoyment of equal opportunity by all of
its citizens.
   ``We will differ, I am sure, from time to time, as to how that
can best be accomplished,'' the attorney general said.
   ``But I think it would be foolhardy not to sit down and counsel
together. The ideas that Rev. Jackson gave us today will get full
consideration and we hope to continue the discussion.''
   Jackson also said he urged Thornburgh to ask President Bush to
convene a White House conference on civil rights ``to take a
comprehensive look at reviving and renewing our quest for justice in
the country.''
   A senior Justice Department official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Thornburgh would relay Jackson's proposal to Bush.
   Jackson was accompanied by Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., Delegate
Jaime Fuster of Puerto Rico and chairman of the House Hispanic
Caucus, and several other civil rights leaders.
</TEXT>
