<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 0401EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Baker'sFirstDay     01-27 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baker's First Day,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Sticks to Formal Style at State</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James A. Baker III faced a major decision on
his first working day as Secretary of State _ deciding to evacuate
the handful of U.S. officials threatened by the spreading civil war
in Afghanistan.
   Baker remained out of the public eye at the agency on Thursday,
but the increased turmoil in Kabul required his immediate attention.
   The secretary's circumspect day stood in sharp contrast to the
last change of administration in 1981, when Secretary of State
Alexander Haig entered the building and boasted that President
Reagan had annointed him ``the vicar of American foreign policy.''
   A U.S. official, speaking on condition he not be named, said
Baker's predecessor, George Shultz, had decided to leave the
decision on whether to close the U.S. Embassy in Kabul to the new
administration. Baker moved the morning after taking his oath of
office, the official said.
   The decision to evacuate the U.S. employees came as the Soviets
continued to pull out troops that have been in the country since
1979 and as fighting has increased between the pro-Moscow government
and U.S.-backed rebels battling for control.
   Although a more formal swearing-in ceremony is scheduled for this
evening at the White House, Baker had been sworn in privately
Wednesday evening at the State Department, hours after he was
confirmed by the Senate as President Bush's chief adviser on foreign
policy.
   Baker, one of Bush's closest friends and the man who managed the
final months of his campaign for the White House, kept a low profile
during his first working day and no schedule was released about his
activities.
   Department spokesman Charles Redman declined to specify any of
Baker's plans for the day, except to say that he was ``getting
established, that's his first priority.''
   Redman noted that Baker had ``met with his top people.''
   Asked by a reporter to identify those people _ so that clues
might be drawn about those in line for top slots during the new
administration's overhaul of personnel _ Redman only smiled.
   The spokesman did say, however, that the new secretary planned to
accompany Bush on his first major foreign trip overseas, to Japan
and China next month.
   True to the former Treasury secretary's crisp and formal style,
Baker wore a suit and tie as he held early-morning meetings with top
aides in his formal office workspace, said one senior official who
met with him.
   Shultz had been known for striking a more informal tone, meeting
with aides in the cozy sitting room next to the office, doffing his
suit coat for a sweater and poking intermittently at the embers in
his fireplace.
   The new secretary also took a cue from Bush and emphasized high
standards in the first message he sent to U.S. diplomats and State
Department employees around the world.
   ``I join with President Bush in emphasizing that public service
should conform to the highest standards of ethical performance,''
Baker wrote in the message cabled to all State Department employees
around the globe. ``For me, ethics means not only abiding by the
letter of public service by also the spirit _ not only in what we
do, but how we do it.''
   Bush had stressed ethics during his campaign in an attempt to
neutralize the criticism aimed at the Reagan administration for its
ethical problems.
</TEXT>
