<DOCNO> AP890127-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 0728EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Hastings     01-27 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hastings,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Delaying Tactics Feared in Hastings Impeachment Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senators must decide whether to tie up the
floor for six weeks or more with the impeachment trial of District
Judge Alcee L. Hastings or sidetrack the proceedings into a
committee.
   Lawmakers expressed concern Thursday at a Senate Rules Committee
hearing that the case could drag out painfully and some said there
was a possibility it would be prolonged even more by defense
delaying tactics.
   The 52-year-old Miami judge, however, said he is entitled to have
the entire Senate hear the evidence that prompted the House on Aug.
3 to vote 413-3 in favor of a total of 17 articles of impeachment
against him.
   ``This is not an agriculture bill,'' Hastings told reporters
Thursday following the committee hearing. ``This is my office that
is at stake here.''
   The impeachment articles say Hastings conspired to obtain a
$150,000 payoff from two convicted racketeers in return for keeping
them out of prison.
   Hastings also is accused of lying during the 1983 trial in which
a jury acquitted him of the bribery conspiracy.
   The articles also say Hastings disclosed wiretap information in
an unrelated matter and thus scuttled a federal criminal
investigation.
   The Rules Committee must recommend by Wednesday whether the full
Senate should hear evidence against Hastings or delegate the task to
a committee.
   A committee was empaneled for the job two years ago, when the
Senate convicted District Judge Harry E. Claiborne following his
impeachment by the House. At the time, Claiborne was in prison for
tax evasion but attempting to keep his seat on the bench.
   Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, expressed concern that Hastings might
employ delaying tactics to foil any effort to strip him of his
$89,500-a-year job.
   ``How do we know that the Senate will not be subjected to the
same shenanigans that went on in the district court?'' Stevens asked.
   Conservative estimates put the length of the proceeding at six
weeks but there is wide skepticism about that forecast. ``I think it
would be longer than that,'' said Sen. Wendell Ford, D-Ky., the
committee chairman.
   In another development, Hastings' attorney, Terence J. Anderson,
demanded that the Senate provide taxpayers' funds to finance the
defense.
   ``The Constitution guarantees that a judge's compensation in
office may not be diminished,'' Anderson said. He acknowledged,
however, that government payment of the defense costs incurred in an
impeachment case would be unprecedented.
</TEXT>
