<DOCNO> AP890127-0040 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 0413EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-RevolvingDoor     01-27 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Revolving Door,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top Bush Aides Going Private</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of President Bush's high-ranking
transition aides are staying away from the federal government,
deciding instead to pursue careers in the private sector.
   In becoming consultants, lobbyists and public relations
executives, the aides are moving through the well-traveled revolving
door that separates government service from private business.
   Among those entering private business are Craig Fuller and Robert
Teeter, the co-directors of the Bush transition office, and Sheila
Tate, the transition spokeswoman.
   Teeter, a longtime political consultant, intends to start a new
firm, spending much of his time in Washington even though his family
will remain in Ann Arbor, Mich., according to his assistant, Mary
Lukens.
   Before he joined the Bush presidential campaign, Teeter ran a
political consulting firm in Detroit.
   Fuller, former chief of staff to Vice President Bush, will become
president of a lobbying firm headed by Anne Wexler, a former Carter
administration official, and Nancy Reynolds, who is a close friend
of former first lady Nancy Reagan.
   Fuller decided to go into private business after he lost out in a
power struggle with John Sununu to be the White House chief of staff.
   Mrs. Tate, Mrs. Reagan's former press secretary and a longtime
public relations executive, is going to work in public relations,
but she would not identify the company until the deal is completed.
   People who worked in government, such as Fuller, will be governed
by existing post-employment ethics laws. ``He is precluded from
lobbying the White House for a year, and you can bet he won't,''
said Mrs. Wexler.
   Fuller will be working on ``public strategies and corporate
communications,'' Mrs. Wexler said. Among the firm's clients are
American Airlines, the Motion Picture Association and Allied Corp.
   Like many others who worked in the Bush campaign and transition,
Mrs. Tate is not subject to the government's post-employment laws,
according to Jane Ley, an attorney with the Office of Government
Ethics.
   Fuller is perhaps the most prominent exception, based on his
service in the vice president's office. He is covered by rules that
impose a cooling-off period in which senior employees of an agency
who enter the private sector are barred from contacting officials of
that agency for a year, except for social affairs.
   There is also a lifetime ban that prohibits all executive branch
officials from lobbying on any issue in which they had a ``personal
and substantial'' involvement while in government.
   Another campaign operative choosing the private sector is Rich
Bond, 38, Bush's deputy campaign manager. Bond has started a
lobbying firm with Frank Donatelli, 39, a White House political
director under President Reagan.
   Donatelli, who also had served as assistant to Reagan for
intergovernmental affairs, said his motive for leaving government
was ``primarily financial.'' But he also expressed a desire to run
his own operation after spending five of the last eight years in
government.
   As a government official, Donatelli could earn no more than
$89,500.
   James Pfiffner, a George Mason University professor who has
examined the presidency and the federal government, said government
experience _ particularly a visible job _ can often enhance a
person's future earning potential.
   Those entering the private sector do so at a time that Bush has
stressed ethics in his administration.
   Bush, in the first days of his presidency, has vowed to press for
laws that clarify codes of conduct and ``protect the public
interest.''
   ``I support what he is doing ... I think it is great,'' said Mrs.
Tate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
