<FIRST>r a PM-Mother-Sex     01-27 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mother-Sex,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother Charged With Forcing Children Into Prostitution</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mother charged with forcing her
9-year-old son and 12-year-old daughter into prostitution with up to
80 adults may have found clients for them by advertising in
pornographic magazines, a prosecutor said.
   Katherine Ann Hubert, 29, of El Cerrito, who was arraigned
Thursday on 19 felony counts and was being held without bail, used
the money she collected for sex acts by her children to buy drugs,
officials said.
   Police were seeking the youngsters' grandmother, a 48-year-old
Concord woman who was not identified by authorities, on a warrant
charging her with pandering in the case.
   Hubert was arrested Tuesday after a guardian who has been caring
for the children told police they had been prostituted while the
family lived in Richmond in the San Francisco Bay area between 1986
and 1988, said police Lt. Ray Howard.
   The girl told investigators her mother forced her to have sex
with 60 men and the boy said he was forced to have sex with 20 women.
   ``We have reason to believe on some occasions there was physical
violence involved in some of these acts,'' Howard said.
   The children said Hubert gave them such drugs as cocaine,
methamphetamine, marijuana, sleeping pills and alcohol in an effort
to desensitize them to sex acts, Howard said.
   The children were removed from Hubert's care last May after an
allegation the girl had been molested.
   The mother is charged with 16 counts of forcing the children into
lewd and lascivious acts, two counts of pandering children for sex
and one count of supplying rock cocaine to her son.
   Hubert seemed nervous Thursday when she appeared before Bay
Municipal Judge Allen Norris, and said she could not afford to hire
an attorney. She was referred to the Public Defender's Office.
   The woman, who was being held at the Contra Costa County Jail in
Martinez, is scheduled to appear in court again Feb. 2.
   Hubert has no criminal record, according to Deputy District
Attorney Brandon Baum.
   Baum said he has prosecuted other child prostitution cases, but
said this case is unusual because of the ``business-like manner in
which the acts took place. ... It was not a haphazard type of
thing.''
   Hubert may have found clients by advertising in pornographic
magazines, he said.
   Baum said there were no signs the mother took any precautions to
protect her children's health or guard them from sexually
transmitted disease.
   The grandmother ``aided and abetted in making arrangements for
the acts to take place,'' Baum said. Most occurred at the family
home.
   ``There are still a lot of unanswered questions about the
grandmother ... her role here,'' Howard said.
   Officials believe the children's father was not involved in the
alleged prostitution and wasn't living with them at the time, the
lieutenant said.
   Shortly after the children were removed from their mother's care
last May, two other girls, ages 2 and 4, were taken from the home,
authorities said. Their relationship to Hubert was unclear.
</TEXT>
