<FIRST>r i PM-Pakistan-Soviets     01-27 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pakistan-Soviets,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shevardnadze Coming For Crucial Afghan Talks With Pakistanis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED AFTAB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze will travel to Pakistan next week for talks with the
country's leaders on a settlement of the Afghan problem, the
Pakistani government said today.
   A Foreign Ministry spokesman said Shevardnadze would arrive in
Islamabad Feb. 4 for a day of talks with President Ghulam Ishaq
Khan, Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto and Foreign Minister Sahabzada
Yaqub Khan.
   According to a U.N. brokered agreement signed last April, all
remaining Soviet troops are to leave Afghanistan by Feb. 15.
   The situation in Kabul, the Afghan capital, has been
deteriorating as the Soviet troops prepare for final withdrawal.
   Shevardnadze will be the highest ranking Soviet leader to visit
Pakistan in more than 20 years, since then-Soviet Prime Minister
Alexi Kosygin visited in the late 1960s.
   ``We hope our talks with the Soviet leader will pave the way for
a peaceful settlement, although the situation on the ground in
Afghanistan is depressing,'' said the spokesman, who cannot be named
under government rules.
   Western diplomats reported Thursday that hundreds of civilians
were killed Monday in a major bombardment by Soviet and Afghan
forces on a tunnel on the highway connecting Kabul to the Soviet
Union.
   U.S.- and Pakistan-backed Afghan rebels had blocked the crucial
road for the last several days, causing severe shortages of food and
fuel in Kabul and other major Afghan cities.
   Responding to the deteriorating security situation, U.S.
Secretary of State James A. Baker III on Thursday ordered the U.S.
Embassy in Kabul closed. Other Western embassies have advised their
nationals to leave Afghanistan immediately while commercial flights
are still operating.
   Senior Pakistani diplomats described the upcoming talks between
Shevardnadze and Pakistani leaders as ``crucial for preventing
further bloodshed in Afghanistan.''
   Direct talks earlier this month between Yuli Vorontsov, first
deputy Soviet foreign minister and ambassador to Kabul, and Pakistan
and Iran-based resistance groups deadlocked because the resistance
refused to include members of the present Marxist administration in
Kabul in a proposed consultative council that is to elect the future
interim government for Afghanistan.
   The resistance had insisted that only those officials of Afghan
leader Najib's administration who have not committed crimes against
the people during the 9-year civil war be included in the council.
   Vorontosov said the government should have the right to nominate
its representatives for the council.
   Pakistani officials said they hoped Shevardnadze would bring a
proposal to resolve the disagreement.
   ``Even a continuation of the deadlock will mean further bloodshed
when the Soviets leave Afghanistan,'' a senior Pakistani diplomat
said.
</TEXT>
