<FIRST>r a PM-NunsCast     01-27 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nuns Cast,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nine Nuns Picked for Cameo Roles in `Nunsense'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine singing, dancing and spoon-snapping nuns have
landed cameo roles in the hit musical ``Nunsense,'' and some are
hoping to make a habit of it to help lighten up their image.
   ``Hopefully if people see us this way they won't feel that nuns
are like when you had them in school,'' said Sister Mary Brigid, a
Carmelite who will be playing wooden spoons to an Irish jig the week
of Feb. 28. ``When I had them in school, I was afraid to talk to
them.''
   The nuns passed a talent audition with flying habits earlier this
month and were chosen for guest appearances in the spoof of convent
life.
   ``Nunsense'' has played in 30 American cities since its 1985
debut. It is now in its third season in Boston, where it has been a
hit among clergy.
   ``It made me proud to be a sister and left me with a warm
feeling,'' said Sister Cheryl Donahue, 37, a Franciscan who will
sing in the show with another nun next month.
   ``I'm not an actress type and I'm kind of shy so I don't know how
I'm going to get through it, but it'll be fun,'' Sister Donahue said.
   Sister Rena Foley, who was a professional dancer before becoming
a nun, became the first performing nun on Tuesday. She began in a
formal habit, but then took it off to reveal a spangled outfit for a
jazz number. Sister Foley will keep center stage until Sunday.
   Five other winning acts each will perform a number at the start
of the second act for one week, starting Tuesday.
   The normal ``Nunsense'' cast is five habit-clad actresses who
sing, clown and tapdance. The off-beat story involves five nuns who
stage a talent show to raise money to bury four of their sisters,
who have died of botulism and are being stashed temporarily in the
convent freezer.
   The show's producers have pledged to donate $2 from each ticket
to charities chosen by the nuns.
</TEXT>
