<FIRST>r i PM-Korea-Politics     01-27 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea-Politics,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chun's Ex-Intelligence Chief Charged With Corruption</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Chun Doo-hwan's
intelligence chief was charged with corruption today and taken to
prison after two days of questioning by criminal prosecutors,
officials said.
   Prosecutors said Chang Se-dong, ex-director of the Agency for
National Security Planning, formerly the Korean Central Intelligence
Agency, was charged with misusing official authority and other
offenses.
   The action came as part of government and parliamentary inquiries
into allegations of human rights abuses and corruption under the
authoritarian Chun government. Chang was the highest-ranking former
official of that government to be charged so far.
   The Agency for National Security Planning, the nation's main
foreign intelligence organization, played a major role in enforcing
Chun's tough rule and suppressing domestic opposition.
   Chang, an ex-general who was one of the most powerful men in the
nation under Chun, was whisked under guard to a prison outside Seoul
after formal warrants were issued. He had been held by prosecutors
since Wednesday for questioning.
   Prosecutors said Chang strongly denied any wrongdong, insisting
he merely followed presidential orders. He was head of Chun's
presidential security before serving as intelligence chief from 1985
to 1987.
   Chun, who took power with military backing in 1980, is in rural
exile at a remote Buddhist monastery. He apologized to the nation in
November for abuses under his rule and went into exile.
   The former president has denied any personal wrongdoing, but some
of his relatives and aides have been convicted or charged with
corruption.
   The charges filed against Chang were vague and relatively mild.
They included illegal construction of a guest house and illegally
using government office space.
   Opposition groups have been demanding the arrest of Chang and
several other former top Chun aides on human rights abuses. South
Korean press reports said prosecutors had difficulty finding hard
evidence to use against Chang.
   The opposition contends President Roh Tae-woo's government is not
making a sufficient effort to prosecute former Chun aides. Roh, a
former general and once close ally of Chun, is closely identified
with the ex-president in the eyes of many South Koreans.
   The inquiry into the Chun regime has dominated South Korean
politics for months and hampered the government's efforts to achieve
broad acceptance.
   On Thursday, Chun refused to accept an order from a National
Assembly special committee to testify on his role in the bloody
suppression of a 1980 uprising in the southern city of Kwangju in
which at least 200 people were killed.
   The opposition is trying to use the Kwangju incident and other
legacies of the authoritarian Chun government to weaken the Roh
government.
   Opposition parties demanded this week that Roh keep an election
promise to submit to a referendum on his rule. It is not clear if
Roh could win such a vote and he might be forced to hold elections
or step down if defeated.
   Chun stepped down last February at the end of a seven-year term
and was replaced by Roh.
</TEXT>
