<FIRST>r i PM-Hungary-Earthquake     01-27 0154</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary-Earthquake,0158</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moderate Earthquake Hits Hungary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A moderate earthquake shook southwestern
Hungary today, crumbling chimneys and cracking walls but causing no
injuries, the official MTI news agency reported.
   The quake, which struck at 4:55 a.m. and lasted seven minutes,
registered 4.5 on the Richter scale, the report said. Experts said
they expected more tremors in the quake-prone area.
   Some 40 minor quakes have been registered in the region, about 94
miles southwest of Budapest, since 1953. None have registered above
6.5 on the Richter scale, MTI said.
   On Thursday, the same area was hit by another earthquake that
registered 3.4 on the Richter scale.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. A quake of magnitude 4 can cause moderate damage in
populated areas, and a quake of magnitude 5 can cause considerable
damage.
</TEXT>
