<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--LincolnLand     01-27 0159</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Lincoln Land,0162</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farmland Owned By Abe Lincoln and His Father Sold at Foreclosure
Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MATTOON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A farmer's $98,500 bid won him farmland once
owned by Abraham Lincoln and his father near the Lincoln Log Cabin
State Historic Site.
   Ron Best beat two other bidders Thursday at a foreclosure sale
held in Mattoon, about 60 miles southeast of Springfield. Best's
purchase will be used to retire a mortgage signed by Raymond W.
Phipps of Springfield in August 1975.
   The unpaid principal and interest totaled $91,079. That amount
will continue to increase at 9 percent until the sale is finalized
in six months.
   Best said the 125-acre site will be used ``for farming and
farming only.''
   The auction had an old-fashioned flavor as several volunteers who
work at the restored Lincoln Log Cabin nearby showed up in period
costumes. Though the character of Thomas Lincoln, who actually
farmed the land, was represented, Abe Lincoln was not.
