<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 0601EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Pope-Criticism     01-27 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pope-Criticism,0564</SECOND>
<HEAD>Theologians Attack Pope's Stance On Birth Control</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roman Catholic theologians from
universities across Europe have attacked Pope John Paul II for his
continued opposition to artificial birth control.
   The criticism prompted the television network ZDF to interrupt
its regular news program Thursday evening and broadcast an editorial
saying: ``The pope should be careful to keep too many Catholics from
walking out on him.''
   Meanwhile in Rome, Lithuania's visiting cardinal said Thursday
that Communist authorities in his Soviet republic would welcome a
visit to the Catholic stronghold by the pope but Moscow continues to
oppose the idea.
   The theologians' German-language declaration complained that the
pope has linked the church's teachings on birth control too closely
to fundamental articles of faith such as the holiness of God.
   It said the link was made so strong that those who criticize the
church's ban on artificial birth control are accused of ``attacking
the fundamental pillars of Christian teaching.''
   The 170 university theology professors who signed the declaration
contended the 1968 Vatican encyclical regarding birth control did
not place an absolute ban on artificial forms of contraception.
   At the Vatican, spokesman Joaquin Navarro said: ``I think we are
talking of a local matter.''
   ``I can also say that some people who signed have withdrawn their
support of the document,'' he added, without providing names.
   The signers of the seven-page document, called the Cologne
Declaration, are from West Germany, the Netherlands, Austria and
Switzerland.
   The statement also focused on the pope's teachings, on disputes
over permission to teach Catholic theology and recent on nominations
to fill bishops' positions.
   ``We are witnesses of a theologically very questionable attempt
to overstep the papal jurisdictional and teaching competence, and to
make it unacceptably prevailing,'' it said.
   It was prompted in part by the pope's appointment last month of
Cardinal Joachim Meisner as archbishop of Cologne, one of the most
influential church posts in Europe. Some local church officials
thought Meisner too conservative.
   Hours after the document was released, West German bishops issued
a statement saying: ``The West German bishops conference decisively
rejects the numerous misrepresentations against Pope John Paul II.''
   Cardinal Vincentas Sladkevicius, in Rome for talks with the pope,
said he raised the issue of a papal visit to Lithuania in a meeting
this week in Moscow with Sergei Kuznetsov, head of the Soviet
department on Catholic affairs.
   ``At this time, the government of Moscow is very much against a
visit of the pope,'' Sladkevicius said.
   Sladkevicius said that Lithuania's Communist Party chief,
Algirdas Brazauskas, had indicated the local government favored a
papal visit.
   The cardinal said the Lithuanian government is ``still very
dependent on Moscow'' and could not clear the way for a papal visit
on its own.
   The Polish-born pontiff frequently has expressed the desire to
travel to the Soviet Union but insisted he would go only if
permitted to visit his flock nationwide.
   He has said that he has been refused permission at least twice to
visit Lithuania.
   Lithuania, an independent country before World War II, was
occupied by the Soviet Union in 1940 and has been viewed as a
stronghold of nationalism. Sladkevicius said about 80 percent of
Lithuania's 3.5 million people are Roman Catholics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890127-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 0606EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Panama-Press     01-27 0772</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama-Press,0797</SECOND>
<HEAD>Noriega Keeps Opposition Media Closed As Campaign Opens</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panama's opposition news media remain
shuttered nearly a year after being closed by Gen. Manuel Noriega,
and with a presidential campaign about to start, there is little
likelihood they will be allowed to reopen.
   The most important opposition newspaper, La Prensa, had a
circulation of 50,000 when Noriega's soldiers stopped its presses
last Feb. 25 and closed its doors.
   ``Even if they allowed us to reopen next month, we do not know if
we could start publishing right away,'' said Winston Robles,
director of the newspaper when it closed.
   ``There will be many technical problems,'' he said. ``We have not
been allowed to go inside the newspaper building since it was shut
down.''
   Also shut were the newspapers El Siglo, La Extra and Quiubo; the
radio stations Continente and Mundial; and Channel 5, a television
station owned by ousted president Eric Arturo Delvalle.
   All were charged with violating a press law protecting the
security of the state. An investigation is still going on and some
reporters were called in to testify last month.
   ``We are going to demand that the news media be allowed to
reopen,'' said Guillermo Ford, candidate for second vice president
on the united opposition ticket led by Guillermo Endara of the
Arnulfista Party and Ricardo Arias Calderon, candidate for the first
vice presidency.
   The presidential elections are scheduled for May 7; the
government is expected to name a candidate soon.
   The Interior Ministry said the issue of reopening the opposition
media is in the hands of the legal department. Other sources
referred all queries to the district attorney's office, which
declined to discuss the matter.
   Other media have to be very careful about what is put on the air
or published, including the independent newspaper La Estrella owned
by the Duque family, whose members have varied political leanings.
   A government decree establishes that television and radio
franchises can be canceled if the stations ``incite to the
disruption of public order, civil disobedience and the overthrow of
the state.'' Radio and television stations air the decree before and
after their news programs.
   In a speech Jan. 17, Noriega, commander of the Panama Defense
Forces and the country's de facto ruler, equated Panama's situation
to that of Nicaragua after the government there closed down an
opposition newspaper.
   He quoted approvingly an observation on censorship by the
Nicaraguan government that ended, ``the nation is at war, under
siege by the United States and by regional oligarchies.''
   The full text of the speech appeared across the top of page 1 in
La Estrella; in the text the quoted observation appeared in capital
letters.
   Noriega has survived more than a year of U.S. attempts to oust
him following an indictment in Florida on drug-related charges.
   When Delvalle tried to fire him, Noriega used his clout to have
Panama's congress dump Delvalle and install Manuel Solis Palma as
president.
   U.S. sanctions have compounded an economic crisis, but Noriega
has broken a general strike, crushed public demonstrations and
presented himself as the defender of Panamanian sovereignty,
claiming the United States wants him out so it can renege on the
Panama Canal treaties that call for U.S. forces to leave in the year
2000.
   Government candidates have the pages of three government-owned
newspapers at their disposal as well as time on a state-owned radio
and television station.
   Most of the newsprint held by La Prensa has been sold to La
Estrella to keep it from wasting in hot and humid Panama.
   ``If we are allowed to reopen, I am sure they would close us down
again within days,'' said Ruben Dario Carles, president of La
Prensa's board of directors. He was referring to past occasions when
the newspaper was closed down by the government.
   Robles and others, including news editor Alfredo (Wilfy) Jimenez
and reporters Migdalia Fuentes and Flor Quintero, were called by the
district attorney's office in December to testify.
   ``We were questioned about stories in which opposition leaders
criticized the government. The government claims by publishing the
stories, we were agreeing with them,'' Jimenez said.
   Jimenez and others tried to open a small daily late last year,
but approval for the publication is pending.
   ``The government must certify that each reporter is a bona fide
journalist,'' Jimenez said. ``Now the permits by the Board of Health
and other agencies such as the Commerce Ministry must also be
confirmed by the Interior Ministry.''
   ``We do not think the conditions exist for free elections without
opposition news media,'' Robles said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
