<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 0608EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-InfantDeaths     01-27 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Infant Deaths,0577</SECOND>
<HEAD>Autopsies Inconclusive On Deaths Of Three Quads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FOREST PARK, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities who initially suggested foul
play caused the simultaneous deaths of three of four quadruplets say
they're halting their investigation with few leads, and the
fatalities remain a mystery.
   Exhaustive medical tests failed to find a reason for the deaths
two weeks ago of 3-month-old Kia, Mia and DeAnthony Walker in this
Atlanta suburb, Clayton County Medical Examiner Joseph Burton said
Thursday.
   ``I'm not telling you it's a matter of black and white; it's
not,'' Burton said. ``The scales just tip away from the direction of
foul play at this time.''
   Police Maj. L. Dwayne Hobbs said the deaths remain suspicious and
the case will remain open, but inactive, unless new evidence turns
up.
   Burton said the cause would be listed as sudden unexplained death
in infancy, but he probably always will have ``haunting suspicions''
about the case. Such an occurrence is unheard of in medical circles,
the medical examiner said.
   The two girls and a boy were found dead early Jan. 13 when their
mother, Tonja L. Walker, checked her babies, who had been sleeping
together in a crib. The only child alive was DeAndrea.
   Doctors initially suspected meningitis as the cause of death, but
autopsies ruled that out, Burton said.
   There were no signs of strangulation or suffocation, he said.
   ``We tested for sedatives, tranquilizers, pesticides, arsenic,
strychnine, cocaine, marijuana, the whole shooting match,'' Burton
said. ``We tested blood, tissues, stomach contents.''
   Two infants had respiratory infections, Burton said. Experts
examining the base of one infant's brain found an unusual change in
a brain cell. That part of the brain controls breathing.
   The deaths fit the pattern of sudden infant death syndrome, an
unexplained illness that most often affects children less than a
year old, said Dr. Diane Rowley, an infant mortality epidemiologist
at the Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta. Infants 3 to 4 months
old are at the highest risk.
   The majority of such deaths occur between late November and
April, Ms. Rowley said. ``There's some question as to whether
something about the cold weather or infections contribute to the
deaths, but that really has not been solved.''
   Some researchers believe siblings are prone to the syndrome, and
studies have documented cases in which twins or siblings born in
separate births have died of it, Ms. Rowley said.
   However, she said the Walker case ``is very rare.''
   ``We're going to write the case up,'' Burton said. ``It'll be
submitted to various forensic pathology journals. When this occurs
again, and it will somewhere, it will let someone know that it's
happened before.''
   The tragedy was not the first to strike Mrs. Walker. In 1985,
prematurely born twins died in a hospital, police said.
   The Walker family is trying to cope with the infant's deaths and
the subsequent investigation, said Tonja Walker's mother, Mary
Walker.
   ``Police said `foul play.' They didn't say who (was the
suspect),'' Mary Walker said. ``The suspicion was on her (Tonja
Walker) as well.''
   She defended her daughter as a good mother who ``couldn't hurt a
fly.''
   ``Does he look like he's neglected?'' she said, holding DeAndrea
in the hallway of the Forest Park Police Department.
   She said the investigation would ``be with us forever. It's
something we'll always have to try to live down.''
</TEXT>
