<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Afghanistan     01-27 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Afghanistan,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan Closes Embassy In Afghanistan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan has decided to close its embassy in
Afghanistan and withdraw its diplomatic personnel because of
increasing tension in that country, the Foreign Ministry said today.
   The move follows a decision Thursday by the United States to
close its embassy in the Afghan capital of Kabul because of concern
over increased strife in the country as Soviet troops complete their
withdrawal.
   ``Because the situation in Afghanistan has become tense and
conditions in Kabul are likely to worsen, we have decided to
temporarily close the Japanese Embassy in Afghanistan and withdraw
the embassy staff from the country,'' the ministry said in a
statement.
   The three embassy personnel stationed in Kabul, including the
acting ambassador, would return to Japan at an undecided date, a
ministry spokesman said.
   The embassy has also confirmed the presence in Afghanistan of 13
non-diplomat Japanese who are in the country temporarily, and all
plan to leave as well, the spokesman said.
   The Soviet Union has pledged to withdraw its remaining troops
from Afghanistan by Feb. 15. The Soviet troops entered Afghanistan
in December 1979 to support the Marxist Afghan government in its
battle against Afghan guerrillas, backed by the United States and
Pakistan.
   The guerrillas have vowed to defeat the government following the
withdrawal of the Soviet troops.
   Japan has pledged $60 million in aid for an estimated 5 million
Afghan refugees who have fled from their homeland because of the
fighting.
</TEXT>
