<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 0634EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Anti-Semitism     01-27 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Anti-Semitism,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Anti-Semitic Acts Reach Five-Year High</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDIE GLAVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Jewish group suggested a rise in anti-Semitic
incidents last year could be attributed in part to developments in
the Middle East, the emergence of neo-Nazi skinheads, and the 50th
anniversary of Kristallnacht.
   A report released Thursday by the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai
B'rith said 1,281 anti-Semitic incidents were reported in the United
States and Puerto Rico in 1988, with vandalism up 19 percent and
harassment up 41 percent over 1987. The 1987 total was 1,018.
   Last year's figure was the highest of any of the past five years.
The number of incidents reached 1,422 in 1982, the highest in the 10
years the group has compiled the audit from reports by its regional
offices and law enforcement officials.
   Among the incidents cited in the survey were the spray-painting
of anti-Semitic and racist slogans at a Jewish high school in
Doraville, Ga.; the explosion of a pipe bomb on the grounds of a
Florida synagogue; and the arson of a synagogue in the New York City.
   Also mentioned in the report were desecrations of Jewish
cemeteries and 54 anti-Semitic incidents on 38 college campuses,
which included vandalism, threats, harassment and assault.
   The report cited a November attack against a Jewish university
student in New York City as being among the most brutal assaults. A
gang of youths allegedly shouted anti-Semitic epithets as they beat,
robbed and stabbed the 19-year-old, who survived.
   ``Isn't it ironic that in our lifetime we've conquered space and
even eradicated smallpox yet we have not developed a vaccine against
the virus of hate,'' said Abraham Foxman, national director of the
Anti-Defamation League.
   There were 117 incidents linked to Palestinian unrest in Israel's
West Bank and Gaza region. Foxman said he believes anti-Semites used
the situation to carry out acts of hatred ``under the guise of a
political conflict.''
   Another 41 incidents were linked to the rise of so-called
skinheads.
   The skinhead subculture emerged in London as early as the 1960s.
But segments of the movement took on Nazi overtones in 1985 and
since have been supported by and associated with white supremacist
groups.
   The league said more than 60 anti-Semitic incidents were sparked
by the observance of the 50th anniversary of Kristallnacht, the
night of violence against Jews in Germany and Austria that many
believe marked the beginning of the Holocaust.
   New York led the nation with 208 incidents, half of those in New
York City. California had 121, Florida 89 and New Jersey 67. There
were no incidents reported in 10 states.
   According to the survey, 124 people were arrested for
anti-Semitic acts in 1988, approximately 90 percent of whom were
under 21.
   It was a record year for harassment incidents against Jewish
institutions in the 10 years the survey has been taken. The group
reported 133 such cases, up about 10 percent from previous years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
