<HEAD>San Francisco Football Coach Resigns After Super Bowl Victory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTEREY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bill Walsh has resigned as coach of the
San Francisco 49ers after leading the National Football League team
to its third Super Bowl championship this decade.
   Walsh, 59, will stay on with the team as executive vice president
for football operations. The team's defensive coordinator, George
Seifert, was named to succeed him.
   ``It's an uplift to me to step aside on a most positive note,''
Walsh said Thursday at a news conference to announce his resignation
Wednesday. ``This is the way most coaches would like to leave the
game.''
   The 49ers beat the Cincinnati Bengals 20-16 in Miami on Sunday to
win the Super Bowl.
   Walsh, who has an overall record of 102-63-1, including playoff
games, joined the 49ers in 1979 after two years as head coach at
Stanford University.

