<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 0703EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a BC-Theater 1stLd-Writethru a0777 01-27 0899</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0777,0915</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Black and Blue,' A Musical Revue, Opens On Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 6 grafs with other reviews. No PMs planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You would think that in this barren Broadway
season, just about any song and dance celebration sporting music by
Ellington, Arlen, Armstrong, Handy and others would lift the spirits.
   But for much of the time, that's not the case with ``Black and
Blue,'' the new musical revue that opened Thursday at Broadway's
Minskoff Theater. It's an uneven production that contains flashes of
sass and expert tap dancing but too often settles for the routine.
   Responsibility for that predictability lies with Claudio Segovia
and Hector Orezzoli who are credited in the program with conceiving
and directing this new revue. The duo, creators of the hit ``Tango
Argentino,'' have staged ``Black and Blue'' with surprisingly little
style, something their earlier show had in abundance.
   The musical attempts to recreate the sizzle and snap of the
Cotton Club and Apollo revues that galvanized Harlem audiences in
1920s, '30s and '40s. ``Black and Blue'' might work better in a
nightclub setting. In the cavernous Minskoff, the lack of production
values are apparent, as is the perfunctory quality of Henry LeTang's
ensemble choreography which seems more Las Vegas glitz than Uptown
swagger.
   Excitement is confined mainly to a small group of terrific tap
dancers, mostly in solos, duets and trios. The tappers include such
veterans as Bunny Briggs, Jimmy Slyde, Ralph Brown and Lon Chaney as
well as a talented young hoofer named Savion Glover.
   Briggs, a little man with saucer eyes and an impish smile,
infuses his tap routines with a delicacy that is astonishing. He
embraces Ellington's ``In a Sentimental Mood,'' treating the song as
if it were a partner, and creates a joyousness that is hard to
resist.
   Slyde gets similar results with ``Stompin' at the Savoy,'' but
his style is smoother, slicker, more like a Fred Astaire routine.
And how many dancers can skate across the stage in taps?
   The best number in the show is another Ellington ditty, ``East
St. Louis Toodle-oo,'' with Brown and Chaney, two elder statesman of
tap, showing that age hasn't diminished their love of dance.
   Most of the singing falls to three formidable ladies _ Ruth
Brown, Linda Hopkins and Carrie Smith. Each of these women has her
moment, a showcase to strut her stuff, but often their talents are
not used to best advantage.
   Miss Brown tears up the place in ``St. Louis Blues'' and the
raunchy ``If I Can't Sell It, I'll Keep Sittin' on It,'' but then
seems uneasy in an overly contrived version of ``Body and Soul.''
   Miss Smith, with the deepest voice this side of Vaughan Monroe,
shines through two ill-conceived production numbers, one to ``I've
Got the Right to Sing the Blues.'' It places her on a huge silver
orb that rolls out on stage and then tilts backwards, subjecting the
audience to a bad case of vertigo. The second, ``Am I Blue,'' has
her perched on a swing high above the stage while the long train of
her dress billows to the floor.
   Miss Hopkins may have the most forceful of the three voices, but
she tends to diminish its power by going for the easy laugh and cute
gesture or phrasing. That cuteness mars songs such as ``Cry Like a
Baby,'' a raucous Big Maybelle Smith number.
   Segovia and Orezzoli also created the scenery, costumes and
lighting. Their settings are minimal, mostly curtains in various
shades of red, yellow, blue and gray, but they serve as backdrops
for the team's striking lighting designs.
   The lighting allows for the performers' shadows, sometimes
reaching to proscenium, to hover over the stage, or to be splashed
on the side walls of the theater. These dancing shadows spark ``I'm
Confessin' That I Love You,'' the one ensemble number that really
utilizes the performers, the stage and the production design.
   The fine orchestra, conducted by Leonard Oxley, is composed of
expert musicians, including Sir Roland Hanna as its principal piano
soloist.
   The best of the recent black musical revues _ the original
``Ain't Misbehavin''' and the off-Broadway hit ``One Mo' Time,'' for
example _ harnessed an energy that built throughout the entire
evening. ``Black and Bllue'' scatters its resources and could end
after just about any number in the second act. There's no emotional
payoff. Instead, you have to wait patiently for those marvelous tap
dancers to come on stage and take over the place.
   In other reviews:
   Howard Kissel in the Daily News said the show ``is in a class by
itself.'' `` `Black and Blue' is closer in spirit to other eras,''
he wrote. ``If you listen ... you hear a dignity, an elegance, a
worldliness that stands in great contrast to the aggressiveness and
desperation that underlie so much of our pop music.''
   In the New York Post, Clive Barnes called the show, ``downright
terrific. ... It has passion, finesse, fun and, above all, style.''
   But Frank Rich in The New York Times said the show was ``a weird,
at times diverting, crosscultural mishmash.''
   ``While bursting with talent worthy of the Cotton Club or the
Apollo or Birdland, `Black and Blue' looks like the bloated
nightclub floor shows that used to flourish in decadent Latin
American capitals just before dictatorships collapsed.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890127-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 0703EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Hudson     01-27 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Hudson,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>NAACP Director Dead at 102</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA METZLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   H. Claude Hudson, a national director of the
NAACP and longtime civil rights activist who once was jailed for his
efforts to end segregation, has died at age 102.
   Hudson, a dentist for 58 years, had been hospitalized since
Saturday with pneumonia. He died Thursday.
   Since 1953, he served on the national board of directors of the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, and had
devoted his life to ensuring equality for all people, friends said.
   ``He was one of our great freedom fighters,'' said Jose DeSosa,
state chairman of the NAACP. ``Dr. H. Claude Hudson has left his
footprints in the sand throughout the United States in his effort
and involvement in the NAACP.''
   Hudson was born April 19, 1886, the son of sharecropper parents
in Marksville, La., and came to Los Angeles in 1923, reportedly at
the urging of Louisiana law enforcement who felt he stirred up too
much trouble while president of the Shreveport, La., chapter of the
NAACP.
   ``At that time, being a member of the NAACP was tantamount to
being a member of the suicide club,'' said family spokeswoman Gisele
Hudson.
   He graduated from Wiley College in Texas, and from Howard
University Dental School in Washington, D.C. In 1931, he became the
first black to receive a law degree from Loyola University School of
Law, Mrs. Hudson said.
   It was at Howard that he developed a longstanding involvement
with the NAACP, which held its first convention at the university.
   While head of the Los Angeles NAACP chapter, Hudson was involved
in efforts to end segregation on county beaches. He and seven other
NAACP leaders briefly were jailed in 1925 after wading into the
ocean to test the policy at Manhattan Beach.
   They were fined $500 for violating the no-swimming ordinance
applying to blacks, but the case later was thrown out by the courts,
and the segregation policy abandoned, Mrs. Hudson said.
   He is survived by his wife, Lena, four children, and five
grandchildren.
   Services were scheduled for Feb. 2 in Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890127-0064 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 0620EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Afghanistan 2ndLd-Writethru   01-27 0817</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0491,0841</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds of Civilians Killed In Shelling Of Highway To Soviet Union</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with three grafs updating with Japan's closing of embassy
in Kabul. Picks up graf 3 pvs, `Western diplomats ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED AFTAB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet and Afghan forces shelled a
mountain tunnel on the highway connecting Kabul to the Soviet Union,
then wiped out villages to the south, killing hundreds of civilians,
Western diplomats said.
   As tensions escalated during the last phases of the Soviet troop
withdrawal, Secretary of State James A. Baker III on Thursday
ordered the U.S. Embassy in Kabul closed, citing increased turmoil
in the Afghan capital.
   Japan today also ordered its embassy closed in Kabul and its
diplomatic personnel to leave the country because of deteriorating
conditions.
   Western diplomats in Islamabad quoted reports from Kabul that
Soviet and Afghan forces had launched a major shelling attack on
both ends of the 10-mile Salang Tunnel in an effort to reopen the
crucial Salang Highway, which is carrying Red Army troops home from
Afghanistan.
   The diplomats, who spoke on condition of anonymity, quoted
witnesses as calling the attack a ``major atrocity.''
   A dispatch from Kabul received by one Western embassy quoted
reports of witnesses seeing ``Soviet tanks rolling over dead bodies
of victims'' along the highway, which runs for 250 miles between
Kabul and the Soviet border.
   The tunnel, part of the highway, cuts through the Hindu Kush
mountains about 60 miles north of the capital.
   ``After shelling the north and south ends of the Salang tunnel,
Soviet and Afghan artillery obliterated all dwellings and villages
south of the tunnel,'' the diplomats quoted the reports as saying.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman said,
``There are eyewitnesses who say no dwellings remain and hundreds of
civilians were killed.''
   The dispatch received by the Western embassy said the report of
all houses being destroyed came from three separate sources,
including a diplomat who defends the Afghan government.
   Afghan media and military officers had reported 377 guerrillas
were killed Tuesday along the Salang Highway, where the insurgents
fighting the Kabul government have attacked many food and fuel
convoys trying to reach the capital.
   Heavy snows also have blocked parts of the road, and Kabul has
suffered severe food and fuel shortages as the end of the Soviet
military withdrawal approaches.
   Moslem guerrillas, backed by the United States and Pakistan, have
fought tha Kabul government since a Communist coup in April 1978.
Soviet troops intevened in 1979 to fight the rebels. Last May, the
Red Army began withdrawing under a U.N.-mediated agreement and all
Soviet military forces are to be gone by Feb. 15.
   The diplomats attributed the brutal Soviet and Afghan attack
Monday to a desire to intimidate Ahmed Shah Masoud, generally
considered the most effective guerrilla commander in Afghanistan.
   Masoud controls the Panjshir Valley, through which the Salang
Highway runs.
   In Islamabad, the Pakistani government said today that Soviet
Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze would arrive next week for
talks on a settlement in Afghanistan.
   A Foreign Ministry spokesman said Shevardnadze would meet Feb. 4
with President Ghulam Ishaq Khan, Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto and
Foreign Minister Sahabzada Yaqub Khan. There was no immediate
confirmation from Moscow.
   Shevardnadze would be the highest ranking Soviet leader to visit
Pakistan in more than 20 years.
   In another development Thursday, the army tried to counter
charges it has dragged young men from their homes to fight Afghan
guerrillas by displaying what it said were volunteers _ solemn
teen-agers and men in their late 30s.
   As the Soviet military withdraws, Afghanistan's conscript army
desperately needs recruits. Although two years of army service is
mandatory, thousands of Afghans have deserted. Many young men have
fled the country either to avoid conscription or to join the
insurgents.
   Baker's decision to shut down the Kabul embassy came on his first
day at his new job.
   The U.S. diplomatic contingent in Kabul already had been reduced
to less than 10 officers and security guards. An official source in
Washington, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the pullout
would be carried out over several days.
   A growing list of countries are debating whether to do the same.
On Saturday, the West German Embassy became the first foreign
embassy to close.
   Besides the diplomatic group, fewer than 20 private U.S. citizens
remain in Afghanistan. Most Westerners are with the International
Aid Mission, a charitable organization that has operated in
Afghanistan for many years.
   The U.S. Embassy said Tuesday it sent a warning letter to
Americans that ``a critical point'' had come in the Kabul area,
increased instablity was likely, and they should leave while
commercial flights remained available.
   Only the Soviet airline Aeroflot and Ariana, the Afghan
government airline, still operate from Kabul. Aeroflot uses military
planes and Ariana flights are unpredictable, sometimes delayed or
canceled for lack of fuel.
</TEXT>
