<FIRST>r a PM-Kidnap-Murder     01-27 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kidnap-Murder,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Charged In Kidnap-Slaying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two people have been charged in the
kidnap-slaying of a warehouse supervisor who police say was abducted
at gunpoint by a former co-worker and shot to death despite the
$25,000 ransom paid by his wife.
   John Martini, 58, and Therese Afdahl, 30, were arrested late
Wednesday after they were spotted by police in nearby Fort Lee.
Martini is also wanted in Arizona where he is charged in the deaths
of two people last November.
   After picking up the ransom Tuesday night, Martini managed to
elude authorities who staked out the drop-off site, officials said.
   Martini and Ms. Afdahl were charged Thursday in the slaying of
Irving Flax, 58, who authorities say worked with Martini as a truck
driver about 20 years ago. Prosecutors say there may be more arrests.
   Martini, who is from Arizona, and Afdahl, a former resident of
Fairview, admitted the crime Thursday, according to today's editions
of the Star-Ledger of Newark.
   ``(Martini) has given a full sworn statement indicating he did
abduct Mr. Flax, hold him for ransom and shoot Mr. Flax three times
in the head, killing him,'' Dennis Calo, assistant prosecutor in
Bergen County, told the newspaper.
   Flax's body was found Tuesday morning in his car in a shopping
mall parking lot in Paramus.
   FBI agents trailing the kidnapper, who had picked up the ransom
in Flax's car, lost track of the auto after it crossed the Hudson
River into New York City.
   John C. McGinley, special agent in charge of the FBI's Newark
bureau, told a news conference that heavy traffic helped the driver
get away.
   ``There was a lot of evasive driving before we lost him,''
McGinley said. ``It looked as though he was looking for any signs of
our surveillance.''
   On Thursday, Superior Court Judge Charles R. DiGisi in Hackensack
ordered Martini held without bail because of the Arizona murder
warrant. Ms. Afdahl was ordered held on $500,000 cash bail.
   Bergen County Prosector John Holl said Martini turned up on
Flax's doorstep in Fair Lawn on Monday morning, and invited him to
go for a cup of coffee.
   The two got into Flax's car, where Martini pulled a gun, forcing
Flax into a rented car driven by Ms. Afdahl, Holl said.
   Holl said Flax was taken to an apartment rented by Martini and
Ms. Afdahl. Telephone calls were then made to Flax's wife,
instructing her to drop off the ransom at a restaurant parking lot.
The prosecutor refused to say how the details of the abduction were
obtained.
   Martini used Flax's car when he picked up the ransom and fled,
authorities said. Martini returned to the apartment and forced Flax
to drive his own car to the shopping mall, where Flax was fatally
shot about 11:30 p.m., Holl said.
   An anonymous tipster told police Martini was in New Jersey.
   Martini and Ms. Afdahl were arrested as they got into a taxi cab
carrying a duffel bag. Inside the bag, police found a .32-caliber
handgun and $29,000, including about $25,000 with serial numbers
matching the ransom money, Holl said.
</TEXT>
