<FIRST>r i PM-Spain-Arafat     01-27 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spain-Arafat,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arafat Meets With Common Market Representatives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN LINNEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO chief Yasser Arafat met today with three
European foreign ministers in his first official contact with the
Common Market, whose support he is seeking for an international
peace conference on the Middle East.
   The head of the Palestine Liberation Organization arrived in the
Spanish capital late Thursday from Iraq and went directly to a
four-hour working dinner with Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez.
   Neither made a statement following the meeting, but a Spanish
government spokesman said both men considered 1989 ``a very
important year'' in the search for peace in the Middle East.
   On Thursday, a senior PLO official said in Baghdad that Arafat
would urge the Spanish, French and Greek foreign ministers to
recognize the symbolic state of Palestine that was proclaimed Nov.
15 during a meeting of Palestinian leaders in Tunisia.
   Israel balks at the idea of an international peace conference
that would include countries not directly involved in the conflict
and refuses to recognize the PLO as an valid representative of the
Palestinian people.
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir let Foreign Minister
Francisco Fernandez Ordonez know during the Spanish official's trip
to Jerusalem earlier this month that Israel felt the EEC had no
business getting involved in a Middle East peace conference.
   Since an uprising against Israeli military presence in the
occupied territories began 13 months ago, 369 Palestinians and 15
Israelis have been killed.
   Fernandez Ordonez said the meeting between Arafat and the three
European leaders was being held ``to comply with a mandate by the
EEC Council of Foreign Ministers, which decided we should initiate
diplomatic action with the parties implicated in the Middle East
problem to promote the peace process.''
   During Spain's current six-month presidency of the Common Market,
Fernandez Ordonez heads the group's foreign ministers.
   The other two members of the EEC trio are Greek Foreign Minister
Carolos Papoulias and French Foreign Minister Roland Dumas. Greece
chaired the EEC for the final half of last year, and France will
take over for six months in July.
   The PLO leader was to have an audience with King Juan Carlos
later today and to hold a news conference before departing.

</TEXT>
