<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Winter Storm Hits Southwest; East to Dry Out</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A winter storm was moving through the Southwest today, where snow
advisories were posted in Arizona and New Mexico, and the
rain-drenched East Coast was to dry up a little.
   Rain, mountain snow and a few thunderstorms developed over
portions of Arizona late Thursday and were spreading slowly eastward.
   A snow advisory was in effect for the eastern mountains of
Arizona, and a winter storm watch was posted today for the central
highlands of New Mexico.
   Light rain fell along portions of the East Coast from the
Carolinas to southern New England on Thursday night, and scattered
light rain also developed in the Pacific Northwest as a cold front
approached.
   Scattered light snow or drizzle fell early this morning over
portions of Pennsylvania and central New York.
   The rest of the nation had generally clear skies, but strong
winds continued along the eastern slopes of the Rockies, where a
high wind warning remained in effect. Winds were to peak at 75 mph
in some areas.
   Temperatures this morning were in the upper 20s in the northern
Great Lakes. Readings across Minnesota were expected to slowly rise
through the nighttime hours. Temperatures were well below zero in
portions of the Rockies.
   Today's forecast called for showers and some thunderstorms over
much of Texas and southern Louisiana; southeast Arizona and much of
New Mexico, with snow over higher elevations. Rain was to be
scattered over northeast Florida, the Georgia coast and the northern
Pacific Coast. Snow was expected across northern New England, and
winds were expected to be strong and gusty along the eastern slope
of the northern Rockies.
   High temperatures were predicted in the teens and 20s in northern
Maine. Temperatures in the 30s and 40s were expected in the Pacific
Northwest; much of the Rockies; the Texas and Oklahoma panhandles;
eastern Montana; the upper Mississippi Valley; Iowa; the Great
Lakes; much of the Ohio Valley and the Atlantic Coast.
   Highs were to reach the 70s in portions of California, and into
the 80s over the central and southern Florida peninsula. The
remainder of the nation was to have highs in the 50s and 60s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 13
degrees below zero at Craig, Colo., to 72 degrees at Fort
Lauderdale, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 58 rain; Boston 41 cloudy; Buffalo 32 windy;
Charleston, S.C. 62 cloudy; Cincinnati 29 fair; Cleveland 32 partly
cloudy; Detroit 32 windy; Miami 69 partly cloudy; New York 43 partly
cloudy; Philadelphia 45 windy; Pittsburgh 32 cloudy; Portland, Maine
32 fair; Washington 50 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 27 fair; Chicago 27 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 43
partly cloudy; Denver 22 fair; Des Moines 29 fair; Indianapolis 30
fair; Kansas City 30 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 25 fair; Nashville
36 fair; New Orleans 62 foggy; St. Louis 32 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 40 fair; Anchorage -11 fair; Las Vegas 37
fair; Los Angeles 54 fair; Phoenix 50 partly cloudy; San Diego 53
partly cloudy; San Francisco 47 fair; Seattle 43 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 16 partly cloudy; Toronto 30 cloudy.
