<DOCNO> AP890127-0069 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 0709EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-US     01-27 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-US,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Defense Chief Expresses Regret Over Tower Remark</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the Defense Agency today expressed
regret over U.S. Defense Secretary-designate John Tower's call for
Japan to increase its military spending.
   ``As for Mr. Tower's comment that Japan can greatly increase its
defense efforts under the constitution, I have the feeling Mr. Tower
does not understand the Japanese people's feelings and
perspective,'' agency director-general Kichiro Tazawa told reporters.
   ``I regret that Mr. Tower went so far as to refer to our
constitution to push us to expand our defense spending,'' said
Tazawa.
   His comments were in response to statements Wednesday by Tower,
who is undergoing confirmation hearings before the U.S. Senate Armed
Services Committee.
   Tower, a former Republican senator from Texas, said the
constitution formulated during the post-war U.S. occupation of Japan
``severely restrained them from building a substantial military
force'' and was ``a lousy idea.''
   ``But I don't believe that constitution is so restraining that
they couldn't devote a substantially larger percentage (of spending)
to their defense,'' Tower said.
   The Japanese constitution, adopted in 1946, renounces war and
forbids the use of force in settling international disputes. But
Japan has been steadily building up its armed forces in recent years
in response to heavy pressure from the United States.
   Acting U.S. Defense Secretary William Taft on Thursday hailed
Japan's increased allotment for defense in its budget for the next
fiscal year.
   ``I commend the government of Japan for continuing to do what is
necessary to meet Japan's defense goals and to positively support
U.S. forces in Japan,'' he was quoted by Kyodo News Service as
saying. ``Given the continuing threat posed by Soviet forces in the
Pacific, growth in Japan's defense and cost-sharing efforts is fully
justified.''
   Japan's Cabinet this week approved a budget for fiscal 1989 that
includes $30.5 billion for defense spending, a 5.9 percent increase
over the previous year. The budget still must be passed by
Parliament.
   The proposed defense budget will amount to slightly more than 1
percent of Japan's gross national product _ the total value of goods
and services _ as it did in 1988 and 1987. The United States devotes
about 6 percent of its gross national product to military spending.
Washington's European allies spend about 3 or 4 percent on defense.
</TEXT>
