<DOCNO> AP890127-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 0715EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-India-Vietnam     01-27 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Vietnam,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnam: Cambodian Talks Will Go On Without Sihanouk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam's foreign minister today said
Cambodian peace talks in Indonesia would be held as scheduled
despite reports that Cambodian resistance leader Prince Norodom
Sihanouk will not attend.
   Nguyen Co Thatch compared the peace talks beginning Feb. 19 with
the final 15 minutes of a soccer match where everyone is ``trying to
score a point. If anyone misses the match, it is his
responsibility.''
   ``The match will continue, I only hope Prince Sihanouk will
change his stand,'' Thach told a news conference.
   Reports from China published in Indian newspapers today quoted
Sihanouk as saying he will not take part in the talks. Sihanouk
reportedly linked his decision to the rejection of his five-point
Cambodian peace plan by Hun Sen, premier of Cambodia's
Vietnam-backed government.
   ``The role of Prince Sihanouk is very important, but he cannot
decide everything,'' Thach said.
   Thach was in India along with Nguyen Van Linh, secretary-general
of Vietnam's Communist Party, who was the chief guest at India's
republic day celebrations on Thursday.
   Vietnamese troops invaded Camdobia in late 1978 and installed a
pro-Hanoi government in Phnom Penh. Vietnam says it will pull out
completely from Cambodia by the end of 1990 or perhaps sooner if a
political solution is reached.
   Hanoi says it now has 50,000 troops in Cambodia. But U.S.
diplomats in Bangkok put the figure at 80,000.
   The Vietnamese are fighting a coalition of three major Cambodian
resistance groups: the communist Khmer Rouge, the non-communist
Khmer People's National Liberation Front of former Cambodian Prime
Minister Son Sann and followers of Sihanouk.
   Armed strength of the resistance is generally estimated at about
47,000, with the Khmer Rouge as the strongest faction.
   The Vietnamese invaded Cambodia in 1978 to drive the Khmer Rouge
from power. From the 1975 takeover of the Khmer Rouge to its ouster,
it is estimated that about 2 million of Cambodia's 8 million people
died from Khmer Rouge executions, famine and civil unrest.
</TEXT>
