<FIRST>r i PM-China-Crime     01-27 0201</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Crime,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Executed 100 In Province This Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 100 people were executed in the first 20
days of the year in China's crime-ridden southern province of
Guangdong, a newspaper today quoted officials as saying.
   The number of death sentences given by courts during the period
doubled from the first 20 days of last year, Mai Chongkai, the
acting president of the provincial People's High Court, was quoted
as saying.
   The independent Hong Kong newspaper Ming Pao did not detail the
crimes committed by those given the death penalty, which in China
usually is carried out by a single bullet to the back of the head.
Earlier reports had said 10 robbers and murderers were executed Jan.
20 in the province.
   Zhou Tongping, vice president of the Guangdong court, was quoted
as saying incidents of serious crime in the province rose faster
than the national rate last year, although he did not give a
specific figure. Serious offenses such as murder and robbery
increased 66 percent nationwide in 1987.
   The report said the regional economic boom and influx of people
from other areas in China is a main reason for the province's high
crime rate.
</TEXT>
