<FIRST>r i PM-Iraq-UN     01-27 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iraq-UN,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Envoy Tours Cease-Fire Line</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. special envoy Jan Eliasson arrived in
the southern Iraqi port of Basra from Tehran today seeking to
breathe new life into stalled Iran-Iraq peace talks, officials
reported.
   Eliasson inspected cease-fire lines in the region and was
scheduled to fly by helicopter to Baghdad later for meetings with
senior Iraqi leaders, including Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz, U.N.
officials reported.
   Eliasson, Sweden's U.N. ambassador and Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar's special emissary, said before leaving Tehran:
``It is very important to create a new momentum to speed up the
trend of future peace talks.
   The negotiations began Aug. 25, five days after a U.N.-sponsored
cease-fire in the 8-year-old gulf war took effect.
   The talks ended in deadlock Nov. 11 after several sessions, with
both sides accusing the other of obstructing progress.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in
Cyprus, quoted Eliasson as saying at Tehran airport that his four
days of talks with Prime Minister Hussein Musavi, Foreign Minister
Ali Akbar Velayati and other officials were ``very useful and
fruitful.'' He did not elaborate.
   IRNA quoted Musavi as blaming Iraq for the deadlock by refusing
to withdraw from territory Iran claims the Iraqis captured in a
series of offensives before the cease-fire took effect AUg. 20.
   Before leaving Iran, Eliasson inspected the southern front line
with Deputy Foreign Minister Mohammad Javad Lavasani, IRNA said.
   The agency said the envoy was taken to an area where Tehran said
the Iraqis captured several hundred Iranians after the Aug. 20
cease-fire. Eliasson also saw three burning oil wells which the
Iranians said the Iraqis set afire.
   ``After this visit, effective steps will be taken by the
secretary-general to secure the release of our prisoners and in
helping us extinguish these oil wells,'' IRNA quoted Lavasani as
saying. He did not elaborate.
   U.N. officials in Baghdad said Eliasson's talks were aimed at
exploring possibilities for resuming the peace talks. No date has
been set for a new round of negotiations.
   The talks have stalled on Iraq's insistence that a 1975 treaty
drawing the southern border between the two countries down the
middle of the Shatt-Al-Arab waterway is invalid.
   Before the treaty, the border ran down the eastern, Iranian bank
which meant the Iraqis effectively controlled the waterway, their
main outlet to the Persian Gulf. Iran insists the treaty is still in
force.
</TEXT>
