<HEAD>Former Vaudevillian, Star of 50s Children's Show, Suffers Heart Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vaudeville veteran Pinky Lee, who was the
host of one of the earliest children's television shows, was
hospitalized today after suffering a mild heart attack while
performing in the musical ``Sugar Babies.''
   Lee was listed in serious but stable condition at St. Francis
Medical Center.
   ``He is pain-free and resting comfortably,'' medical center
spokeswoman Theresa Staley said Thursday. Lee apparently has no
history of heart trouble.
   The hospital did not have Lee's age. Published reports put it
between 62 and 89.
   The entertainer collapsed backstage Wednesday while starring in a
one-night performance of the vaudeville-style musical before a
Peoria Civic Center Crowd of about 2,000 people.
   ``It was almost a full house,'' said center spokesman Denny
Johnston. Few in the crowd were aware of Lee's heart attack, said
booking manager Debbie Ritschel.
   Lee, whose real name is Pincus Leff, was star of the daily NBC-TV
children's program, `The Pinky Lee Show,'' broadcast in 1950 and
1954-56.
