<FIRST>r a PM-TinyHorse 1stLd-Writethru a0414 01-27 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tiny Horse, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0414,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pony's a Pet, Council Says in Dropping Eviction Fight</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, ``From New ...' to uppercase New York.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THOUSAND OAKS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city finally has admitted
Ragtime the tiny stallion is really a horse of a different color.
   After a two-year fight to evict the pint-sized steed that Patty
Fairchild keeps as a pet, the City Council voted Wednesday night to
give up.
   Larry Horner, mayor of this Los Angeles suburb, said the decision
came partly because council members were afraid of being saddled
with an international reputation as animal-haters.
   ``From New York to Nova Scotia, people are telling us to stop
picking on the horse,'' Horner said. ``It's time to just bow out of
it.''
   Ragtime, who stands just 27 inches tall, is a special breed of
miniature horse. He sleeps in the yard but has the run of the house,
and is even allowed to sit on the sofa and watch television.
   ``I'm just relieved,'' Mrs. Fairchild said after the vote. ``It
just feels good that it's all over.''
   Some people in Mrs. Fairchild's upper middle-class neighborhood
say a horse is a horse, no matter how small, and they spurred the
city on in its efforts to kick Ragtime out in keeping with an
ordinance barring farm animals from residential neighborhoods.
   The issue has been in court twice, most recently two weeks ago,
when Ventura Municipal Judge John Hunter decided Ragtime was a pet,
and so couldn't be corralled out of the neighborhood under the
anti-livestock law.
   But neigh-sayers like the Oakbrook Village Homeowners Association
say they haven't given up yet. The association will raise its
anti-Ragtime arguments once again in a lawsuit scheduled for a
hearing Feb. 27.
</TEXT>
