<FIRST>r a PM-PolygamistClan     01-27 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Polygamist Clan,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Sentences Trio To Maximum Terms For Lawman's Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEG McENTEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge called three polygamist clan
members ``anarchists'' before sentencing them to up to 15 years in
prison for killing a state corrections officer in a shootout at the
family's farm.
   ``These defendants acted as anarchists, and this court has been
presented with no credible information that, if given the
opportunity, they would not again engage in anarchism and armed
conflict,'' Third District Judge Michael R. Murphy said Thursday.
   Murphy sentenced clan leader Addam Swapp, 27, and brother-in-law
John Timothy Singer, 22, to one to 15 years in Utah State Prison for
manslaughter. Swapp's brother, Jonathan, 21, received a one-year
jail term for negligent homicide.
   The sentences were pronounced two days before the first
anniversary of the Jan. 28 shootout at the clan's Marion compound
that ended a standoff with state and federal officers. Corrections
Lt. Fred House was killed and Addam Swapp was wounded in the
exchange.
   The impasse had begun 13 days earlier, when Addam Swapp bombed a
Mormon chapel near the farm.
   House was killed during an attempt to arrest the Swapp brothers
as they walked outside the main farmhouse, where nine children were
closeted with the six adults.
   House was directing his reluctant dog toward the pair when he was
struck by a bullet that nicked the armhole of his armored vest.
   Singer admitted firing the fatal shot, but insisted he was only
shooting at the dogs. Jonathan Swapp also acknowledged firing his
rifle but said he shot only to keep his wounded brother from being
hit again.
   Addam Swapp, wounded in the wrist and chest, did not fire.
   Swapp has said the chapel bombing was a divinely inspired act
intended to trigger the resurrection of his late father-in-law, John
Singer, and the collapse of a ``wicked and corrupt'' church and
state.
   Singer, the clan's patriarch, was killed in 1979 by police during
an arrest attempt at the same farm. Addam Swapp is married to two of
Singer's daughters.
   John Timothy Singer's attorney, Fred Metos, said his client would
appeal the conviction and sentence.
   Last May, the Swapps, Singer and his mother, clan matriarch
Vickie Singer, were convicted of federal offenses in the bombing and
standoff.
   In September, U.S. District Judge Bruce Jenkins sentenced Addam
Swapp to 15 years, John Timothy Singer and Jonathan Swapp to 10
years and Vickie Singer to five years imprisonment.
</TEXT>
