<SECOND>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0532,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top Official Reported Talking To Pro-PLO Representative</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 5th pvs, ``The talks...'' to UPDATE with
denial from Husseini associate. Pickup 6th pvs, ``Husseini is...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An aide to Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin held
secret meetings with a jailed Palestinian linked to the PLO, and
reports of their talks were passed to top PLO officials abroad, an
Israeli newspaper said today.
   Defense Ministry spokesman Eitan Haber declined to comment on the
report. Israel officially bans contacts with the Palestine
Liberation Organization, which it views as a terrorist group. It
bitterly protested a U.S. decision last month to open a dialogue
with the group.
   The daily Maariv reported that the meetings took place between
Shmuel Goren, Israel's policy coordinator for the West Bank, and
Faisal Husseini, whom the Defense Ministry confirmed Thursday would
be freed.
   Maariv said the two discussed possible peace initiatives,
including Rabin's plan to hold elections in the occupied West Bank
and Gaza Strip and to grant Arabs limited autonomy following a
three-to-six-month cease-fire in the Palestinian uprising.
   The talks reportedly took place during the past week in the Kfar
Yonah prison in central Israel, where Husseini has been serving a
six-month term without trial.
   Fuad Al-Aref, an associate of Husseini, said he talked with the
jailed Palestinian leader Monday and asked about rumors that he had
been meeting a Defense Ministry official. ``He denied it,'' Al-Aref
said.
   Husseini is due to be freed from prison Sunday, and the daily
Hadashot reported he would meet with Rabin after his release to
discuss the defense minister's plans for peace negotiations.
   Rabin's proposal, made public early this week, has been rejected
by the PLO and several local Palestinian leaders.
   Similar proposals in the past have been turned down by the PLO as
inconsistent with demands for an independent Palestinian nation.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir also dismissed Rabin's plan, saying
the government has not yet formulated its official peace proposals.
   The Israeli government, led by the right-wing Shamir, has come
under increasing pressure to introduce some kind of peace initiative
as the 13-month-old Palestinian uprising continues.
   The United States and European countries have criticized Israel's
harsh efforts to end the uprising _ which has taken 369 Palestinian
and 15 Israeli lives _ and have moved closer to PLO chief Yasser
Arafat since he recognized Israel and renounced terrorism last month.
   In the occupied territories today, soldiers shot and wounded four
Palestinians in sporadic clashes with stone-throwing protesters. The
army confirmed one injury in the West Bank city of Tulkarem.
   Hadashot said that after Husseini's release, he was to see Rabin
and then test feelings in the occupied territories toward peace
proposals.
   Husseini, the son of a Palestinian hero who fell leading a battle
against the Israelis on Jerusalem's outskirts in 1948, has ties to
the PLO and Hamas, the fundamentalist Moslem movement that opposes
any compromise with Israel.
   He was jailed in April 1987 and has spent most of the last 21
months under administrative detention _ emergency regulations that
do not require specific charges or a trial. He was last arrested in
April. Israel has accused him of being a ringleader of Palestinian
resistance.
   Husseini heads an institute in East Jerusalem, the Arabic Studies
Center, that researches Palestinian history and culture.
</TEXT>
