<HEAD>Kemp Pledges to Improve Housing Conditions</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Top 6 grafs new with Kemp quotes; picks up 3rd graf pvs, Kemp
has.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Confirmation Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jack Kemp, seeking confirmation as secretary of
housing and urban development, told Congress today that homelessness
``is a national tragedy of appalling proportions'' and pledged to
improve housing conditions in America.
   In remarks prepared for his confirmation hearing before the
Senate Banking Committee, Kemp said ``we can help recapture the
American dream for our distressed inner cities and those who live in
poverty and despair.''
   On the problem of homelessness, Kemp noted that President Bush is
committed to full funding of the McKinney Act, which Congress passed
last year to provide emergency shelter.
   But he said ``funding, while necessary, is not sufficient. We
need to work together to provide a complete and effective safety
net'' with both public and private efforts.
   ``It is a national tragedy of appalling proportions that there
are Americans without basic shelter and human services,'' Kemp said.
   He also pledged to work toward making home ownership possible for
people in public housing, to press for urban enterprise zones to
encourage inner city development, and to seek a national housing
policy that will make housing more affordable for poor and young
families.
   Kemp has shored up support among his former colleagues on Capitol
Hill, personally meeting or speaking by telephone with each member
of the panel since Bush nominated him. Most have said they
unequivocally support his confirmation, and a few declined to make
their decision public before the hearing, but none said they oppose
him.
   ``I think it was one of the best appointments the new president
made,'' said Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, a conservative ally. ``I'm
sure he's going to be confirmed.''
   Gramm said he hoped to question Kemp about the possibility of
expanding nationwide a pilot program begun two weeks ago in Dallas
that makes vacant HUD houses available to families with incomes as
low as $15,000 a year.
   Sen. Jim Sasser, Budget Committee chairman and member of the
subcommittee on housing who supports Kemp's confirmation, wants to
know what direction Kemp plans to take on several rental subsidy
programs due to expire soon.
   In notes prepared for today's session, the Tennessee Democrat
said that by ``not addressing this situation head on it seems that
we are making a policy choice to increase the number of homeless.''
   He also intended to query the nominee about proposals to impose
user fees on federal home loans. Sasser said such fees would
increase interest rates on home mortgages, drive more people from
the housing market, contribute to stress on the rental market and
further increase homelessness. He also said the idea is ``contrary
to an explicit provision that the committee put in the 1987 Housing
and Community Development Act.''
   Others said they wanted to know his thoughts about rural housing
problems and energy efficiency in public housing.
</TEXT>
