<FIRST>r a PM-GuardianHusband     01-27 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Guardian Husband,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Wants Comatose Wife to Undergo Abortion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man has asked a court to appoint him the
guardian of his comatose wife so he can authorize an abortion in an
attempt to help her recover.
   Martin Klein, 34, of Upper Brookville, said in papers filed
Thursday in state Supreme Court that doctors told him his wife,
Nancy, 32, would have a better chance of recovery if the pregnancy
were terminated.
   Supreme Court Justice John Burke signed an order which requires
North Shore University Hospital in Manhasset, the state attorney
general and the Nassau County district attorney to show why Klein
should not be appointed guardian.
   Legal experts say the case is unusual.
   ``It is a very complicated, sensitive medical and ethical
question,'' said Andrew Schepard, a family law professor at Hofstra
University Law School. ``On the one hand the mother has a shot at
life, and on the other hand this is considered a viable fetus, and
who gets to decide? It is going to require complex medical
testimony.''
   Mrs. Klein, who is 16 weeks pregnant, has been in a coma and on a
respirator since being injured in a car accident Dec. 12.
   Dr. Joseph Smith of the Albert Einstein College of Medicine
backed Klein with a letter to the court that said, ``I believe with
a degree of medical certainty that Mrs. Klein's pregnancy presents a
serious threat to her life.''
   Klein, who said he visits his wife almost every day, said his
wife's mother, Ann Zusselman, and other family members support his
request.
   A hospital spokeswoman, Carol Hauptman, declined to comment,
saying the hospital had not been served with the court order.
   The Kleins have a 3-year-old daughter.
</TEXT>
