<SECOND>PM-BRF--Escapee Captured,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inmate Who Threw Down Crutches To Escape Is Captured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DULUTH, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An inmate who escaped from a sheriff's
deputy after throwing down his crutches outside a hospital and
sprinting away has been recaptured, authorities said.
   Dennis John Hannuksela, who is awaiting trial on murder charges,
was arrested Thursday in a car in West Duluth, said Sheriff's Deputy
Charles Berquist.
   Authorities were acting on a tip when they apprehended
Hannuksela, Berquist said. Hannuksela escaped Wednesday.
   Two other occupants of the car were questioned and charges are
possible, Berquist said. He was unsure whether additional charges
would be filed against Hannuksela.
   Hannuksela, 29, had used crutches during his entire six-month
stay in jail. He had one foot in a splint when he ran for freedom
outside the Northland Medical Center. He had not been handcuffed
because of his condition.
   Sgt. Tom Person, a supervisor at the jail, has said Hannuksela's
injury was not faked and speculated that the prisoner,
``anticipating his escape, punched up his adrenaline to the point
that he could run like crazy.''
