<FIRST>r w PM-FlowerDisease     01-27 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flower Disease,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Private Company Will Seek to Develop Agent to Control Plant Disease</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private company will seek to develop
commercially a first-of-its-kind biological agent for the control of
disease in major floral crops, the Agriculture Department said today.
   The commercial development will be handled by the W. R. Grace &amp;
Co., which has a research center in Columbia, Md.
   R. Dean Plowman, administrator of USDA's Agricultural Research
Service, said the biocontrol agent is based on a naturally occurring
fungus that attacks other harmful soil-borne fungi that cause
disease in floral crops.
   Tests at the agency's Beltsville, Md., laboratories _ just 15
miles from the W. R. Grace &amp; Co. facility _ showed that the agent
suppressed disease on a number of major floral crops, including
zinnias, snapdragons, chrysanthemums and poinsettias.
   Plowman said the agent was first isolated by a USDA scientist at
the Beltsville research center.
   Grace intends to evaluate the agent and then market the first
commercial product for use against fungus disease of greenhouse
crops, said Francois P. Van Remoortere, president of the company's
research division.
   The USDA and Grace signed a research agreement under a 1986 law
that authorizes increased cooperation between private companies and
individual federal research laboratories. The law encourages the
movement of federally developed technology into the marketplace.
</TEXT>
