<HEAD>Precede BEIRUT, Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Iranian President Criticizes Bush; Hopes Fade for Release of Hostages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Iranian president's comments on
hostages. No pickup. ADDS byline. ^By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's president today criticized
President Bush for saying that Washington would appreciate help in
gaining the release of the nine Americans held hostage in Lebanon,
Tehran radio reported.
   Also today, hopes faded that two Britons held hostage in Lebanon
would be freed soon. A radio station said the expected release was
``mere speculation.''
   Apparently interpreting Bush's statements to mean that release of
the hostages was a pre-condition for resuming ties with Iran,
President Ali Khamenei said, ``In setting conditions for resumption
of ties, the American president should know that we, not they, have
conditions to set.''
   ``We have always said that ties with America can only be resumed
when America revises its arrogant attitude,'' Khamenei added.
   ``It was America which expressed interest in resuming ties with
Iran; Iran does not need America,'' the radio reported him as
saying. The report was monitored in Nicosia.
   Bush said in his inaugural address that the United States would
cooperate with any country that could help release the American
hostages in Lebanon.
   He did not mention Iran by name, but his remarks were seen as a
call for Iran to help free the hostages with the promise of better
relations.
   Ties between the United States and Iran were severed soon after
the 1979 Islamic revolution, when militant Iranian students took
over the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and held 52 Americans hostage for
444 days.
   Fifteen foreigners, including the nine Americans, are believed
held hostage in west Beirut by pro-Iranian factions. The hostage
held longest is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for
The Associated Press. He was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   Reports in Beirut the last three days spoke of a release by
Saturday of John McCarthy, a journalist, and Brian Keenan, a teacher
who holds Irish and British citizenship.
   A British Embassy spokesman had said the purpose of Ambassador
Allan Ramsey's visit Thursday to Moslem west Beirut was to check the
reports.
   However, embassy spokesman Antoine Haddad told The Associated
Press today: ``We still have no hard information.'' He would not
comment further.
   The Voice of the Nation radio station, based in Moslem west
Beirut, said today: ``Reports of an imminent hostage release
appeared to be mere speculation based on rumors.''
   McCarthy, 31, a producer for the London-based Worldwide
Television News agency, was kidnapped April 17, 1986, as he drove to
the airport for a flight home. Keenan, 38, was kidnapped six days
earlier as he walked to the American University of Beirut.
   No group has claimed the abduction of McCarthy or Keenan.
</TEXT>
