<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 1106EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Czechoslovakia 1stLd-Writethru   01-27 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czechoslovakia, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0546,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czechoslovakia To Reduce Its Troops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Czechoslovakia announced today it
will cut its armed forces by 12,000 soldiers and reduce its army
budget 15 percent in the next two years.
   The move followed announcements of troop cuts by East Germany and
Hungary and of defense spending reductions in Poland.
   All four nations acted after the Soviet Union announced Dec. 7 it
will reduce its forces by 500,000 men by 1991. This will include
withdrawing 50,000 troops and 5,000 tanks from East Germany, Hungary
and Czechoslovakia.
   The Warsaw Pact troop cuts have been billed by the Kremlin as a
boost to new East-West talks opening in March on reducing
conventional arms and weapons across Europe.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev has also made clear that
slashing military spending will free more funds for sorely needed
modernization of Soviet bloc economies.
   Czechoslovakia's official CTK news agency announced the plans a
day after Soviet army Gen. Alexei Lizichev disclosed that Prague
planned to follow East Germany and Hungary into force reductions.
   The general gave no details, but CTK said later that it was
decided to cut the armed forces by 12,000 men over the next two
years and reduce military spending by 15 percent.
   According to data from NATO, Czechoslovakia has 145,000 soldiers.
   The Council for the Defense of the State also decided that
Czechoslovakia will scrap 85O tanks, 165 armored vehicles and 51
fighter planes, CTK reported.
   Military maneuvers and tactical exercises will be reduced by 5O
percent, and the number of reserve soldiers will be cut by 15,000
over the two-year period, CTK said.
   The measures are intended to ``increasingly emphasize the
defensive nature'' of the Czechoslovak army and represent ``gradual
implementation of the initiative to create a zone of trust,
coooperation and good neighborly relations between NATO and Warsaw
Treaty states,'' CTK said.
   It said Czechoslovakia is prepared to continue troop reductions
if NATO adopts similar measures.
   In the interview Thursday on CTK's Czech-language news service,
Lizichev also was quoted as saying the Soviets will eliminate 10,000
tanks and 800 planes worldwide as part of its announced reduction of
the Red Army.
   Hungary announced this year it will cut military spending by 17
percent, and Poland also has announced plans to reduce its military
outlay.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
