<FIRST>u a PM-Bundy 1stLd-Writethru a0493 01-27 0716</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bundy, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0493,0733</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor's Office Releases Tape Bundy Made Before Execution</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `A sheriff's ...' with 4 grafs to UPDATE with
Colorado comment, Utah search underway; Picks up 5th graf, `Meanwhile,
officials ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT KALLESTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forty-five minutes before his execution
in Florida's electric chair, Ted Bundy described in precise detail
the location of two victims' bodies in Utah and Colorado,
authorities have disclosed.
   In a final interview with Florida State Prison Warden Thomas
Barton, the serial killer gave directions to investigators trying to
find the two bodies, but denied involvement in any murders in four
other states. The interview was made public by Florida Gov. Bob
Martinez' office late Thursday.
   Bundy said he didn't know the identity of his Utah victim, but he
believed the Colorado victim was Denise Oliverson, 24, last seen
riding her bicycle in April 1975 near her home in Grand Junction.
   Sgt. Greg Kuhn of the Grand Junction, Colo., Police Department
said today officials will listen to the Bundy tape and talk to the
investigator who interviewed Bundy. Police probably will decide
Monday whether to search for Oliverson's body, he said.
   In Utah today, about 20 searchers with metal detectors focused on
an area 10 miles southeast of Price, in central Utah, in a search
for one Bundy victim, said Carbon County Chief Deputy Jerry Cowan.
   The searchers had metal detectors to pick up any jewelry that
might have been worn by the victim. But Cowan said there is heavy
snow cover and the prospects for success were uncertain.
   ``The snow covers the sagebrush, resembling mounds, but we're at
least going to make an effort,'' he said.
   Meanwhile, officials in Washington state expressed anguish over
another legacy left by the serial killer: a request that his ashes
be scattered over the Washington Cascades.
   ``Personally, I'm kind of offended by the whole thing,'' said
Dale Potter, a spokesman for the Mount Baker-Snoqualmie National
Forest. ``I expect the hiking community and many other people who
use the national forest land would be somewhat offended by the
thought of it.''
   However, Potter said there are no regulations to prohibit Bundy's
ashes from being scattered over the mountains, where the bodies of
some of his victims were found.
   In Bundy's five-minute interview with Barton, conducted at 6:15
a.m. Tuesday, he used a map to point out the sites where he had left
the two victims in Utah and Colorado. Bundy was executed shortly
after 7 a.m.
   His memory of the Utah victim was especially vivid as he
pinpointed a dirt road between Price and Green River.
   ``About 200 yards in on the dirt road ... and to the left, maybe
50 yards, there's the remains of a young woman who disappeared from
Brigham Young University in June of 1975,'' Bundy said.
   Bundy had been suspected in the death of Susan Curtis, 15, who
was attending a youth conference at Brigham Young University when
she disappeared in June 1975, according to The Salt Lake Tribune.
   Bundy, 42, said the Colorado victim was dropped in a river.
   ``I believe the date was in April 1975,'' Bundy said. ``The young
woman's body would have been placed in the Colorado River five miles
west of Grand Junction. It was not buried.''
   ``That's all the ones that I can help you with,'' Bundy said.
``The ones that I know about. No missing ones outstanding that we
haven't talked about.''
   In response to further questions, Bundy specifically denied
killing anyone in Illinois, New Jersey, Vermont or Texas.
   ``Okay, that's all we've got,'' Barton said. ``Okay, Ted. Thank
you.''
   Bundy quietly answered, ``You're welcome.''
   Bundy was executed for the February 1978 rape-murder of
12-year-old Kimberly Leach of Lake City, Fla. In the days prior to
his execution, Bundy confessed to 23 murders. Investigators believe
he may be linked to as many as 100 deaths beginning in 1969.
   A Washington state investigator who interviewed Bundy before the
execution said Thursday that he ran out of time before he could ask
the killer about two Oregon women who disappeared in 1973.
   Robert Keppel, chief criminal investigator for the Washington
attorney general's office, said he was unable to inquire about the
disappearances of Rita Lorraine Jolly and Vicki Lynn Hollar.
</TEXT>
