<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
has decided to turn down an invitation to visit Afghanistan and
observe the final phase of the Soviet troop withdrawal, U.N.
officials said today.
   The officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said there was
no point in the U.N. chief visiting at this time, before what is
widely assumed will be the fall of the Soviet-backed Kabul
government to U.S.-backed Afghan rebels.
   But they said Perez de Cueller has not informed Afghanistan he
will not be coming and that the invitation is still officially under
consideration.
   Officials said Afghan President Najib recently invited the U.N.
chief to visit, partly in the hope that his presence would prevent
more bloodshed.
   Under a U.N.-mediated agreement, all Soviet troops are to
withdraw by Feb. 15, and heavy fighting has been reported between
the soldiers and the rebels.
