<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 1202EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-LaRoucheCharges 1stLd-Writethru a0570 01-27 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-LaRouche Charges, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0570,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>In Light of Virginia Convictions, Government Drops Boston Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT to three sted two associates.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT W. TROTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal prosecutors dropped conspiracy and fraud
charges against Lyndon H. LaRouche Jr. today, as the political
extremist was sentenced in Virginia in connection with $30 million
in defaulted loans.
   All charges were dropped against LaRouche and three associates,
but the Justice Department said it will not drop charges against
defendants in the case who are fugitives.
   LaRouche was sentenced in the Virginia case to 15 years in prison
for scheming to defraud federal tax collectors and deliberately
failing to repay more than $30 million in loans from his political
supporters.
   The U.S. Attorney's office had vowed to pursue the Boston case
regardless of the verdict in U.S. District Court in Alexandria, Va.,
but the stiff sentence he faced convinced officials that justice has
been served.
   ``In short, the interests of the United States and effective law
enforcement having thus been served from the point of view of both
deterrence and punishment, it is the government's view that further
prosecution is not warranted given the resources such prosecution
would demand, and the relatively slight benefits likely to flow
there from,'' according to a document filed today.
   LaRouche, who has run for president four times, is known for his
extreme views _ including support of an AIDS quarantine and often
vitriolic anti-Soviet rhetoric.
   The complex Boston case, which ended in a mistrial last May,
included allegations of government infiltration of LaRouche groups
purportedly involving the FBI, CIA, Oliver North and other
government operatives. A retrial was scheduled to begin Feb. 22.
   LaRouche, six aides and five political organizations were charged
with conspiring to obstruct a federal grand jury investigation into
allegations that Larouche's 1984 presidential campaign raised more
than $2 million through credit card and loan fraud.
   LaRouche was charged with one count of conspiracy for allegedly
ordering supporters to destroy records and refuse to cooperate with
investigators. All the aides and organizations also were charged
with conspiracy, and four of the groups were charged with fraud.
Three more defendants are fugitives.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
