<HEAD>Guild Ratifies New Two-Year Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new two-year contract between The Associated
Press and the Wire Service Guild has been ratified by a vote of 348
to 127, the union announced Friday.
   The contract covers 1,400 people, including the news service's
domestic reporting and editing staff. It is retroactive to Dec. 1,
1988, when accord was reached, and extends through Nov. 30, 1990.
   The contract provides for a 4 percent increase in the top-scale
salary minimums for newspeople of $27 a week to $695 weekly in the
first year of the contract, and a 3.6 percent increase of $25 a week
in the second year, to $720 weekly.
