<FIRST>r a PM-Steinberg     01-27 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steinberg,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Steinberg Jury Rehears Testimony on Nussbaum's Condition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors deliberating the child murder case against
disbarred lawyer Joel Steinberg have asked for fresh clothing,
hinting that a verdict might not come quickly.
   The request came after the jury, which began its fifth day of
deliberations today, asked Thursday to rehear testimony on the
physical condition of Steinberg's abused companion, Hedda Nussbaum.
Defense lawyers accuse her of the November 1987 killing of
6-year-old Lisa Steinberg.
   The Manhattan state Supreme Court jury asked if it could use the
doctor's testimony and a videotape of Ms. Nussbaum to assess her
condition and capabilities at the time of the child's death. Justice
Harold Rothwax said it could.
   They retired Thursday at 8 p.m. without reaching a verdict and
resumed deliberations at 10:20 a.m. today.
   But before quitting for the day, the sequestered jurors, who
began deliberating Monday, asked for fresh clothing to be sent to
them from their homes, an indication they were perhaps still a long
way from a verdict.
   Steinberg, 47, is charged in the fatal beating of Lisa, whom he
illegally obtained at birth from an unwed Long Island teen-ager. The
child was removed comatose from Steinberg and Ms. Nussbaum's
apartment Nov. 2, 1987, and died of a brain injury three days later.
   Ms. Nussbaum, 46, testified against him in exchange for limited
immunity from prosecution. Steinberg's lawyers charge it was Ms.
Nussbaum who fatally beat the girl. Prosecutors at first charged
her, along with Steinberg, but later said she was too physically and
emotionally disabled to have harmed the child.
   The jury Thursday asked to rehear testimony of Dr. Neil Spiegel,
an emergency room doctor at Bellevue Hospital who examined Ms.
Nussbaum after her arrest on Nov. 3, 1987, and found her
``chronically debilitated, malnourished, wasted,'' and described
numerous bruises, cuts and broken bones.
   The judge has told the jury it may not use Ms. Nussbaum's
condition to conclude that because Steinberg allegedly beat her, he
therefore beat Lisa.
   Rothwax has told the jury that it must unanimously acquit
Steinberg of murder before considering lesser charges of
first-degree manslaughter, second-degree manslaughter and criminally
negligent homicide.
</TEXT>
