<HEAD>Rebels Blow Up Colombia's Biggest Oil Pipeline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist rebels blew up part of Colombia's
biggest oil pipeline and forced it to close, the state oil company
Ecopetrol said Friday.
   It was the first time the pipeline, in northwestern Colombia, was
attacked this year. Rebels have blown up parts of the pipeline 67
times since it was built three years ago.
   The pipeline, which was attacked Wednesday, will be shut through
Saturday, the company said.
   The pipeline takes oil 500 miles from the Canon Limon field along
the Venezuela border to the Caribbean port of Covenas. It pumps
about 220,000 barrels a day.
