<FIRST>u w PM-Reagan-Speaking 1stLd-Writethru a0559 01-27 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Reagan-Speaking, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0559,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Sees No Wrong in Reagan's Million Dollar Book Deal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout with Bush quotes, details of lecture deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said today he found nothing
unseemly about former President Reagan signing a multi-million
contract to write his memoirs.
   Bush was asked at a news conference whether, in light of the
stress the new president has put this week on ethics in government,
he felt Reagan was ``cashing in'' on his presidency.
   Reagan reportedly will receive $5 million for his memoirs and a
book of speeches from Simon &amp; Schuster. In addition, a partner in
the Washington Speakers Bureau has a ``handshake agreement'' to
represent Reagan and his wife, Nancy, as their exclusive lecture
agents.
   One industry source, speaking on condition he not be identified,
said it would be reasonable to assume the former president could
command $40,000 for a speech.
   Asked about the book deal, Bush said, ``I don't call it cashing
in. I suspect every president has written his memoirs and gotten
money for it. ... I don't think it's ever been challenged.''
   Bush did not address the question of lecture fees for Reagan.
   Bernie Swain, a partner in the speakers bureau, said he was in
the process of signing Reagan up.
   ``I have a handshake agreement. That is all I am working on right
now,'' he said.
   Swain said the terms of the agreement with the Reagans had not
been settled.
   He said most of the former president's speaking engagements would
be in the West, at least for the present. The Reagans now live in
Los Angeles.
   Don Walker, president of the Harr Walker Agency in New York, said
his firm represent several speakers who get fees in the $40,000
range. But generally that amount is paid for speeches which require
travel.
   The Walker agency's clients include former Secretary of Defense
Caspar Weinberger, former President Ford and former Secretary of
State Henry Kissinger, among others.
   Swain said his firm had received requests in the past to arrange
speeches by Reagan while he was in office, but had referred all such
requests to the White House.
   He said Maureen Reagan, the president's daughter, and former
White House Chief of Staff Kenneth Duberstein had also been added to
the bureau's roster of speakers this week.
</TEXT>
