<FIRST>u w PM-US-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru a0465 01-27 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0465,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says Embassy Closed to Protect American Lives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: Top 7 grafs new with Bush comments, picks up 5th graf, The
U.S. diplomat. ^By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said today that a lot of
uncertainty exists about the civil warfare in Afghanistan in the
wake of the Soviet troop withdrawal and that the U.S. Embassy there
was closed to protect American lives.
   Bush, in a wide-ranging news conference in the White House
briefing room, was asked about Secretary of State James A. Baker
III's decision to evacuate the fewer than 10 diplomats and security
guards left in the U.S. Afghan outpost. All travel by American
civilians to the war-torn country had already been banned.
   The aim of the U.S. diplomatic pullout is to make sure no
Americans are exposed to the strife that is expected to intensify
when the last Soviet troops depart. All 50,000 are supposed to leave
the country by Feb. 15.
   Bush said he did not discuss the turmoil in Afghanistan in a
conversation with Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev last week, but
that he was convinced the Soviets would continue their withdrawal.
   Bush went on to say that he believed there is ``uncertainty about
what follows,'' and that he hoped the United States would play a
``catalytic role for helping bring about stability'' in the future.
   ``I think there's a lot of uncertainty. There's enough
uncertainty that the secretary of state was taking prudent action in
this regard,'' Bush said. ``It is a prudent policy to protect a
handful of American lives.''
   Afghan guerrillas, armed by the United States and Pakistan, are
fighting to wrest control of the country from government forces
backed by the Soviets. The drive by the Mujahedeen rebels for Kabul
and a deteriorating situation in that capital threatened to expose
the Americans to the cross-fire.
   The U.S. diplomatic contingent was gradually reduced over the
years, and the country has been without a full-time American
ambassador since Adolph Dubs was killed by Afghan forces a decade
ago.
   The Red Army's departure, under the Geneva accords signed last
April, will remove a stabilizing influence on the Kabul government.
The guerrillas, meanwhile, are likely to redouble their offensive
against government forces no longer backed by Soviet troops.
   Apart from the small contingent of about 10 diplomats and guards,
there are fewer than 20 U.S. citizens in Afghanistan. They have been
encouraged to leave, and the State Department has urged Americans
not to travel to the country.
   On Wednesday, the mayor of Kabul said the capital had a
three-month supply of food and fuel in case of a guerrilla siege.
Soviet soldiers handed out emergency rations. Soviet cargo planes
began flying loads of flour and fuel to Kabul on Saturday.
   The Reagan administration, in its final days, pondered whether to
abandon the embassy or to leave the decision to its successors. A
U.S. official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said it finally
was left up to Baker and he decided to close the embassy on his
first day of the job.
   Earlier, Charles E. Redman, the State Department spokesman,
quoted reports from Kabul that Soviet and Afghan artillery attacks
had obliterated a number of villages south of the Salang Tunnel,
through which Soviet troops are departing the country.
   ``There are eyewitnesses who say no dwellings remain and hundreds
of civilians were killed,'' Redman said. He said no U.S. embassy
personnel were in the devastated area.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890127-0115 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 1236EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-BushGoesSlow 1stLd-Writethru a0428 01-27 0701</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush Goes Slow, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0428,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: China-Bound President Cautious Still On Soviets
And Mideast</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Inserts 2 grafs after 5th graf bgng: Bush and ..., to UPDATE
with Bush news conference. Edits to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's trip to China next month
underscores the importance of American relations with the world's
largest country, and although the two have no overriding problems,
Bush has some serious issues to discuss with the Chinese.
   One is the joint effort the United States and China are making to
promote reconciliation between South Korea and North Korea. Another
is the growing improvement in relations between China and the Soviet
Union.
   Bush's trip will be the first visit to Beijing by a U.S. chief
executive in nearly five years. President Reagan visited the Chinese
capital in April 1984.
   But while Bush looks to the Far East, stopping lso in Japan for
Emperor Hirohito's funeral and in South Korea, two other regions
where problems are far more pressing have been consigned at least
for now to the back burner.
   Bush and his top foreign policy advisers, Secretary of State
James A. Baker III and Brent Scowcroft, the national security
adviser, are taking their time about the Soviet Union and the Middle
East.
   ``Let's take our time now,'' Bush told reporters today. ``Let's
take a look at where we stand.''
   He said he did not think after a long talk on the telephone with
Soviet Preisdent Mikhail S. Gorbachev that the Soviets consider his
reflective stance ``foot-dragging.''
   Baker, who is inexperienced in both areas, told the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee during his confirmation hearing that he
wanted to ``review the bidding'' in U.S.-Soviet negotiations to
reduce long-range nuclear weapons.
   Baker also said the United States should avoid ``a headlong
rush'' to provide Moscow with loans and credits, which are
traditionally a useful tool in improving relations.
   Scowcroft has more experience in foreign policy matters, but he
too is taking a very cautious approach in dealing with Moscow. He
worries that Gorbachev's peace offensive may have as one of its main
goals ``making trouble within the alliance'' of Western nations. He
is suspicious that Gorbachev's motivation is to buy time to reform
the Soviet economy _ which is a lot different from approaching
Gorbachev primarily as a world leader trying to ease East-West
tensions.
   ``I think the Cold War is not over,'' Scowcroft said in a recent
assessment of the superpower relationship.
   While Bush has not insisted on concessions from Moscow before
ascending the summit with Gorbachev, the White House spokesman,
Marlin Fitzwater, said Thursday they would meet only ``when the time
is right.''
   It's a bit early to make sweeping judgments, but the indications
are a slowdown in the reconciliation promoted by President Reagan
and Secretary of State George P. Shultz after Gorbachev's rise to
power in the Kremlin in March 1985.
   There is a similar go-slow attitude developing toward the
Arab-Israeli conflict in the Middle East, which drew serious
attention from the Reagan administration toward the end but hardly
the concentration trained on Moscow.
   Reagan and Shultz, in their final days, broke a 13-year embargo
and opened U.S. talks with the Palestine Liberation Organization.
Shultz made five trips to the Middle East in 1988, and while neither
the Arabs nor Israelis agreed to negotiations, Shultz left office
optimistic about the future.
   ``There is more diplomatic fluidity now and opportunity there
than there's been in some time,'' he told reporters on his final
trip, to Vienna, last week.
   Baker, on the other hand, emphasized that ``we ought to all be
realistic about the prospects for achieving a breakthrough.'' He
also told the Senate committee ``there is no more intractable
problem facing us.''
   Baker was cool about the dialogue with the PLO, suggesting it
would be continued only if it proved useful. And he ruled out a
Palestinian state, which the Reagan administration also opposed.
That appears to eliminate an option that has ardent Arab support and
could make it more difficult to entice Arab nations into any U.S.
scenario for the Middle East.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Barry Schweid is head of the AP's State
Department staff.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
