<DOCNO> AP890127-0118 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 1243EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Bush-Press     01-27 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Press,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Loose in First News Conference</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the first news conference of his presidency,
George Bush today engaged in an upbeat, at times jocular
give-and-take with reporters, interjecting his own ideas on the
format.
   Although Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater announced the surprise
news conference would run for 15 or 20 minutes, the president stood
before the White House press corps for about 45 minutes, apparently
comfortable fielding questions on a wide variety of topics.
   Bush's appearance was not scheduled and produced scrambling by
camera crews, reporters and photographers when it was announced on
15 minutes' notice.
   At one point, he interupted the questioning to ask about the
customary practice of allowing for follow-up questions by each
reporter after the president answers the initial question.
   In an exchange that produced much laughter, Bush stopped after a
question on the minimum wage and said, ``Wait, let me ask you to
stop the proceedings.''
   He turned to Fitzwater and said nodding to the assembled
reporters, ``Don't take it out of their time.''
   ``What would be the fair and noble way to handle follow-up
questions as we do these things? Would it be good to have them or
not have them?'' he asked.
   Some reporters replied that follow-ups are needed when the
president doesn't fully answer a question.
   ``You mean my first answer is less than precise,'' Bush said to
chuckles.
   He then noted with a gesture toward the reporters lined up along
the side of the room that with the seated journalists _ who tend to
be called on first _ getting two questions, ``the standees have
gotten no time at all.''
</TEXT>
