<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--AlcoholBan     01-27 0152</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Alcohol Ban,0156</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alcohol Ban in Czechoslavakia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities plan to ban sale of
alcoholic drinks at sports events and other public gatherings to
combat alcoholism, an official report said Friday.
   The ban will be included in a law expected to be adopted in
March, an official of the city's largest anti-drug research center
said.
   ``This law has been discussed ever since the late 1970s, but each
time there was somebody who didn't like it,'' the official said on
condition of anonymity.
   The ban will include sale of alcoholic beverages at cultural
events and dances, according to the official CTK news agency's
broadcast Friday.
   Authorities are also considering a ban on public smoking on
trains and sale of tobacco products to youngsters under 16, CTK said.
   Czechoslovakia, a country of 15.5 million, has 51,313 officially
registered alcoholics, an increase of 26 percent in seven years, the
agency said.
</TEXT>
