<FIRST>u w PM-Iran-Contra 2ndLd-Writethru a0616 01-27 0705</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Contra, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0616,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Hears Arguments on Presidential Subpoenas</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs pvs 13th graf, If the, with 4 grafs on officials saying
trial won't be blocked by secrecy problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge in the Iran-Contra case said today he
has the authority to compel President Bush and former President
Reagan to testify at the trial of fired National Security Council
aide Oliver North.
   U.S. District Judge Gerhard Gesell made the comment at a hearing
where the government argued that North's subpoenas served last month
for the testimony of Bush and Reagan should be quashed.
   Gesell said that if it becomes necessary to have the testimony of
either man at North's trial, it would be sought only as ``a last
resort.''
   ``As far as the power of the court to require testimony'' of
Reagan or Bush, ``I do not think there is any ... question,'' said
Gesell. He added that he thought the court's authority in such
situations is ``indisputable. ... The court has the power.''
   Gesell said such authority must be ``exercised with great
deference to the office of the president'' and should not be used
``except as a last resort if there is no other way to resolve the
issue.''
   Gesell didn't rule on the government's motion to quash the
subpoenas.
   Washington attorney Larry Simms, who sat in the spectator section
of the courtroom, acknowledged to reporters after the hearing that
he is representing Reagan.
   Simms said former Justice Department official Theodore Olson is
the lead attorney representing the former president.
   Meanwhile, Gesell said he had denied the request of independent
counsel Lawrence Walsh for a subpoena to get spiral notebooks in
which North recorded his daily activities when he was at the NSC.
   North invoked his Fifth Amendment privilege against
self-incrimination in trying to avoid turning over the notebooks.
Gesell did not explain his denial.
   Walsh and Gesell are proceeding as though North will go on trial
next Tuesday, although those plans could be thrown off by an
interagency intelligence group in the Bush administration.
   The group, whose work led to the Jan. 13 dismissal of conspiracy
and theft charges against North, has been reviewing classified
documents that North's lawyers and prosecutors plan to present at
trial in connection with the 12 criminal charges that remain against
him.
   Two administration officials said today, however, that secrecy
problems would not block the trial.
   The interagency task force had identified some documents that
might pose problems if Gesell allowed their disclosure in open court
by the defense. A lot would depend, however, on Gesell's rulings
from the bench during the trial on the relevancy and admissability
of the documents, said the officials, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Government secrecy specialists who are familiar with the
documents did not expect the sensitive material to be admitted into
evidence because it didn't appear relevant to the case, the
officials said.
   They said administration officials planned to closely monitor the
trial in the event there was an attempt by North's lawyers to
introduce into evidence documents that would compromise national
security.
   Gesell ruled in a Dec. 12 order that to ensure a fair trial for
North, there must be extensive disclosure by the prosecution from
the 300 classified documents it planned to use at trial, including
the verbatim text of many intelligence reports. That order and the
intelligence group's refusal to declassify many of the documents led
to Walsh's decision to seek dropping the conspiracy and theft counts
against North.
   Gesell issued a sealed order on Jan. 19 detailing how much must
be disclosed from the 300 classified documents North plans to use at
trial.
   North is accused of concealing from Congress and former Attorney
General Edwin Meese III his efforts on behalf of the Nicaraguan
Contras and of covering up the NSC's role in diverting money from
the Iran arms sales to the Contras.
   North also is accused of illegally accepting a $13,800 security
system at his home from co-defendant Richard Secord, converting to
his own use at least $4,300 in traveler's checks from Contra leader
Adolfo Calero and conspiring to defraud the Treasury of tax revenue
in connection with charitable contributions supporting the Contras.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
