<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     01-27 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Intelligence Chief Charged With Corruption</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors investigating alleged
wrongdoing under former President Chun Doo-hwan charged the nation's
former intelligence chief with corruption Friday and put him in
prison.
   Chang Se-dong, who was director of the Agency for National
Security Planning, was charged after two days of questioning.
   His arrest capped months of a government investigation into
alleged corruption and abuse of power under Chun's seven-year
authoritarian rule, which ended in February.
   Chang, 53, is the highest-ranking Chun official to be arrested.
   A legislator from the governing Democratic Justice Party and two
people who were Cabinet ministers under Chun were arrested on
corruption charges early this month.
   Last year, about a dozen members of Chun's family, including two
brothers, were convicted or charged with taking bribes and
embezzling millions of dollars.
   Chang, a former army general, was one of the most powerful men in
the nation under Chun. He played a major role in enforcing Chun's
tough rule and suppressing opposition.
   Prosecutors said Chang denied wrongdong, insisting that he just
followed presidential orders. Chang was head of Chun's presidential
security before serving as intelligence chief from 1985 to 1987.
   Prosecutor-General Kim Gi-chun indicated Chang's arrest marked an
end to the investigation.
   ``In the probe, we did our best. There were no preset limitations
to our investigation. All people found involved were sent to
prison,'' he told reporters.
   The charges against Chang are vague and relatively mild. They
include illegal construction of a guest house, which critics say was
to be used as Chun's office-mansion after retirement, and illegal
use of government office space.
   South Korean press reports said prosecutors had difficulty
finding hard evidence to use against Chang.
   The inquiry into Chun's government has dominated South Korean
politics for months, with opposition groups demanding the arrest of
Chang and several other former top Chun aides on human rights abuses.
   The opposition contends President Roh Tae-woo's government is not
making sufficient efforts to prosecute former Chun aides. Roh, a
former general and once a close ally of Chun, is closely identified
with the ex-president in the eyes of many South Koreans.
   Chun took power with military backing in 1980. Roh won
presidential elections in December 1987 and took office in February.
   In November, Chun apologized to the nation for abuses under his
rule and went into rural exile at a remote east coast Buddhist
monastery.
</TEXT>
