<HEAD>Airline Mechanics Blame Other Unions for Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking Iberia airlines jet mechanics blame
leftist unions as much as managers for the dispute that has caused
the company to trim about 100 flights a day, a mechanics' union
official said Friday.
   The mechanics' union mounted its ninth 24-hour strike since Dec.
23 on Friday.
   Union official Ramses Rodriguez said the mechanics are trying to
pressure Iberia to train them to meet international specifications.
They fear they could lose their jobs in 1993 when the European
Economic Community is to take steps to unify the labor pool and
establish common job norms.
   Rodriguez said, however, that communist- and socialist-led unions
representing most of the company's 21,000 ground employees failed to
include the point in collective bargaining. He said the mechanics
want separate talks to include their retraining in a larger pact
with the company.
   Iberia has estimated strike losses at $30.6 million.
