<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Jews     01-27 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Jews,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bronfman Urges Soviet Jewish Emigres to Head to Israel, Not United
States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the World Jewish
Congress said Friday that more Jewish emigres from the Soviet Union
should go to Israel, rather than the United States.
   Edgar M. Bronfman also said West German leaders promised they
would cooperate with international efforts against a Libyan plant
the United States says is intended for making poison gas.
   In an interview, Bronfman said the number of Soviet Jewish
emigres has increased vastly. In 1986, only 681 were permitted to
leave. More liberal policies allowed that number to jump to 20,000
in 1988.
   Soviet Jews leave with travel documents for Israel and travel to
Vienna, where many seek permission to resettle in the United States.
They then head to facilities in Ladispoli town outside Rome and
often wait weeks for a decision on their applications.
   ``They should go to Israel, or more of them should go to
Israel,'' said Bronfman. ``Now, it's a real strain on the U.S.
economy.''
   The American businessman said it costs $7,000 to resettle each of
the Soviet Jews in the United States.
   He noted that Soviet Jewish emigres have refugee status when they
leave.
   ``(But) most of the Soviet Jews who are leaving now are not
physically threatened. It's difficult to call them refugees,'' said
Bronfman.
   In September, the United States for the first time began
rejecting Soviet Jews for refugee status, with the current rejection
rate running at about 21 percent, according to Karl Zukerman of the
Hebrew Immigration Aid Society in New York.
   Bronfman said he wanted to avoid saying the United States had
``tightened'' its official policies regarding Soviet Jews, but
rather that Washington had ``largely ignored'' various restrictions
when the numbers were small.
   Bronfman spoke at length about his talks this week with West
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl and Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich
Genscher regarding the plant in Rapta, Libya, which the United
States says is being built to produce chemical weapons with help
from West German companies.
   Bronfman said German leaders assured him that legal penalties
will be increased for cases of illegal arms and arms-related exports.
   He said most importantly, the West Germans agreed to cooperate
with their allies to ensure the plant cannot produce poison gas.
   ``The teeth of the tiger will be pulled so that the plant cannot
produce poison gas,'' Bronfman said. ``How that's going to be done,
I did't get into that. I will be more satisfied when the world is
assured that Libya cannot produce chemical weapons.''
   The Libyan government denies the charges and maintains the plant
is a pharmaceutical complex.
   Bronfman called alleged West German involvement an example of
``greed overcoming common sense.''
</TEXT>
