<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Reagan     01-27 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Reagan,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush: Nothing Wrong with Reagan's Multi-Million Dollar Memoirs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   By W. DALE NELSON=
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Friday he sees nothing
wrong with Ronald Reagan receiving large sums of money for his
memoirs, noting that other former presidents have done it. ``I don't
think it's ever been challenged as inappropriate,'' Bush said.
   Bernie Swain, a partner in the Washington Speakers Bureau, says
he has a ``handshake agreement'' to represent Reagan and his wife,
Nancy, as their exclusive lecture agents. He said terms had not been
settled, but other industry sources said the former president could
command fees of $40,000 or more per speech.
   Earlier, it was reported that Reagan will receive $5 million from
Simon &amp; Schuster for his memoirs and a book of speeches.
   Bush was asked at his news conference if he thought it was
``appropriate to cash in on the presidency.''
   ``I don't know whether I'd call it `cashing in.' I expect every
president has written his memoirs and received money for it,'' he
said.
   He said he had read that President Grant received $500,000 at a
time when ``half a million really meant something'' for his memoirs.
   ``So I think there's plenty of tradition that goes with
presidents writing memoirs and being paid for it,'' he said.
   Asked whether it might not create a wrong perception, the
president replied, ``No, because I think there's been a long history
of that. And, I don't think it's ever been challenged as
inappropriate.''
   Bush did not address the question of lecture fees.
   The president was also asked whether the emphasis he has placed
on government ethics during his first week in office implied any
criticism of the Reagan administration's ethical record. He said,
``No.''
   Bush said he has spoken out as he has on the issue ``because I
feel strongly about it.''
   Swain said he was in the process of signing Reagan up for his
speakers bureau and that most of the former president's speaking
engagements would be in the West, at least for now. The Reagans now
live in Los Angeles.
   Don Walker, president of the Harry Walker Agency in New York,
said his firm represent several speakers who get fees in the $40,000
range. But generally that amount is paid for speeches which require
travel.
   The Walker agency's clients include former Secretary of Defense
Caspar Weinberger, former President Ford and former Secretary of
State Henry Kissinger, among others.
   Swain said his firm had received requests in the past to arrange
speeches by Reagan while he was in office, but had referred all such
requests to the White House.
   He said Maureen Reagan, the president's daughter, and former
White House Chief of Staff Kenneth Duberstein had also been added to
the bureau's roster of speakers this week.
</TEXT>
