<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     01-27 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OWENSBORO, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Don't ask Anabel Thompson the names of her
great-grandchildren. She has 100 of them.
   ``I couldn't tell you,'' she said. ``I've never known anyone with
that many great-grandchildren.''
   Mrs. Thompson, who will turn 90 in March, grew up with seven
brothers and a sister, raised 12 children with her husband and has
61 grandchildren.
   With the arrival of Ben Thompson last month, she reached the
century mark in great-grandchildren.
   ``The ones who live here come by to see me all the time,'' Mrs.
Thompson said. ``The ones who live out of town I usually see in the
summertime. I love my great-grandchildren as much as my own
children.''
   ``All the grandkids come to mother for advice and confide in her
a lot,'' said Patsy Clayton, one of Mrs. Thompson's daughters.
   ``Daddy always talked about throwing a rock in the water and
watching it ripple and ripple. That's how I think about all the
great-grandchildren.''
   A family reunion is planned in July. If Mrs. Thompson is able to
go, young Ben Thompson probably won't be the youngest she sees.
Great-grandchildren numbers 101, 102, and 103 are on the way.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: Following item also moving on sports circuits.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHARLEVOIX, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Mount McSauba ski resort says its
problem wasn't that prices were too high but that they were too low.
   ``Downstaters would call, ask our rates, laugh and hang up,''
said Ike Boss, recreation director. ``They thought any hill that
only charged $3.50 for skiing must be a piece of junk.''
   So operators doubled the lift ticket price to $7, and
out-of-towners have begun using the hill more frequently.
   Boss said he had to raise prices after Mount McSauba suffered
losses for years. But some local skiers said it's now difficult to
afford a day on the slopes.
   ``If you have a 7-year-old and a 4-year-old, as I do, I have to
spend $21, even though my 4-year-old cannot last longer than two
hours,'' said Lauri Wilson.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Organizers of a charity golf tournament wanted
to play on a frozen lake, but balmy weather swamped that idea.
   The Suburban Rotary Club moved this weekend's Arctic Open to a
country club after temperatures soared into the not-so-Arctic 40s
and 50s and melted the course.
   A nine-hole course was to be fashioned on Wehrspann Lake, with
hundreds of discarded Christmas trees lining the course.
   The Rotary club and the tournament co-sponsors, Wendy's fast-food
restaurants, hope to raise about $20,000 for scholarships for
handicapped students.
   One foresome planning to attend consists of politicians more
accustomed to teeing off on each other than teeing off together:
former Mayor Mike Boyle and three mayoral candidates, including City
Councilman Jim Cleary.
   Cleary, who invited the others to join him in a foursome, was
spokesman for a citizens group that recalled Boyle from office two
years ago.
   Boyle has not ruled out another try for the office.
