<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 1420EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-FirstWeek     01-27 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-First Week,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Says His First Week Was `Lovely'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Friday his first week in
office had been ``wonderfully harmonious,'' but conceded rougher
times loom ahead.
   Seven days almost to the hour after his inauguration, Bush was
still basking in the newsness of the job at his first full-fledged
news conference.
   ``I'm just getting a preview of coming attractions. And it's been
lovely,'' Bush said, adding, ``It's going to change and I know it.''
   He sloughed off questions about some of the rough spots of the
first week, including the furor over a Treasury Department proposal
for a depositor fee and renewed controversy over the abortion views
of Dr. Louis Sullivan, his nominee for secretary of health and human
services.
   ``I think it's been a wonderfully harmonious week. And these are
just little ripples on the surface of an otherwise calm pond,'' Bush
said.
   The president's news conference concluded a week rich in
symbolism but relatively lean of substance.
   That, Bush said, was the point of the first week, calling it a
time for setting ``a certain tone and outreach.''
   ``There'll be plenty of time for controversy, plenty of time for
lively debate on substance,'' he told reporters.
   In his first week, Bush called world leaders, including Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev; held a concilatory meeting with a
bipartisan delegation from Congress; set up a commission to recomend
an ethics code for government officials, and hammered the ethics
theme home in talks before various governmental groups.
   The White House also announced Bush would travel to Canada,
Japan, China and South Korea and said Japan's prime minister, Noburo
Takeshita, would visit here next week.
   Was Bush concerned that he would be criticzied for not having
much ``meat behind the words?''
   ``There is a danger of that. But people realize we've been here
five days,'' Bush said, referring to working days.
   He defended anew his decision to undertake a thorough review of
U.S.-Soviet relations.
   ``People ... understand that in things like the foreign policy
area, it's prudent to have a review. They understand that we've got
to get our people in place.
   ``We'll just go forward,'' he added. ``If we just sat around and
did nothing but be pleasant to people on the Hill or something, ...
I suspect that would grow a little old.''
   And he said he was sticking by his HHS secretary-designate,
disputing statements that Sullivan had disagreed with Bush's
conviction that the Supreme Court decision legalizing abortion
should be overturned. ``We are in sync,'' Bush declared.
   And he quickly distanced himself from the much-criticized
proposal of Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady to charge depositors a
fee to shore up the nation's ailing savings and loan industry. Bush
said that the proposal hadn't even made it to his desk yet and it's
``a little absurd'' to be commmenting on it at this stage.
   Overall, Bush said, ``It's been a good easy week _ and I expect
it will change dramatically in the weeks ahead.''
   While claiming the week had been marred by a head cold, he said
he still planned to ``smile and enjoy it while you can.''
   ``Because I can already sense, you know, looking forward, a
little more confrontation out there.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
