<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ilona Staller, Italy's porn star parliamentarian
known as Cicciolina, bared her breasts in front of the U.S.
Consulate on Friday after failing to obtain a visa to perform in San
Francisco.
   As photographers snapped away on Via Veneto, the 37-year-old Ms.
Staller opened her coat and blouse and held up a sign saying, in
Italian, ``Why is the United States afraid of Cicciolina's breasts?''
   ``This isn't the end. I am not giving up,'' said Ms. Staller, who
has been invited to perform in the O'Farrell Theater in San
Francisco. The Hungarian-born Ms. Staller has been trying for weeks
to obtain a U.S. visa.
   Embassy spokesman Mark Dillen said her application was under
review. He declined to give any reason for the delay, but it is
believed to stem from her failure to list her arrests on the
application.
   She has been arrested on obscenity charges several times, and on
Wednesday was convicted of public obscenity.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 41-year-old former legal secretary who calls
herself Billie Jean and claims she is married to Michael Jackson has
been convicted of trespassing at the pop superstar's mansion.
   Lavon A. Muhammad, who also says Jackson fathered her 6-year-old
twins, was found guilty Wednesday of eight misdemeanors, including
trespassing and violating a court order to stay more than 100 yards
from Jackson's Encino property.
   The woman, who calls herself Billie Jean Jackson, allegedly has
harassed Jackson for five years, leading to a 1986 restraining order.
   Jackson's song ``Billie Jean,'' about a man denying a paternity
claim, is one of his biggest hits.
   Van Nuys Municipal Judge Stephen E. O'Neil told Ms. Muhammad she
faces up to 2{ years in jail at sentencing Monday if she continues
to refuse psychiatric treatment.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dirty dancing got rhythm and blues singer
Bobby Brown in trouble with the police but didn't stop the show.
   Brown, arrested during a performance Wednesday for violating
Columbus' anti-lewdness ordinance, paid a $652 fine and returned to
finish his show.
   ``He brought a woman up from the audience and was dancing around
her, then got right up to her'' and moved in a simulation of sexual
intercourse, said police Maj. John Wood.
   When Brown left the stage, Sgt. Bobby Horne, head of security at
the Municipal Auditorium, arrested him.
   The city ordinance prohibits performers at an event attended by
people under age 18 to show nudity or sexual pictures or models or
to use ``four-letter sexual words.''
   Brown was booked at the jail and was back on stage about an hour
later, Wood said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BELLEVUE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Donaldson and Elena Akhmilovskaya,
the American and Soviet chess players who eloped in November, met
across a huge playing board at a shopping center exhibition match,
and played to a draw.
   For their marriage, that might have been best, Donaldson admitted
after the match Thursday night. ``It's too dangerous,'' he said. ``I
felt it in my heart. Maybe married couples shouldn't play against
one another.''
   They played their first game against one another Thursday on an
8-foot chessboard. During the game, the couple smiled repeatedly at
one another.
   ``That was because we both thought we were winning,'' Donaldson
said.
   Donaldson, ranked 40th in the world, and Ms. Akhmilovskaya,
ranked fourth among women chess players, eloped to Germany from a
tournament in Greece.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former world chess champion Anatoly Karpov of the
Soviet Union refused to talk about the possibility of taking away
the world title from countryman Garry Kasparov.
   Instead, the 37-year-old Karpov wanted to focus Thursday only on
25-year-old Johann Hjartason of Iceland, his opponent in a World
Chess Federation quarterfinal match that starts Saturday night.
   ``This is a very interesting problem and a very interesting
question. But I think this is the wrong time to discuss it. I have
to play this match and I only want to talk about this match,''
Karpov said when asked about his chances of dethroning Kasparov.
   Kasparov won the world championship from Karpov in 1985 and
retained his title against Karpov in 1987 when their 24-game match
ended in a 12-12 tie.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DOTHAN, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Randy Owen, Teddy Gentry, Jeff Cook and Mark
Herndon showed up in court, but the members of the country music
group Alabama did not wait around to hear the verdict in their favor
in a breach-of-contract case.
   A jury ruled Thursday the group did not break a video contract,
but it found Alabama's booking firm, Dale Morris and Associates,
liable for $3,000 to Dare Productions.
   Dare Productions of Dothan filed the $12 million suit in 1982,
charging the group and its Nashville booking firm with breaching a
contract allowing the production company to tape a 1981 concert and
market the video.
