<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Fed     01-27 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Fed,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Says He and Greenspan Have Similar Views</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Friday that Federal Reserve
Board Chairman Alan Greenspan worries more than he does about
inflation right now, but that otherwise their views are similar.
   ``Basically and generally speaking, I think we're fairly close
together,'' Bush said at his first presidential news conference.
   Bush was asked about what appeared to be a disagreement between
himself and the Fed over its policy on interest rates.
   Greenspan earlier this week told Congress that the risk of higher
inflation was great enough that the Fed should ``err more on the
side of restrictiveness than of stimulus'' in setting interest rate
and credit policy.
   The Fed has been gradually tightening credit, pushing up
short-term interest rates, in recent months to keep the economy from
overheating.
   Bush, however, said this week that he didn't want the Fed to
``move so strongly against fear of inflation that we impede growth.''
   Greenspan ``is more concerned about inflationary pressures than I
am right now. Seems to me, there's an area of difference,'' Bush
said Friday.
   Bush said one cause of Greenspan's concern appeared to be recent
statistics showing that the nation's factories were operating at
82.4 percent of capacity last month _ the highest level in nine
years.
   Many economists have suggested that the high level of factory
utilization, combined with an unemployment rate at a 14-year low of
5.3 percent, could soon combine to force up the price of
manufactured goods.
</TEXT>
