<DOCNO> AP890127-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 1443EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-DetroitNewspapers     01-27 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Detroit Newspapers,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Upholds News-Free Press Joint Operating Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Court of Appeals today cleared the way
for the partial merger of Detroit's two daily newspapers, the Free
Press and the News.
   In a 2-1 decision, the court said a ruling last year by
then-Attorney General Edwin Meese III approving the joint operating
agreement of the two newspapers was ``based on a permissible
construction'' of the Newspaper Preservation Act.
   The act creates an exemption to the antitrust laws that permits a
joint arrangement between two newspapers if the attorney general
determines that one of the two papers is ``a failing newspaper'' and
in probable danger of financial failure.
   The appeals court said Meese's application of the legal standard
to the facts in the case ``was not arbitrary, capricious or an abuse
of discretion.''
   ``Congress ... delegated to the attorney general, not to us, the
delicate and troubling responsibility of putting content into the
ambiguous phrase, `probable danger of financial failure,''' the
appeals court ruling said. ``We cannot say that his interpretation
of that phrase ... was unreasonable.''
   The ruling affirmed a decision in September by U.S. District
Judge George Revercomb. He rejected contentions by a group of
Detroit advertisers and readers that the morning Free Press, owned
by Knight-Ridder Inc., was not a failing newspaper entitled to
antitrust exemptions under the 1970 Newspaper Preservation Act.
   Knight-Ridder has threatened to close the Free Press if the joint
operating agreement is not approved. The News is owned by Gannett
Co. Inc.
   Consolidating the two newspapers' business, advertising,
circulation and production departments would result in layoffs of
between 600 and 800 employees _ compared with the loss of 2,200 jobs
if the Free Press were shut down.
</TEXT>
