<DOCNO> AP890127-0148 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 1541EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Tower-NATO     01-27 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tower-NATO,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Secretary-Designate to Warn Allies of Possible Kremlin Ploy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MUNICH, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Tower, the U.S. defense
secretary-designate, arrived Friday for a strategy session with NATO
allies in which he will warn of a possible Kremlin ploy to weaken
the Western alliance.
   Tower took a break from Senate confirmation hearings to address
the 26th annual conference of policymakers from the 16 NATO members.
He is expected to be confirmed.
   ``I find this to be a very interesting and productive conference
because of the frankness of the exchange of views,'' Tower told The
Associated Press upon arrival. He has attended all but one of the
previous 25 meetings.
   Tower apparently was referring to the sometimes volatile
exchanges that take place at the sessions delving into defense
strategy, arms control and fair distribution of security costs and
burdens.
   Tower refused further comment on his expectations for the session
on grounds he is ``embargoed from giving interviews until
confirmation.''
   But copies of a speech Tower is to deliver Sunday were released
Friday. In it, Tower restates his support for ``modernizing,'' or
extending European-based short-range missiles now capable of
striking as far away as 300 miles.
   ``Continued wrangling and delays only provide the Soviet Union
with an opportunity to try to undermine NATO unity,'' he says,
referring to debates among Europeans about the need for and wisdom
of modifying the missiles to effectively replace medium-range
rockets being withdrawn from Europe under the superpower treaty
signed in 1987.
   Tower makes several references in the address to what he
perceives as a possible Kremlin ploy to enhance differences among
the Western allies and thus weaken NATO.
   ``We cannot afford to be lulled into a false sense of security,''
the address reads. ``The jury is still out on how long or how far
the Soviet leadership will tolerate change.''
   He also presses the Western alliance to take advantage of its
technological superiority by developing more sophisticated weapons
systems than the economically strapped East bloc could afford to
match.
   The weekend session, ``Alliances in a Changing World,'' will give
Washington's allies their first good reading of the defense plans of
President Bush.
   It also is expected to spotlight differences among the allies
over how East-West disarmament should proceed.
   As Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev has pushed for deep cuts in
nuclear stockpiles and announced some unilateral reductions in
troops, tanks and short-range missiles in Eastern Europe, West
Europeans have been increasingly critical of NATO doctrine.
   For example, West German public opinion polls show declining
fears of the East bloc and waning support for more defense spending
and the presence of allied troops, tanks and low-flying aircraft.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
