<FIRST>r a AM-Administrator-Heart     01-27 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Administrator-Heart,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heart Transplant Program Developer Dies Awaiting Heart</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who helped develop New Mexico's
only heart transplant program died Friday after his own heart was
stricken suddenly by a viral infection and a donor organ could not
be found, officials said.
   Robert Shafer, 46, assistant administrator for medical staff
affairs at Presbyterian Hospital, suffered the attack last week, and
his condition rapidly deteriorated.
   ``The feeling of helplessness has gripped us all,'' said hospital
spokeswoman Lynn Villella. ``The donor program has done everything
humanly possible.''
   Shafer left work Jan. 19 with flu-like symptoms and was admitted
to the hospital Monday. He was put on a list of transplant
candidates Tuesday and placed on a heart-lung machine Wednesday
after his heart failed.
   On Friday morning, his family requested he be taken off the
machine after all his organs began to deteriorate, she said.
   Shafer, an administrator at the hospital for 20 years, oversaw
its heart program when it began in 1969 and helped direct its
development since then, Ms. Villella said.
   The program began transplants in 1986 and since then has done 32,
plus one heart-lung transplant.
   Gov. Garrey Carruthers had issued an appeal for a donor, as did
Shafer's wife, Joyce, who pledged to work to increase public
awareness of the need for donor organs. ``This should never happen
to anyone else,'' she said in a statement.
   Many viruses can either attack the heart directly or cause the
body's immune system to damage the heart, said Dr. Ronnie Garner, a
Presbyterian pathologist.
   Shafer's case was particularly unusual because of the quick
progression to complete heart failure, he said.
</TEXT>
