<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Afghanistan     01-27 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Afghanistan,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Says Embassy Closed to Save U.S. Lives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, offering a dim assessment of
the situation in Afghanistan as Soviets troops withdraw, said Friday
that U.S. Embassy officials have been ordered out of the war-torn
country to save their lives.
   ``It is a prudent policy to protect a handful of American
lives,'' Bush told an impromptu White House news conference.
   Bush, queried about the reason behind Secretary of State James A.
Baker III's decision to close the Kabul embassy, said:
   ``I think there's a lot of uncertainty. There's enough
uncertainty that the secretary of state was taking prudent action in
this regard.''
   Fewer than 10 diplomats and security guards are left in the U.S.
outpost. All travel by American civilians to the country had already
been banned.
   The safety of the U.S. contingent came into question in recent
weeks as fighting has intensified between U.S.-supported rebels and
the Soviet-backed regime of Najibullah.
   The rebels are expected to launch an all-out drive against the
government forces once the last of 50,000 Soviet soldiers leave the
capital, which Moscow has said will come by Feb. 15.
   Bush said he did not mention Afghanistan last week when he spoke
at length with Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, but said he
was convinced the withdrawal will continue.
   Bush went on to say that he believed there is ``uncertainty about
what follows'' the pull-out and that he hoped the United States
would play a ``catalytic role for helping bring about stability'' in
the future.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman echoed Bush's comments,
saying the decision to remove the employees was made ``solely on
security grounds, in a deteriorating situation and growing
uncertainty that the regime can provide any kind of security in the
coming days.''
   Redman added that the move, which affects fewer than 10 diplomats
and security guards, does not mean that the diplomatic post has been
shut down for good. ``We hope to have our people back there as soon
as the security situation would permit that,'' he said.
   Fewer than 20 U.S. citizens are in Afghanistan. They have been
encouraged to leave by U.S. officials.
   A group of Afghan employees will remain at the embassy,
essentially as housekeepers, the spokesman said.
   Redman pointed out that closing the embassy does not create a
major diplomatic problem because the United States does not
recognize the legitimacy of the Najibullah regime and the embassy
had acted primarily as ``a listening post.''
   ``We don't have any interests to represent because we don't
recognize the legitimacy of that regime in any case,'' Redman said.
   Afghan guerrillas, armed by the United States and Pakistan, are
fighting to wrest control of the country from government forces
backed by the Soviets. The drive by the Mujahedeen rebels for Kabul
and a deteriorating situation in the capital threatened to expose
the Americans to the cross-fire.
   The U.S. diplomatic contingent was gradually reduced over the
years, and the country has been without a full-time American
ambassador since Adolph Dubs was killed by Afghan forces a decade
ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890127-0152 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 1558EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Czech-Troops     01-27 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czech-Troops,0568</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czechoslovakia, Bulgaria Announce Troop Cuts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Czechoslovakia and Bulgaria
announced Friday they will follow their Warsaw Pact allies and cut
troops and defense spending.
   Only Romania, increasingly isolated in the Soviet bloc, has not
made a similar announcement.
   Czechoslovakia said Friday it will cut defense spending by 15
percent and trim its armed forces by 12,000 men, 850 tanks, 165
armored vehicles and 51 fighter planes in the next two years.
   Hours later, the Bulgarian state news agency announced the State
Council and government approved a motion from Communist leader Todor
Zhivkov to reduce the country's 1989 defense budget by 12 percent
and its armed forces by 10,000 men.
   By 1991, Bulgaria also will scrap 200 tanks, 200 artillery
systems, 20 aircraft and five naval units, BTA said without
elaborating.
   According to NATO, Bulgaria has 135,000 men under arms and
Czechoslovakia 145,000.
   East Germany, Hungary and Poland all have announced cuts in
military manpower and spending, following the lead of Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev who said Dec. 7 he would reduce the
Red Army by half a million men by 1991.
   The cuts seem designed to boost new NATO-Warsaw Pact talks on
reducing conventional troops and weapons across Europe, to open in
Vienna in March.
   They also benefit the Communist governments by freeing funds for
sorely needed economic reforms and by creating pressure for NATO to
follow suit with cuts of its own.
   A spokesman at the Western military alliance's Brussels
headquarters said Thursday the recently announced Soviet bloc
reductions still leave a ``great imbalance'' in Europe, with Western
ground troops outnumbered almost 2-1.
   CTK, the official Czechoslovak news agency, billed the measures
as a unilateral contribution to boost confidence and security in
Europe. Prague would contemplate more cuts if the West follows the
East's lead in cutting men and armaments, it said.
   The Czechoslovak army's reserve force would lose 15,000 men and
the number of divisions involved in military maneuvers and tactical
exercises would be halved, according to CTK.
   It said 20,000 soldiers now on active duty would be transferred
to army construction brigades, while the equipment for three more
divisions would be put into storage and most men from those
divisions diverted to other duties.
   The cuts in Czechoslovakia, East Germany and Hungary are in
addition to those announced by Gorbachev, who told the United
Nations on Dec. 7 that 50,000 Soviet troops and 5,000 Soviet tanks
would be withdrawn from those nations.
   Soviet defense officials have said partial withdrawal could begin
as soon as April.
   East Germany has said it would cut its armed forces by 10,000
soldiers and reduce defense spending by 10 percent. It also will
scrap 600 tanks and 50 warplanes.
   Hungary already has cut its military budget by 17 percent in real
terms from 1988, and in December announced plans to retire more than
50 top officers who are over 60 years old, including 10 generals.
   Poland said it has reduced its army by 15,000 men during the past
two years and would dissolve two divisions in 1989 and reduce two
more by 85 percent.
   It also said its military budget for 1989 is $1.9 billion,
representing 3.6 percent of this year's national income compared to
the 1988 budget's 3.8 percent of the year's national income.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
