<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 1601EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-MametPlay     01-27 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mamet Play,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>Broadway Hit `Speed-the-Plow' Gets Mixed London Reviews</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The London premiere of David Mamet's
``Speed-the-Plow'' received mixed reviews for the play itself and
for the actress in the role created by Madonna.
   The acerbic comedy, which ended its hit Broadway run New Year's
Eve, opened in London on Wednesday at the National Theater, where
Mamet's ``Glengarry Glen Ross'' had its world premiere in 1983.
   That play won the London equivalent of the Tony Award as the
year's best, but on the basis of its critical reception,
``Speed-the-Plow'' seems unlikely to follow suit.
   Jack Tinker of The Daily Mail praised ``the strong and sinewy
dialogue'' of Mamet's short, three-act play, a morality tale set in
the wheeler-dealer environment of modern Hollywood.
   Tinker thanked the National for repairing ``the damage'' caused
by casting Madonna in New York, but he nonetheless felt the play has
``a hole where its heart should be.''
   Milton Shulman similarly faulted the play's ``basically hollow
center'' while admiring the ``breathless pace'' of the staging by
its original Broadway director, Gregory Mosher.
   ``Speed-the-Plow'' stars Colin Stinton and Alfred Molina as
fellow movie producers and longtime friends and Rebecca Pidgeon as
the temporary secretary, Karen, who momentarily throws their
friendship into question.
   Maureen Paton in The Daily Express wrote that Ms. Pidgeon ``puts
Madonna to shame (not difficult).'' The critic found the play
``biliously funny.''
   Michael Billington in The Guardian praised the actress'
``emotional directness'' and said Mosher's direction ``whips along
zippily.''
   But Michael Coveney in The Financial Times thought the play
``thinly textured'' and denounced Ms. Pidgeon as ``another woefully
inexperienced National Theater recruit.''
   ``Speed-the-Plow'' is expected to move to the commercial West End
in the summer, and the opening saw a full turn-out of London
producers.
   Mamet's play is the second American play to open in London this
week. On Monday, the Young Vic Theater opened ``Two-Way Mirror,''
two Arthur Miller one-acts which were poorly received in their
American debut in New Haven, Conn., in 1982.
   The London reception was marginally better, with critics
reserving most praise for David Thacker's production and the
performances of the stars, Helen Mirren and Bob Peck.
   Miller's writing itself drew mixed marks, with Charles Spencer in
The Daily Telegraph commenting: ``I was uneasily aware that if the
plays had been by a less venerable author and performed by less
persuasive actors, they would have commanded a great deal less
attention.''
</TEXT>
