<FIRST>r i AM-Soering     01-27 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soering,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>German Sought by United States to Get Speedy Hearing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STRASBOURG, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Court of Human Rights
agreed Friday to give a speedy hearing to a West German fighting
extradition to the United States, where he faces the death penalty
for a double murder in Virginia.
   In its interim ruling, the court agreed to give priority to the
case of Jens Soering, according to court spokesman Jack Henning. He
said the hearing will probably take place in late April or early May.
   The 22-year-old West German is wanted in Virginia for the March
30, 1985, murder of the parents of his girlfriend at their home in
Bedford County.
   He is in jail in Britain, which agreed to extradite him to stand
trial in Virginia. However, he is appealing that decision to the
European Court of Human Rights.
   Soering argues he faces the death penalty in violation of the
European Human Rights Convention, which says ``no one shall be
subjected to ... inhuman or degrading treatment or punishment.''
   He also argues a lack of legal aid for appeals in Virginia
violates his human rights and that he was denied a full hearing in
the British courts to fight extradition.
   Virginia officials have agreed at Britain's request to recommend
that Soering not be put to death.
   The European Court of Human Rights, a body of the Council of
Europe, hears alleged violations of the European Convention of Human
Rights. Its rulings are binding on the 21 member states of the
council, which has its headquarters in this city.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
