<FIRST>r w AM-US-Vietnam 290   01-27 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Vietnam, 290</SECOND>
<UNK>Vietnam Promises Cooperation on MIA's</UNK>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam has promised the Bush administration it
will continue to cooperate with U.S. attempts to obtain an
accounting of U.S. servicemen still missing from the Vietnam war,
the State Department said Friday.
   Vietnam's ambassador to the United Nations, Trinh Xuan Lang,
spent an hour Thursday discussing that issue with officials from the
State Department, National Security Council and the Pentagon.
   It was the first visit by a Hanoi official for diplomatic
discussions since the northern half of Vietnam became independent
from France in 1954. The southern half of Vietnam came under Hanoi's
rule after 1975.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said the session with
Lang dealt exclusively with the POW-MIA issue.
   The administration allowed Lang's visit by waiving restrictions
which limit his travels to the New York City area.
   He had asked for permission to visit Washington to attend a
reception Thursday evening sponsored by Sight Savers International,
a non-profit group which trains foreign doctors in eye surgery
techniques.
   The administration used Lang's visit to reaffirm its concerns
about obtaining an accounting for the more than 1,700 U.S.
servicemen still missing in Vietnam.
   ``We explained the need for our investigations to be as thorough
as possible, for which the ambassador pledged his government's
continuing cooperation,'' Redman said.
   Redman and other officials have said Lang's visit should not be
construed as a softening of U.S. terms for normalizing relations
with Vietnam.
   The principal condition is the withdrawal of Vietnamese troops
from Cambodia.
   Lang was to meet Friday afternoon with Sen. Frank Murkowski,
R-Alas., who has proposed the establishment of U.S. offices in
Vietnam to deal with humanitarian issues.
</TEXT>
