<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 1640EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-DanceSettlement     01-27 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dance Settlement,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>FTC Says Miami Company Agrees to Pay $105,000 Fine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Miami company franchising the Fred Astaire
Dance Studios has agreed to pay a fine of $105,000 for violating a
1964 Federal Trade Commission order requiring certain refund and
cancellation rights for its students, the commission said Friday.
   The company, Ronby Corp., signed a consent decree agreeing not to
violate the order in the future, the FTC said.
   The decree settling the commission's complaint was filed with the
U.S. District Court in Miami. Under the decree, the company neither
admits nor denies guilt. But if the court adopts the decree, the
company may be punished for future violations.
   Over the objections of one of its members, the commission agreed
to accept the fine in installments.
   The commission said Ronby violated the 1964 order by requiring
customers to listen to sales pitches for future lessons before
completing their first course, by selling additional lessons during
instruction time, by failing to give refunds and attempting to
conceal the true price of lessons and by using relays of sales
representatives in attempts to sell lessons.
   The commission issued, for 30 days of public comment, draft
modifications of the 1964 decree. It said the changes would
strengthen protection for the students. Among other things, the
modifications call for pro rata refunds for unused lessons when a
customer cancels, and would require Ronby to cancel the franchise of
any studio violating terms of the modified order.
   The commission acted on a 3-1 vote, with Andrew J. Strenio
dissenting. He said he objected to installment payment of the fine,
and would have at least insisted on provision of collateral until
all the payments were made.
</TEXT>
