<FIRST>r i AM-OilRig     01-27 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Rig,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Engineer Says Firefighting System on Rig was Nearly Useless</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABERDEEN, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A firefighting system was clogged and
``virtually useless'' on an oil rig where 167 men died in an
explosion and fire last year, a company engineer told an official
inquiry Friday.
   However, an Energy Department report last year said the system,
which sprays water to put out a fire, was turned off at the time
anyway because divers were repairing water intakes.
   Conrad Wottge, Occidental Oil Corp.'s facilities engineering
manager, said Friday he had warned of problems with what is called
the ``water-deluge system'' on the Piper Alpha rig in March 1988,
four months before the disaster.
   An interim inquiry concluded in September that an explosion in a
gas compressor of the North Sea rig ruptured gas pipelines, setting
off a series of explosions and fires. It was the world's worst oil
rig disaster.
   Wottge said the existing firefighting system was ``virtually
useless'' because it could not be counted on to put out a fire. He
said its pipes were clogged with mineral deposits and needed to be
replaced.
   He said design of a new system was underway at the time of the
disaster on July 6.
   He also said the rig had no structural fireproofing.
   The engineer recommended in March that most of the gas stored on
the rig be removed.
</TEXT>
