<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 1704EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Bennett     01-27 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Bennett,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>WIth AM-Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Friday he left William
Bennett, the head of his anti-drug effort, out of the Cabinet to
free Bennett for anti-drug activities and not to lessen the
importance of Bennett's post.
   Bennett and some of his supporters were surprised that Bennett
was not made a member of the Cabinet.
   Bush could have permitted Bennett to meet with the Cabinet, as he
has done with Carla Hills, the administration's trade
representative, and Richard Darman, director of the Office of
Management and Budget.
   ``The reason he (Bennett) isn't in the Cabinet is that I tried to
reduce down the numbers of full Cabinet members,'' Bush told a news
conference. He was referring to the fact that he removed two
Cabinet-level posts from advisory group, including CIA director and
United Nations ambassador.
   ``And I think Bill Bennett's time is best spent not worrying
about agricultural subsidies _ when we have a meeting on agriculture
_ but concentrating on drugs.''
   Bush said he doesn't want his action misinterpreted as a
statement that he believes fighting drugs is of lesser importance
than other issues that might come before the Cabinet.
   ``You will see me, side by side with Bill Bennett, on putting the
proper emphasis from the Oval Office on my determination to do
everything in the government's power...to eliminate this scourge.''
   Bush said he wants to ``find a way to step up the total funding
on anti-narcotics,'' but he offered no specifics.
   The position of drug czar, formally known as director of National
Drug Control Policy, was set up last fall when Congress passed a
package of anti-drug legislation. The bill specified that the drug
czar should be a Cabinet-level job, but that is not the same as
actually being in the Cabinet.
   A Bush transition team official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Bennett was surprised when he was not invited to the
new administration's first Cabinet meeting Monday.
   Members of Congress also were surprised Bush left Bennett out of
the Cabinet. Rep. Bob Dornan, R-Calif., said Bush should change the
decision.
   ``If the administration is going to keep the high profile it says
drugs is going to be, then I think there has to be room at the table
so that at every Cabinet meeting, there is a presence at the table
of this problem,'' Dornan said.
   Dornan said Congress had anticipated the drug czar would have
Cabinet rank in creating the job, even though the Cabinet's
membership is up to the president.
   Sen. Joseph Biden Jr., D-Del., chairman of the Senate Judiciary
Committee, said he was dismayed by the decision not to make the
position a Cabinet post.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
