<FIRST>r w AM-Grain-Soviets     01-27 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grain-Soviets,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Buy More Grain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has bought another 25,000
metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized prices, the Agriculture
Department said Friday.
   Christopher E. Goldthwait, acting general sales manager for the
department's Foreign Agricultural Service, said the wheat was part
of an authorization of more than 2 million tons under the Export
Enhancement Program, or EEP.
   Goldthwait said the wheat is for shipment for March. Counting
some left over from a previous EEP arrangement and a newly
authorized 2 million tons this week, the Soviets have more than 2.01
million tons still available under the program.
   With the latest sale, the Soviet Union has bought about 1.9
million tons of wheat for delivery in the sixth year of a long-term
supply agreement, which was extended last fall to run through Dec.
31, 1990.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels
of wheat. The 25,000 tons are equal to about 917,500 bushels worth
around $3.7 million at recent U.S. farm prices.
   The EEP arrangement allows private exporters to sell wheat and
other designated commodities to specified countries at reduced
prices in order to meet foreign competition. The exporters then
collect free government surpluses of grain or other products as
bonuses, or subsidies.
   Sales for delivery in the sixth year of the agreement also
included about 10.2 million tons of corn, along with 450,000 tons of
soybeans, 1.28 million tons of soybean meal, and 500,000 tons of
grain sorghums.
   Goldthwait said the 25,000 tons of wheat were sold by the Peavey
Co., which will get subsidy of $23.70 per ton, or about 65 cents per
bushel under the EEP arrangement.
</TEXT>
