<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia-Havel     01-27 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia-Havel,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds Call for Playwright's Release</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of established writers, painters
and other Czechoslovaks in the arts publicly sided with human rights
dissidents and urged the release of banned playwright Vaclav Havel,
emigre sources said.
   They also urged authorities to open a dialogue immediately with
burgeoning independent groups and with young people.
   It was believed to be the first time so many establishment
figures in Czechoslovakia took sides publicly with dissidents of the
Charter 77 human rights movement. That 1,000-member group Monday
urged Communist authorities to open a dialogue with independent
groups on political and social reform.
   The appeal by 692 writers, painters, filmmakers, actors, and
others came in a letter dated Thursday to Czechoslovak Premier
Ladislav Adamec, two emigre sources said on condition of anonymity.
The signatories include Oscar-winning film director Jiri Menzel,
actress Jana Brejchva and painter Jan Bauch, the sources said.
   The letter also said the signatories were ``disturbed and
offended'' by how the official media reported on demonstrations last
week in Prague, the sources said.
   The emigre sources said the letter called for release of Havel,
the country's best-known dissident, and other activists detained
with him on Jan. 16.
   Fifteen activists were arrested, but only Havel, 58, and two
others remain in custody. All have been told they will face charges
of hooliganism or disturbing public order. Government spokesman
Miroslav Pavel said this week Havel probably will be charged with
hooliganism, which carries a penalty of up to two years in jail.
   Last week's wave of demonstrations was the biggest since the
weeks after the Soviet-led invasion of Czechoslovakia in 1968
crushed government reforms.
   Governments, trade unions and artists in the West expressed
outrage in 1979 when Havel and five other dissidents were jailed
after a two-day subversion trial.
   Articles in the official media have branded as anti-socialist
Charter and other independent groups who called a banned rally on
Jan. 15. The use of police force to crush that rally fueled last
week's protests, and all but one of the new protests were broken up
by police.
   At last week's demonstrations, thousands of people chanted for
the release of Havel.
</TEXT>
