<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 1753EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FmHA-Budget     01-27 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FmHA-Budget,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farm Losses Don't Add to Deficit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $36 billion backlog of losses piled up by the
Farmers Home Administration is not adding to the federal budget
deficit, according to a report Friday by the Congressional Research
Service.
   ``Although FmHA loan losses are large, the budget impact of these
losses have already been recognized in scaled-down projections for
future loan repayments,'' the report said. ``The writeoff of these
delinquent loans per se does not require a budget outlay; hence, the
deficit is not affected.''
   The report said a recent audit by the General Accounting Office,
another agency of Congress, showed that FmHA over a 40-year period
through 1987 had as much as $36 billion in accumulated deficits that
will require large sums of congressional funding.
   ``This led some observers to conclude that FmHA will likely fuel
the federal budget deficit by requiring an infusion of cash similar
to the plight of the savings and loan crisis,'' the report said.
   The FmHA funds its accumulated losses by borrowing directly from
the Treasury. Each year, the report said, the agency asks Congress
for reimbursement of losses that were incurred two years earlier.
For example, the budget requests for the 1990 fiscal year that will
begin Oct. 1 will be for fiscal 1988 losses.
   ``To date, FmHA has been reimbursed by annual congressional
appropriations for virtually all of the $39 billion in loan
writeoffs that it has recognized through (fiscal) 1989,'' the report
said. ``FmHA estimates that nearly $20 billion in loan loss
reimbursement requests will be submitted over the next several
years.''
   The report said that while it may be inaccurate to compare FmHA
losses to the savings and loan situation, ``the magnitude of FmHA's
loan repayment problems should not be diminished.''
   But it added: ``Most budget projections already take into account
that the most seriously delinquent FmHA loans will not be repaid.
Therefore, unless there were another downturn in the farm economy or
other economic shock that caused a further deterioration in the
repayment capacity of FmHA borrowers, future outlays and the federal
deficit should not be further affected by loan repayment problems.''
   The report, which was dated Jan. 18, was written by agricultural
policy analyst Ralph Chite of the Congressional Research Service's
food and agriculture section.
   As an agency of the Agriculture Department, the FmHA is often
called the government's lender of last resort for farmers who cannot
qualify for credit elsewhere. As of last Sept. 30, the agency had
total loans outstanding of about $62 billion.
   Less than half of the total, about $25.5 billion, was owned under
farm lending programs. The balance was for FmHA loans for rural
housing and rural development.
   Of the total $62 billion in loans, about $9.2 billion were
delinquent as of last Sept. 30. The farm delinquencies represented
$8.3 billion of that amount. The FmHA has sent collection notices to
thousands of delinquent borrowers telling them to make arrangements
with the agency for repayments or face the possibility of forced
sales or foreclosures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890127-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 1754EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-GippSweater     01-27 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gipp Sweater,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Donor Of Gipp Sweater Regrets It Left Notre Dame For Reagan's Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS P. WYMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man who gave the University of Notre
Dame a sweater worn by football legend George Gipp says he is
stunned the university gave it away _ even to Ronald Reagan.
   ``Belatedly, I now regret not stipulating that the Gipp monogram
would be `on loan,''' said John N. Cackley in an opinion column in
Friday's South Bend Tribune.
   ``I never dreamed that someone at Notre Dame would go to the
extreme of satisfying egos in the White House and at the university
just to create an atmosphere of good old-fashioned `show biz,'''
said Cackley, a 1937 graduate and executive director emeritus of the
alumni association.
   University President Edward Malloy presented the blue and gold
Notre Dame sweater to Reagan when the national champion Notre Dame
football team visited the White House on Jan. 18, two days before
Reagan left office.
   Reagan played the dying Gipp in the 1940 movie ``Knute Rockne,
All-American,'' his first big break in the movies. He has used as a
political slogan Rockne's instruction to his players to ``win one
for the Gipper.''
   Cackley, of South Bend, said the 70-year-old sweater was an
``authentic, irreplaceable, one-of-a-kind'' item that had been
displayed only six months near the athletic department offices.
   ``Tradition, so often cherished at this institution, was shunted
aside with the Gipp article being handed over to the old actor for
his Notre Dame collection,'' he said.
   Charles Lennon, director of the Notre Dame Alumni Association,
said at least 15 alumni called to praise the idea.
   ``Most of our alumni would certainly understand the gift has
strong meanings for the president, as well as to the university,''
he said.
   Cackley said the dying Gipp gave the sweater to roommate Percy
Wilcox, who later passed it to another classmate, Tom Lee. Lee gave
the sweater to Cackley, who kept the sweater about five years before
giving it to Notre Dame.
   ``The sweater was not intended to be a give-away, regardless of
who might like to have it _ whether that be Ronald Reagan, Jimmy
Carter, John Paul II or anyone else,'' he said.
   University spokesman Richard Conklin referred questions to James
E. Murphy, associate vice president for university relations, who
was out of town Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
