<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-MiddleEast     01-27 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Middle East,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Cautious on PLO Connection</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Friday he would keep U.S.
talks going with the Palestine Liberation Organization but was
skeptical about direct overtures to chairman Yasser Arafat.
   In contrast to the warm reception the barnstorming Palestinian
leader is receiving on a support-seeking tour of Western Europe, the
president was reserved.
   ``I haven't given any thought at all to a meeting of the
chairman, Mr. Arafat, with an American official,'' Bush said at a
news conference.
   U.S. talks with the PLO were opened last month by then-President
Reagan. The U.S. ambassador to Tunisia, Robert Pelletreau, was
designated as the only official channel to the organization, some of
whose factions the State Department has charged with terrorism.
   Bush said he would ``wait to see how we go forward'' before
considering a high-level meeting.
   He acknowledged U.S. policy in the Middle East had changed with
the overture to the PLO. He said as long as the organization stayed
committed to Arafat's renunication of terrorism and acceptance of
Israel's right to exist ``we will have, when appropriate, meetings
with the PLO.''
   But asked if he would direct Secretary of State James A. Baker
III to meet with Arafat or another high-level official, Bush took a
cautious stance.
   ``I would wait to see how we go forward,'' Bush said. ``The point
of talking to them is to try to facilitate peace in the Middle East.
... If there are some logical steps that require high-level signoffs
by various participants over there then, and then only, would it be
proper to elevate the meetings to that level.''
   Bush added: ``We are just starting. ... You crawl before you
walk.''
   The president did not say what specific steps he required the PLO
to take before he would consider such a high-level meeting.
</TEXT>
