<FIRST>r w AM-Allen-CivilRights     01-27 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Allen-Civil Rights,000</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the U.S. Commission on Civil Rights
said Friday he hopes the panel will receive more attention from
President Bush than it did during the Reagan administration.
   Chairman William B. Allen said he hadn't heard directly from Bush
about any plans to elevate the stature of the commission or to boost
spending.
   However, Allen said, ``I would certainly urge it upon the
president to give greater attention to the Commission on Civil
Rights.''
   Asked how he would describe Bush's position on civil rights
issues, Allen said, ``I would not purport to speak on behalf of the
president. I think that he's capable of doing that himself.''
   ``I will say to you, however, that it seems to me Mr. Bush has
made it clear that he wishes to chart his own course, he wishes to
form his own reputation. And I believe we owe him the opportunity to
do just that,'' he said.
   Allen spoke at a forum sponsored by the Cato Institute, a
conservative think tank.
   In statements and meetings with black leaders, Bush has tried to
separate himself from the poor relationship that minority groups had
with the Reagan administration, in which he served as vice president
for eight years.
   During his news conference Friday, the president was asked about
the Supreme Court's affirmative action decision earlier this week
that drew criticism from many civil rights leaders.
   Bush told reporters the decision ``didn't kill all set-asides and
it didn't kill off affirmative action. I have been committed to
affirmative action.''
   He also said he wants to see reinvigorated programs by the Office
of Minority Business and the Small Business Administration.
   Allen, in an interview, sought to distance himself from the
criticism of the affirmative action ruling voiced by other civil
rights leaders.
   ``This ruling has a good deal more than has met the eyes of the
first people who looked at it,'' he said. ``It is not, in the first
place, an overturning of affirmative action. Quite the opposite, it
is a fairly emphatic reaffirmation of affirmative action as a remedy
available to Congress. ...
   ``In the second place, it is a statement that states and
municipalities may indeed also use racial preferences. But they are
required to do so only subject to strict scrutiny. They must be able
to prove either that they themselves were involved in
discrimination, or that others subject to their jurisdiction were
practicing discrimination,'' Allen said.
</TEXT>
