<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 1807EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Egypt-Taba     01-27 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Egypt-Taba,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Taba Talks End Without Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Egypt and Israel failed to reach an agreement on
a disputed beach resort in a second round of talks ending Friday,
representatives of both sides said.
   Egyptian officials announced this week they planned to declare
sovereignty over the Red Sea resort on Sunday.
   But Israeli Foreign Ministry spokesman Alon Liel said Friday that
Egypt apparently would tone down its original declaration and simply
announce Sunday that Egypt's Tourism Ministry is authorized to
handle talks on purchase of Taba's Israeli-owned luxury hotel.
   Israel says it wants more talks on ownership of the hotel and an
Israeli-owned resort village on the 250-acre strip. It says it also
wants more talks on ensuring access for Israeli tourists.
   Liel said the two sides discussed the issues but scheduled no new
talks.
   Nabil Arabi, head of the Egyptian delegation, said after the end
of talks Friday: ``We did not reach any agreement, and we're going
to report that back to our government.''
   Egyptian negotiators have argued that Egypt won sovereignty when
a panel of international arbitrators determined the location of a
series of border markers Sept. 29.
   But the Israelis argue that the arbitrators did not say how the
border should run from the last marker to the sea about 200 yards
away. If the border is extended in a straight line, Taba falls in
Egyptian territory. If it cuts back at a sharp angle, the resort
would be on Israeli land.
   Taba has been disputed since Israel refused to hand it back to
Egypt in 1982. Israel withdrew from the rest of the Sinai Peninsula
at that time under terms of the Israeli-Egyptian peace treaty.
   Israel captured the Sinai in the 1967 Middle East War.
</TEXT>
