<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Iran 440   01-27 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Iran, 440</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Says Iran Could Help Free Hostages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush asserted Friday that Iran could
influence the release of U.S. hostages in Lebanon and such a step
could help revive U.S.-Iranian ties.
   ``I don't want to ... think that the status quo has to go on
forever,'' Bush said of the defunct relationship between the two
countries.
   Speaking at a White House news conference, Bush said, ``... There
was a period of time when we had excellent relations with Iran.''
   At one pont, Bush said he wanted to make ``a broad appeal,
transcending Iran, to anybody that can be helpful to get the
hostages out.''
   Bush was queried about comments from Iran's president Ali
Khamenei, who criticized him for saying in his inaugural address
that Bush would appreciate help in gaining the release of the nine
Americans held hostage in Lebanon.
   ``It was America which expressed interest in resuming ties with
Iran; Iran does not need America,'' Tehran radio quoted Khamenei as
saying.
   Bush said he was unaware of the remarks.
   But stopping short of listing specific conditions for a renewal
of the diplomatic relations that were severed in early 1980, Bush
said Iran could make progress with the United States through ``the
renunciation of terror in any form, and facilitating to the degree
they can the release of the hostages.''
   Bush, when queried, said Iran was not holding the hostages,
adding that ``different groups'' were involved in their fate.
   But to the question of whether Iran exercised control over them,
Bush said the United States has ``varying degrees of intelligence on
that, various assessments as to how much control they have over
Hezbollah or these families or whoever it is.''
   Hezbollah is a pro-Iranian Moslem fundamentalist group that
operates in Lebanon, where the hostages are believed to be held.
   ``I would just reiterate my view that the way to improve
relations is to let them go, give these people their freedom _ they
didn't do anything wrong,'' Bush said.
   Asked if Iran could affect the hostages' release, he responded,
``I think they can have influence.''
   Ties between the United States and Iran were severed soon after
the 1979 Islamic revolution, when militant Iranian students took
over the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and held 52 Americans hostage for
444 days.
   Fifteen foreigners, including the nine Americans, are believed
held hostage in west Beirut by pro-Iranian factions.
   The hostage held longest is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press. He was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
</TEXT>
