<DOCNO> AP890127-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 1716EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-DetroitNewspapers     01-27 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Detroit Newspapers,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Clears Way for Partial Merger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court cleared the way Friday
for the partial merger of Detroit's two daily newspapers under an
exemption to anti-trust laws granted by then-Attorney General Edwin
Meese III.
   A split panel of the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here upheld
Meese's decision to allow the Detroit Free Press and The Detroit
News to form a joint operating agreement under the Newspaper
Preservation Act.
   Circuit Judge Laurence Silberman, writing for the 2-1 majority,
rejected arguments that Meese had arbitrarily overruled an
administrative law judge's findings that the two newspapers did not
qualify for the anti-trust exemption.
   Silberman said Meese's decision was ``based on a permissible
construction'' of the 1970 law empowering the attorney general to
let two newspapers form joint operating agreements after determining
that one of the dailies was in ``probable danger of financial
failure.''
   ``Congress ... delegated to the attorney general, not to us, the
delicate and troubling responsibility of putting content into the
ambiguous phrase, `probable danger of financial failure,''' the
appeals court ruling said.
   ``We cannot say that his interpretation of that phrase ... was
unreasonable,'' Silberman wrote in an opinion joined by Circuit
Judge Spottswood W. Robinso the same period, were unprofitably solely
because the two dailies had cut prices in an unsuccessful effort to
force each other out of business.
   Knight-Ridder has threatened to close the Free Press if the joint
operating agreement is not approved.
   ``This is clearly good news for the future of the Free Press,
good news for our readers and the people of Michigan,'' Free Press
publisher and chairman David Lawrence said in a statement. ``My hope
is that this decision will allow us to go forward soon,'' Lawrence
said.
   There was no immediate comment from Gannett Co. Inc., which owns
the News.
   In a separate order issued after the opinion, the circuit court
vacated a stay that prevented the merger from taking place while the
issue was under review. The ruling upheld a decision in September by
U.S. District Judge George Revercomb, who refused to enjoin the
merger.
   Meese approved the merger even though an administrative law judge
and the head of the Justice Department's anti-trust division
separately concluded that the Free Press did not qualify for the JOA
status.
   The administrative law judge held that once a JOA were denied,
the News would raise its prices, allowing the Free Press to follow
suit and return to financial solvency.
   Opponents seized on this conflict within the Justice Department,
but Silberman rejected their argument, saying Meese ``did not want
to play the high-stakes regulatory game that the law judge had
proposed.
   ``He obviously was concerned that if he gambled on'' the law
judge's prediction that both newspapers were bluffing, ``Detroit
would lose a newspaper,'' wrote Silberman.
   ``Both men relied upon the very same facts to make different
evaluations of the competitive strength of the Free Press,''
Silberman acknowledged. ``But, it is only the attorney general's
conclusions that have legal significance, and we cannot say that his
determination is unreasonable.''
</TEXT>
