<FIRST>r w AM-EducationSpending     01-27 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Education Spending,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Education Secretary Mum On Whether Bush Will Seeks More Funding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos told Congress
on Friday that President Bush is reworking next year's proposed
budget to incorporate education programs he espoused during the
campaign but was mum on whether Bush would seek more money.
   Cavazos, testifying at a Senate Labor Committee hearing, said a
high Bush education priority would be targeting federal education
money to disadvantaged kids and he said Bush is eager to prove his
campaign promise to be known as the ``education president.''
   But, under questioning from Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., who
called the hearing to discuss the role of the nation's schools in
training future workers, Cavazos was not specific about whether Bush
would recommend spending more on education in the next fiscal year
than the nearly $22 billion proposed by former President Reagan in
his farewell budget.
   Cavazos said he is working ``with the White House to shape that
budget. ... Many of the things that the president talked about
during the campaign hopefully will be reflected in that budget.''
Bush is expected to submit budget amendments to Congress next month.
   Among the Bush education priorities is encouraging school
districts to allow parents to choose the school their children
attend, a move Cavazos said would result in competition that would
expose poor schools.
   ``If it is not of high quality, it should not remain open,'' the
secretary said in his first appearance before the 101st Congress. In
an unusual move applauded by Kennedy, Cavazos, the first witness,
stayed to listen to other witnesses.
   Kennedy opened the hearing by saying that when adjusted to
account for inflation, federal education spending was below its 1980
level. He borrowed Bush campaign rhetoric in suggesting Bush could
prove his commitment by proposing an increase in education spending.
   ``With a new administration, perhaps we can fund education as if
our future depends on it _ because it does,'' said Kennedy, D-Mass.,
chairman of the committee. ``The road to a kinder, gentler nation
begins at the schoolhouse.''
</TEXT>
