<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-ColdWar     01-27 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Cold War,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Now Wants to Avoid Terms Like `Cold War'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an apparent change of heart, President Bush
said Friday he would not use the term ``Cold War'' to describe
relations between Washington and Moscow. He used exactly those words
seven months ago.
   ``I want to try to avoid words like `Cold War' if I can because
that has an implication,'' Bush said at a White House news
conference. ``If someone says `Cold War' to me, that doesn't
properly give credit to the advances that have taken place in this
relationship.
   ``So I wouldn't use that term. But if it's used in the context of
_ do we still have problems, are there still uncertainties, are we
still unsure of _ in our predictions on Soviet intentions, I'd have
to say yes, we should be cautious.''
   In a speech June 29 in San Francisco before the World Affairs
Council, a foreign policy group, Bush said:
   ``We've got to remember the Cold War is not over. We must be bold
enough to seize the opportunity of change but at the same time, as
one pundit titled his column, be prepared for `the protracted
conflict.'''
</TEXT>
