<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Press 1stLd-Writethru a0695 01-27 0685</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Press, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0695,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush at First News Conference: Easy-Going but Makes His Points</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 5th graf, The session, to give precise times</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barely a week into his new job, President Bush
proved himself deft at his first full-blown White House news
conference, making his points while keeping things light with an
easy-going style.
   Laughter was frequent as Bush, occasionally bantering with
reporters, showed the relaxed and upbeat demeanor he has maintained
since his election.
   Although Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater had said the conference
would run 15 or 20 minutes, noting that Bush had a cold and a raspy
voice, the president stood before the White House press corps for 43
minutes.
   ``I sound worse than I feel,'' Bush said as he stepped to the
podium.
   The session seemed to mark a departure from the pattern of Bush's
predecessor, President Reagan, whose news conferences were few and
far between. In his first week, Bush held an eight-minute
question-and-answer session with reporters in the Oval Office the
day after his inauguration, was interviewed for 12 minutes by two
reporters on behalf of the entire press corps and then conducted the
lengthy news conference.
   At one point Bush looked down at a digital watch on the podium
and laughingly counted down the seconds saying ``this thing is
buzzing away up here'' and suggesting he had to wrap things up.
   He then proceeded to take several more questions.
   At another juncture, following an answer he gave on Third World
debt, Bush admitted, ``I`m not sure I got to the substance of your
question there,'' and offered the reporter a chance to ask it again.
   The news conference at 11 a.m. EST Friday came as a surprise,
true to Bush's admitted efforts to keep the press corps off guard.
   It was announced by the White House press office on 15 minutes
notice, causing a scramble by camera crews, reporters and
photographers to set up in the room where Fitzwater conducts his
daily briefings.
   At one point Bush interrupted the flow to ask about the customary
practice of allowing follow-up questions by reporters after the
president answers their first one.
   He brought it up as a reporter sought a follow up a minimum-wage
question.
   ``Wait, let me ask you to stop the proceedings,'' Bush said
   ``What would be the fair and noble way to handle follow-up
questions as we do these things? Would it be good to have them or
not have them?'' Bush asked.
   Reporters said follow-ups are needed when the president doesn't
fully answer a question.
   ``You mean my first answer is less than precise?'' Bush said, to
chuckles.
   Gesturing to reporters lined up along the side of the room, he
noted that with the seated reporters getting two questions, ``the
standees have gotten no time at all.''
   Likewise, he said, referring to people sitting toward the back
near Dallas Morning News bureau chief Carl Leubsdorf, he said those
in ``the Leubsdorf area there (are) untested on the question.''
   The follow-ups became something of a running joke. When a
reporter shouted out a request to follow up on another person's
question on U.S.-Iran relations, Bush exclaimed in mock indignation,
``No, you don't get to follow his question!''
   A question about whether the president should limit pay raises
for his own staff if Congress approves a federal pay raise also
produced a light moment.
   Bush looked meaningfully over at senior staff members standing to
the side of the podium.
   Fitzwater, turning red, said laughingly, ``It's a trick question,
sir.''
   Bush did not flinch when asked a question that might have seemed
strange to many TV viewers.
   ``Did you find the note in your underwear drawer,'' a reporter
asked as part of a question on how his first week in the White House
had gone. A week earlier, Bush had indicated President Reagan, who
left him a written message in his Oval Office desk, might also have
left a note in the bedroom bureau.
   ``No note in the underwear, and it's been a good, easy week,''
Bush replied.
</TEXT>
