<FIRST>r a AM-Bundy-FBI     01-27 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bundy-FBI,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>FBI Plans Summit For Bundy Investigators</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bundy, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI on Friday said it will convene a meeting
in Quantico, Va., of law enforcement agents from around the country
in hopes of clearing up unsolved murders believed to have been
committed by Ted Bundy.
   Terry Green, an FBI major case specialist, declined to say how
many would be invited to the meeting, ``designed to answer a lot of
questions that have come up about whether Bundy may have been
involved in their particular cases.''
   The meeting will take place within three weeks if the schedules
of various investigators allow it, Green said.
   ``It's easier to answer if everybody is in one place so we can
discuss the peculiarities in each case,'' he said.
   In the days before his execution, Bundy, 42, confessed to 23
murders, including three in Washington to which he had not been
linked. Investigators believe he may have committed as many as 100
slayings beginning in 1969.
   Bundy has been linked to murders, solved and unsolved, in Oregon,
Idaho, Utah, Colorado, Florida, Vermont, New Jersey and Pennsylvania.
   Green works in the FBI's Violent Criminal Apprehension office in
Quantico, Va., a clearinghouse for unsolved homicides. ``We collect
reports and put investigators in touch with each other so they can
have joint investigations,'' he said.
   He confirmed that Robert Keppel, an investigator for the
Washington state attorney general's office who tracked Bundy for
more than a decade, was invited.
   Bundy was executed Tuesday at Florida State Prison for the 1978
rape-murder of 12-year-old Kimberly Leach of Lake City, Fla. He was
also sentenced to die for the 1978 murders of two sorority sisters
at Florida State University.
   Bundy pursued young women and girls, many of whom had dark hair
parted in the middle. Prosecutors said he preyed on their sympathy,
often gaining their confidence by using crutches or an arm sling and
asking them to carry things for him.
</TEXT>
