<FIRST>r w AM-Barry-CourtLeaks     01-27 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Barry-Court Leaks,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barry Lawsuit Charging Leaks Revived</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court on Friday revived a
lawsuit by Mayor Marion Barry Jr. in which he alleged that Joseph E.
diGenova, at the time the U.S. attorney for the District of
Columbia, leaked to the media testimony from grand jury probes into
possible corruption in Barry's administration.
   Barry's original suit, in which he sought to bar diGenova from
any further leaks to reporters, was dismissed by U.S. District Court
Judge Aubrey Robinson in 1987 after Robinson ruled that Barry had
failed to provide his contentions.
   Federal law stipulates that ``an attorney for the government ...
shall not disclose matters occurring before the grand jury.''
   On Friday, however, Judge Harry T. Edwards of the Court of
Appeals for the District of Columbia cited news stories quoting
``law-enforcement officials familiar with (Mayor Barry's)
testimony,'' and ruled that Barry had compiled enough evidence to
warrant granting him a hearing on the matter.
   Edwards' said diGenova and his associates must now respond,
``because they are in the best position to know whether (they are)
responsible for a violation'' of the rule barring grand jury leaks.
   The former U.S. attorney, now in private practice, said he would
not comment without reading the opinion.
   If, during the course of the hearing, diGenova or other federal
officials are found to have leaked grand jury testimony to the
media, they could face contempt of court charges. Edwards said,
however, that it was uncertain whether the officials could face
criminal or civil charges in connection with the matter.
</TEXT>
