<FIRST>u i AM-Poland 2ndLd-Writethru   01-27 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0748,0658</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity Leaders Meet with Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with date set on talks. Pick up
8th pvs, `Among those...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leaders and top government
officials on Friday agreed to meet Feb. 6 for talks to address
political and economic freedom and the future of the banned
independent union.
   ``I am satisfied and very tired. I made hours of overtime,''
Solidarity leader Lech Walesa told reporters waiting outside the
Roman Catholic Episcopate, where Walesa is staying.
   A joint communique announcing the date of the talks was carried
by the state-run news agency PAP.
   ``The meeting discussed the problems of trade union pluralism,
including Solidarity, and other problems which will be the subject
of the round-table talks,'' the communique said.
   It said a preliminary decision to set up three working teams for
economic and social policy, political reforms and union pluralism
had been taken.
   Participants also agreed to set up committees to deal with
agriculture, mining, reform of law and the courts, associations,
self-government, mass media and youth, the communique said.
   Walesa and a group of other Solidarity leaders and senior
advisers returned to the Episcopate by bus after holding nearly 12
hours of talks with government officials.
   They conferred in a secluded house in the woods of Magdalenka, a
Warsaw suburb, to lay the groundwork for the more elaborate
negotiations on such topics as political and economic freedom and
union pluralism.
   The last category will address the future of Solidarity, which
Walesa founded at the Lenin shipyard in Gdansk during the labor
turmoil of August 1980.
   At first, the communist authorities accepted Solidarity as the
first free trade union in the Soviet bloc, but then suppressed and
outlawed it after martial law was imposed in 1981. Walesa, who won
the 1983 Nobel Peace Prize, still works as an electrician at the
shipyard.
   Among those attending with Walesa were Bishop Tadeusz Goclowski
of Gdansk; Zbigniew Bujak, leader of the former Solidarity
underground; Mieczyslaw Gil, Solidarity chairman at the Nowa Huta
steel mill in Krakow, and Wladyslaw Frasyniuk, a Solidarity leader
from Wroclaw in the southwest.
   Also in the group were three of Walesa's closest advisers:
Catholic journalist Tadeusz Mazowiecki, historian Bronislaw Geremek
and lawyer Andrzej Stelmachowski.
   The government did not identify its delegates, but national
Solidarity spokesman Janusz Onyszkiewicz said they included Interior
Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak, Politburo member Stanislaw Ciosek
and the deputy chief of official trade unions, Romuald Sosnowski.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Stefan Staniszewski said Thursday the
main negotiations with opposition groups ``should begin in the next
few days.'' In response to a question, he called Feb. 5 ``very
probable,'' but then said that was a Sunday and Feb. 6 was more
likely.
   Jacek Moskwa, a spokesman for the opposition, said its
headquarters would be in space the Warsaw University administration
offered to a committee of activists Walesa formed in January.
   Walesa traveled to Warsaw by train Thursday and met with senior
advisers, but no details were released. Solidarity said he would
hold a news conference Saturday.
   Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski's government made the offer of talks
with the opposition during strikes in August that were the worst in
Poland since martial law crushed Solidarity.
   Walesa has traveled to Warsaw four times for talks with senior
government officials. After the last meeting Nov. 19, he said he
would not agree to the larger negotiations until a political
decision was made to legalize the union.
   The Communist Party Central Committee made a dramatic policy
reversal on the matter last week, approving a proposal that more
than one legal trade union be permitted and opposition groups be
allowed to participate in government organizations.
   At a meeting Sunday in Gdansk, the Solidarity leadership agreed
to negotiate with the government on legalizing the union.
</TEXT>
