<FIRST>r i AM-Haiti     01-27 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haiti,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers Beat Workers; Hundreds Demonstrate In Gonaives</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Soldiers wielding billy clubs
brutally dispersed about 600 laid-off workers who had gathered
outside a government office Friday to collect severance pay, Radio
Haiti Inter said.
   In another development, several hundred youths set up barricades
of burning tires and shouted anti-government slogans Friday morning
in the northern port city of Gonaives before police scattered them
with tear gas, the independent station reported.
   The town returned to normal by early afternoon, the station said.
   Many residents of Gonaives, 100 miles north of Port-au-Prince,
were angered by the military government's decision last month to
crack down on smuggling, the livelihood of hundreds of middlemen in
Haiti's provincial port cities.
   Since a nationwide 24-hour general strike paralyzed most of Haiti
on Jan. 17, small, sporadic anti-government demonstrations and
strikes have erupted in several small provincial towns, called by
teachers demanding back pay, truckers demanding road repairs and
youths denouncing unpopular officials.
   The 600 workers in Port-au-Prince, mostly women, were recently
laid off by Amtex Inc., an assembly plant. They gathered in front of
a Social Affairs Ministry branch office in Delmas, on the capital's
north side, to negotiate severance pay.
   In what appeared to be an unprovoked attack, two truckloads of
soldiers from the notoriously repressive Dessalines Barracks arrived
and beat people with billy clubs, bruising many and bludgeoning a
pregnant woman, Haiti Inter said.
   No one was arrested, and no serious injuries were reported, the
radio said.
   Social Affairs Minister Arnold Guerrier said he was investigating
the incident.
</TEXT>
