<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Baker     01-27 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Baker,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush: Big Plans for Baker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Friday Secretary of State
James A. Baker III would advance ``bold, new initiatives'' in
foreign policy.
   At a ceremonial swearing-in in the East Room of the White House,
Bush praised his longtime friend and fellow Texan, saying, ``he's
savvy, he's sensitive, he's tough.''
   Before an audience of about 200 persons, including congressional
leaders and family members, Baker took the oath of office
administered by Chief Justice William Rehnquist.
   Actually, the ceremony was just for show. Baker actually was
sworn in Wednesday night in a short ceremony at the State Department
following his Senate confirmation.
   Presiding at that ceremony was deputy executive White House clerk
Daniel J. Marks.
   Bush called Friday's ceremony ``a very special occasion for me,''
citing a friendship with Baker that began in Houston in the 1960s.
   ``I have great confidence in him. And, judging from the way he
sailed through the confirmation process, the United States Senate
shares that confidence,'' he said.
   He said Baker would be ``my principal foreign policy adviser.''
   In brief remarks, Bush recalled his pledge in his inaugural for a
``new engagement.''
   ``Nowhere is the need for new engagement greater than in foreign
policy,'' he said. ``The world demands new strategies and new
solutions.''
   Saying that ``totalitarian forces still threaten to undermine the
will of the people,'' Bush said: ``We must keep democracy on the
march.''
   ``This is the time for America to reach out and take the lead,
not merely react,'' he said, describing Baker's role as ``leading,
coming up with bold new initiatives.''
   Baker, noting he and Bush had ``come a long distance together,''
said the more he learns about the job, ``the more humble I become.''
   ``We're entering a new era of international relations, one that's
filled with more than its share of promise and perhaps more than its
share of perils as well,'' Baker said.
   Baker, who served as chief of staff and Treasury secretary in the
Reagan administration, joked that from experience he knows that
``after the swearing-in, comes the swearing at.''
   He also said he hoped he and Bush would do better as a
foreign-policy team ``than we did on the tennis courts in Texas.''
</TEXT>
