<FIRST>u a AM-SecondAssault     01-27 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Second Assault,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stepfather Admits 2nd Assault of Leukemia Victim While On Bail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who pleaded guilty in September to sexually
assaulting his leukemia-stricken 9-year-old stepdaughter has
admitted molesting her again while awaiting sentencing.
   The 31-year-old man admitted the offense in court Thursday in an
agreement with the prosecutor not to press charges. Prosecutor
Marshall Gandy said he agreed in order to spare the sick girl the
rigors of testifying at a trial.
   The first assault occurred as the child was resting from a
chemotherapy session that left her weakened, authorities said.
   The second assault took place Nov. 1 when the man, under court
order to stay away from the girl, was babysitting her, according to
testimony Thursday. At the time, the man was free on $5,000 bail,
set by a magistrate.
   Two caseworkers with the Texas Department of Human Services had
testified in October that the man was likely to be a repeat offender.
   Prosecutors criticized District Judge Frances J. Maloney for
twice delaying sentencing after the September guilty plea. The judge
did not return telephone calls Friday.
   After the second offense, Maloney ordered the man jailed on
$500,000 bail. The stepfather's name has not been released to
protect the identity of the girl.
   Aggravated sexual assault of a child is a punishable by life in
prison.
   Maloney, who delayed sentencing in September pending a
psychological review of the man and delayed it again because of
scheduling conflicts, on Thursday set sentencing for Feb. 13, this
time at defense attorney Fred Talkington's request.
   Talkington said he sought the delay so he could schedule
testimony from a psychologist. The defense attorney said he will
seek probation for the man because prison offers nothing ``that can
help him with this problem.''
