<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 1901EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ImmigrationDiscrimination     01-27 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Immigration Discrimination,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Says 16 Percent of Employers Discriminating</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Employers are discriminating against
``foreign-looking'' job seekers at an ``alarmingly high level'' and
many businesses don't understand the 1986 immigration changes, 10
congressmen said Friday.
   The lawmakers based their complaints on a study by the General
Accounting Office that found 16 percent of employers surveyed
admitted to engaging in discriminatory hiring practices, such as
asking only ``foreign-looking'' people for work authorization
documents and hiring only U.S. citizens.
   The GAO, an investigating arm of Congress, estimated this means
as many as 528,000 employers nationwide are engaging in unfair
employment practices, the congressmen said in a letter to Attorney
General Dick Thornburgh.
   The study also found that 22 percent of 4.2 million employers in
the GAO survey population were not aware of the sanctions against
knowingly hiring undocumented workers, and of those who were aware
of the law, 20 percent did not understand its major provisions.
   ``There seems to be a strong relationship between lack of
information on employer sanctions and discriminatory behavior,'' the
congressmen said.
   While the 1986 immigration reform law bars employers from hiring
undocumented workers, it makes it against the law for employers to
discriminate against eligible job seekers.
   ``We are especially concerned about the GAO's claim that its
findings do not show a `pattern' of discrimination,'' the
congressmen told Thornburgh. ``This interpretation, in our view, is
less important than the report's clear evidence that discrimination
is occurring at an alarmingly high level. This is an unacceptable
situation.''
   Signing the letter were Democratic Reps. Albert Bustamante of
Texas; Esteban Torres, Ronald Dellums, Edward Roybal, Mervyn
Dymally, Robert Matsui, Norman Mineta, and Matthew Martinez of
California; and Edolphus Towns and Robert Garcia of New York.
   Also signing were Democrats Jaime Fuster, Puerto Rico's
congressional resident commissioner, and Ron de Lugo, congressional
delegate from the Virgin Islands.
</TEXT>
