<DOCNO> AP890127-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 1907EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DamTurbines     01-27 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dam Turbines,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court: Corps Can Install But Not Operate Turbines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court says the Army
Corps of Engineers may install a controversial type of turbine at a
hydroelectric dam but can't use the equipment until an environmental
lawsuit is settled.
   In a decision issued in Richmond, Va., on Tuesday, the court gave
the corps the go-ahead to proceed with construction on the $57.2
million project on the Richard Russell Dam.
   But the court left intact a lower-court injunction against
testing or using the turbines once they are installed.
   The dam is on the Savannah River on the Georgia-South Carolina
border, roughly 75 northwest of Augusta, Ga.
   The ruling came in a lawsuit brought by the South Carolina
Wildlife Department, the National Wildlife Federation and the
federation's South Carolina and Georgia affiliates.
   They had sought to keep the ``pump-storage'' turbines out of the
dam altogether, arguing that the devices, which send water that
flows through them back over a dam to generate additional
electricity, can cause widespread fish kills.
   In May, U.S. District Judge Falcon Hawkins issued an injunction
blocking both installation and use of the turbines until a
supplemental environmental impact statement is completed. The corps
appealed the injunction.
   But the three-member appeals panel said installation alone will
cause no environmental damage.
   Jim Parker, spokesman for the Army Corps' Savannah District, said
the agency is ``pleased to be able to move forward with the
installation.'' He said the corps believes it will be able to
operate the turbines without hurting the environment.
   Ellison Smith, attorney for the environmentalists, said the order
means the court still has review power over the project.
   The corps ``can do everything but turn them on and test them,''
he said.
   Parker said corps officials will meet next week to get a better
idea of when the project, originally scheduled for completion next
year, might be finished and how much the delay has cost.
</TEXT>
