<HEAD>Government Says Guerrilla Gorriaran Merlo Staged La Tablada Attack</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS with two grafs to ADD Somoza's nationality. Pick up 3rd
pvs, ``His participation...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have raided 50 homes as
they hunt for a prominent leftist extremist who led an assault on an
infantry base that left 38 people dead, officials said Friday.
   The government said it believes Monday's attack was led by
Enrique Gorriaran Merlo, who claimed he took part in the Sept. 17,
1980, assassination of deposed Nicaraguan dictator Anastasio Somoza.
   ``His participation is presumed, taking into account his former
guerrilla activity, his training and the connection he had in recent
times with (leftist groups),'' said Attorney General Andres
D'Alessio.
   Gorriaran Merlo, 47, is a former leader of the Peoples
Revolutionary Army leftist group that battled Argentina's army in
open combat in the 1970s. The guerrilla army was decimated.
   Gorriaran Merlo has been wanted by Argentine police for years.
President Raul Alfonsin ordered his prosecution shortly after taking
office five years ago, but the guerrilla was thought to have fled
the country.
   On Monday, about 60 heavily armed civilian commandos burst onto
and briefly controlled the 3rd Infantry Regiment at La Tablada on
the outskirts of Buenos Aires. Hundreds of soldiers routed the band
after a 27-hour battle in which 28 guerrillas were killed and 18
captured. Ten police and soldiers also died.
   ``We know that in this attack more people participated than were
killed or arrested,'' D'Alessio said. Acknowledging public concerns
that the group might strike again, he added:
   ``We know that an armed group that suffers a public defeat of
this size in general sees it as necessary to do something to
demonstrate it's still in condition to keep operating.''
   Alfonsin blamed the attack on leftist subversives, basing the
charge in part on the identification of bodies of those arrested as
former members of the Peoples Revolutionary Army.
   Two of the 17 men and three women who were captured Monday and
Tuesday have been released, D'Alessio said, and two others have been
jailed as a result of the raids.
   Police said they raided 50 homes since the attack and intend to
seek information and evidence in at least 100 other homes.
   Weapons were seized at some of the homes, D'Alessio said. At
least a dozen people picked up for questioning have been released.
   Arrest warrants have been issued for five people, including
Gorriaran Merlo, D'Alessio said. He would not identify the other
four.
</TEXT>
