<FIRST>r a AM-FiredChaplain     01-27 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fired Chaplain,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Pink Slips Reform School Chaplain In Budget Cutback</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State officials have fired the only
paid chaplain at a juvenile detention center in Westfield, saying
the state can no longer afford to pay him $49.20 pay for a one-hour,
weekly counseling session.
   ``It's not the $49.20, but the shabby treatment of the chaplaincy
that bothers me,'' the Rev. Benjamin Lockhart, a 71-year-old retired
minister who served the lockup for 27 years, said Friday.
   ``We are engaged in a serious piece of business and it kind of
makes you wonder what people think is important when they will pay a
painter, but not a clergyman,'' he said.
   George Ashwell, a Division of Youth Services administrator in
Springfield who oversees the Westfield center, said Lockhart, who
puts in about an hour a week, was the only contract employee let go
at the detention center because of cuts in consultant budget
accounts ordered by Gov. Michael S. Dukakis.
   The cuts are part of a package of measures proposed by Dukakis to
help the state meet a $600 million shortfall in the current fiscal
year's $11.2 billion budget.
   ``I do not feel that the general public wants the budget to be
balanced on the backs of the chaplains,'' Lockhart said in a letter
to center officials, the governor and state legislators. ``Westfield
Detention Center, which deals with troubled youth, needs more, not
less chaplaincy service.''
   Ashwell said that one other Protestant clergyman has served as a
volunteer at the Westfield center and lay members of other church
groups have also visited the youths.
   The detention center houses 24 juveniles facing criminal charges.
   Elizabeth Dowd, a spokeswoman for youth services Commissioner
Edward J. Loughran, said Friday that because of the state's fiscal
crisis, the department had to eliminate ``a number of managerial and
other employees.''
   ``We felt that since (Lockhart) only spent an hour a week at the
facility and the services were covered by other volunteers, we could
eliminate that contract,'' Dowd said.
   She said that she did not know how many employees had been fired,
but she believed chaplains for at least two other institutions were
also let go.
   Lockhart agreed that the session he spends with troubled youths
lasts only about an hour, but said he was angry that ``they sent me
a letter on Saturday telling me not to show up on Sunday.''
   He charged that when he went to the youth home last Sunday as a
volunteer, he was barred from entering, which Ashwell denied.
   After formal Protestant and Catholic services were discontinued
at the youth center some time ago, Lockhart said, he instead met
weekly with from four to eight youths.
   ``We would talk about various things out of the Bible,'' he said.
``You try to bring hope to them, turn them around. These people have
fouled up their lives and they need someone to help them get back.
But if you are on the outside you can't do that.''
   Lockhart served as minister of a Baptist church in Agawam for
many years and prior to his retirement, he was Protestant chaplain
at the Hampden County jail for 30 years.
</TEXT>
