<FIRST>r w AM-NuclearPlant     01-27 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Plant,1st ld-writethru, a0729,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Department Denies Seeking To Ease Nuclear Safety Rule</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 8th graf to include Ahearne's first name</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department denied Friday it is
considering lowering a safety standard to make it easier to restart
a South Carolina nuclear reactor that produces a scarce gas needed
to make nuclear warheads.
   Gary Pitchford, a department spokesman at the Savannah River
Plant near Aiken, S.C., said ``some in the department'' have
supported the idea of changing the safety standard, but not as a
means of speeding the reactor restart.
   Pitchford stressed that other persons in the department opposed
the change in safety standards, and the idea is not being considered
in connection with a Savannah River restart. He and other officials
said the idea has been studied for several years both at Savannah
River and in the commercial nuclear industry.
   ``There is no consideration being given to changing the (safety
standard) for the restart of the `K' reactor,'' Pitchford said in a
telephone interview. The ``K'' reactor was shut down last spring to
make repairs and to retrain operators.
   The New York Times, in its Friday editions, reported that the
chairman of a nuclear safety advisory panel had told a Senate
committee the Energy Department was considering relaxing the safety
standard in order to speed the reopening of reactors at Savannah
River, which is the nation's only source of tritium.
   Tritium is a perishable gas that is critical to the production of
nuclear warheads. Savannah River has been unable to produce tritium
since last spring, and the Energy Department has said the plant may
not be reopened before year's end.
   The plant is operated under Energy Department contract by E.I. du
Pont de Nemours &amp; Co.
   The Times quoted John Ahearne as saying the department's office
at Savannah River was ``trying very hard to make the case'' that the
current definition of the worst possible reactor accident _ a
complete break in a cooling pipe _ was unrealistic. Ahearne was
reported to have said department officials proposed that the minimum
safety standard be based on the danger posed by a leak in the pipe
rather than a full break.
   The ``leak-before-break'' standard, if applied at Savannah River,
would make it easier for du Pont _ and Westinghouse Electric Corp.,
which takes over as operator April 1 _ to get Energy Department
approval for a reactor restart plan.
   In a telephone interview on Friday, however, Ahearne said he had
told the Senate panel that du Pont officials _ not the Energy
Department _ were pushing for adoption of the ``leak-before-break''
safety standard. He also said he had not asserted that the du Pont
plan was aimed at speeding up the reactor restart.
   Ahearne said department safety officials were ``very, very
skeptical'' of the idea.
   Clif Webb, a du Pont spokesman at Savannah River, said Friday
that the company had been studying the ``leak-before-break''
question for a few years but had not yet reached an official
corporate position on whether it should be applied at Savannah River.
   Webb also denied that the study was aimed at speeding up the
reactor reopening.
   Ahearne, chairman of the Energy Department's Advisory Committee
on Nuclear Facility Safety, said his panel last December had
reviewed du Pont's scientific work and concluded it was ``a long
way'' from justifying the lower safety standard.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
