<DOCNO> AP890127-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 1943EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-US     01-27 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-US,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan Rips Tower Attack On Defense Budget</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan on Friday criticized U.S. Defense
Secretary-designate John Tower's call for more pressure on Tokyo to
increase its military spending and said the country is doing its
share to bolster its defense.
   Tower's remarks during Senate confirmation hearings virtually
guaranteed that the issue of Japan's share of the burden for its
defense will come up during Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita's
Washington visit next week.
   ``U.S.-Japan defense arrangements have been a pillar of Japan's
security and we have been making efforts toward our defense under
this framework, and such a policy has been widely trusted by the
people,'' Defense Agency Director General Kichiro Tazawa told
reporters.
   Tazawa said Tower's comment that Japan could greatly increase its
defense spending despite its constitution, which restricts its
military to defensive capabilities, reflected a lack of
understanding of the Japanese perspective.
   ``I regret that Mr. Tower went so far as to refer to our
constitution to push us to expand our defense spending,'' Tazawa
said.
   A senior Foreign Ministry official said there was no need for
Takeshita to apologize for Japan's defense spending, given its
recent efforts to increase its military and overseas development
assistance budgets.
   ``The government's proposal for the new budget has a remarkable
5.9 percent increase in the defense budget and 7.8 percent for
(foreign aid). We are doing very fine in our own view,'' said Yukio
Okamoto, director of the Foreign Ministry's First North American
division.
   Washington has urged Japan to do more for its own defense _
especially to improve its ability to defend crucial sea-lanes _ but
military spending is controversial here. The Japanese constitution,
adopted in 1946 during the U.S. occupation, renounces war and
forbids the use of force in settling international disputes.
   In confirmation hearings in the Senate Armed Services Committee
on Wednesday, Tower said the decision to inflict a constitution that
severely restrained Japan from building a substantial military force
during the U.S. occupation was ``a lousy idea.''
   ``But I don't believe that constitution is so restraining that
they couldn't devote a substantially larger percentage (of spending)
to their defense,'' Tower said.
   Japan has been steadily building up its armed forces in recent
years. The government this week approved a budget for fiscal 1989
that includes $30.5 billion for defense spending. The budget must be
passed by Parliament.
   The new budget raises Tokyo's share of the cost of keeping 55,000
U.S. troops in Japan to $1.11 billion, about 75 percent of the total
cost.
   Its economic assistance to developing countries is likely to
exceed $11 billion, making it the world's largest donor of foreign
aid.
   By 1990, Japan's defense spending, which is increasing more than
5 percent annually, will exceed that of most of the European allies,
a Pentagon official said recently.
   The proposed 1989 defense budget amounts to slightly more than 1
percent of Japan's gross national product. The United States devotes
about 6 percent to military spending and the European allies 3
percent to 4 percent.
   He said the U.S.-Japan summit next week was intended mainly to
allow Bush and Takeshita to develop closer relations and discuss
global issues. He said Takeshita did not expect to discuss specific
issues with Bush.
   ``We think there is a full understanding of our policy by the
U.S. government,'' Okamoto said. ``We will continue to point to our
record of success in this field.''
</TEXT>
