<FIRST>r a AM-MiamiRiots     01-27 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Miami Riots,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Rep. Conyers: Profound Injustice in Miami</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANDRA WALEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressman, after touring the scene of Miami's
three nights of riots, promised Friday to turn around the ``legacy
of broken promises'' to the area and help secure federal funds.
   ``The injustice here is so profound that everyone in America
knows there's something very wrong here,'' said U.S. Rep. John
Conyers, D-Michigan.
   Conyers, chairman of the Government Operations Committee and a
member of the Judiciary subcommittee on civil and constitutional
rights, said he was on a quest for justice.
   ``There are too many trigger-happy policemen abusing the rights
of black people in this area,'' said Conyers, who was invited to
Miami by Raymond Fauntroy, head of the local Southern Christian
Leadership Conference chapter.
   Conyers said he would help coordinate relief for predominantly
black Overtown, where the fatal shooting of a black motorcyclist by
a Hispanic police officer a week ago triggered three days of
burning, looting and violence.
   The unrest spilled over into the Liberty City area, and left one
dead, 11 wounded by gunfire and about $1 million damage to buildings.
   ``Overtown has been shorted,'' Conyers said. ``The question is
how did it happen and what we can do.''
   Earlier, the congressman met with Miami Mayor Xavier Suarez, who
called Conyers a ``foremost expert on the issue of race relations.''
   Conyers also met with about 125 residents at a meeting held on
the same block where the riots broke out.
   He said at the meeting that federal aid promised by the Carter
administration after the 1980 riots, which were sparked by the
beating death of a black motorcyclist by police officers, was cut by
the Reagan administration.
   For example, he said of $40 million in loans promised for small
business owners, $16 million was sent. He said of $10 million for
low-income housing, $2 million was sent.
   At the meeting, Patricia Lloyd, sister of the slain motorcyclist,
said said the officer who shot her brother Clement should face a
charge more serious than manslaughter. ``I'd like to see him charged
with murder,'' she said.
   Patrolman William Lozano is free on $10,000 bond, charged with
two counts of manslaughter in the deaths of Lloyd, 23, and Allan
Blanchard, 24, his passenger who died of injuries in an ensuing
crash.
   Clement ``was shot in cold blood,'' she said, but prosecutors
have said the shooting did not meet legal thresholds for first- or
second-degree murder charges.
   A police union leader said at the meeting more black officers
should be patrolling the city's predominantly black neighborhoods.
   ``Black people in the community are demanding it,'' said Officer
Sam Harlan, president of the Miami Community Police Benevolent
Association.
   Eighteen percent of the officers in the Miami Police Department
are black. Anglos account for 39 percent and Hispanics 43 percent.
City officials say the composition of the force meets federal
affirmative action guidelines and reflects Miami's population.
</TEXT>
