<FIRST>r a AM-EmergencyLanding-Fatigue     01-27 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Emergency Landing-Fatigue,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>NTSB Says Metal Fatigue Caused Piedmont Flight to Drop Engine After
Takeoff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fatigued metal in a bolt cracked, causing an
engine to fall off a Piedmont Airlines jet minutes after takeoff
last week, federal investigators concluded Thursday.
   The fracture of a back bolt put the front two bolts under stress
and caused their eventual fracture, said James Kolstad, acting
chairman of the National Transportation Safety Board.
   His conclusion came in a letter to T. Allan McArtor,
administrator of the Federal Aviation Administration.
   ``There are several ways it (fatigue) could have happened,'' said
William Bruce, who is heading the NTSB investigation. ``What caused
the fatigue is what we're looking for.''
   Bruce said the investigation, which typically takes nine months,
is continuing.
   The right engine tore away from the Boeing 737 jet as Piedmont
Airlines Flight 1480 left O'Hare International Airport on Friday.
The engine fell in a field at the airport.
   The control tower told the pilot to return to O'Hare, but tapes
released this week showed the pilot never fully realized the problem
until the plane was back on the ground minutes later. None of the 27
passengers or six crew members were injured.
   The incident was the second of its kind involving a Boeing
737-200 series jet in the last 13 months.
   Last January, the government ordered airlines to inspect
engine-mount bolts on Boeing 737-200 series aircraft after an engine
fell off a USAir flight shortly after takeoff from Philadelphia.
   No one was hurt in that incident and the engine landed in an open
field.
   The Boeing 737-200 series jet has two engines, one mounted under
each wing and secured to the wing at the front by two bolts and at
the back by a single bolt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
