<FIRST>u i AM-Arafat     01-27 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arafat,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arafat Says PLO Has Asked Bush To `Turn Over New Leaf'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN LINNEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yasser Arafat said Friday the PLO has
contacted President Bush and asked him and his administration to
change U.S. policy in the Middle East.
   The chairman of the Palestine Liberation Organization, at his
first meeting with representatives of the European Economic
Community, earlier met with three European foreign ministers and
discussed ways to promote an international peace conference on the
Middle East.
   Arafat has traveled to Stockholm, Vienna, Athens and Helsinki on
a campaign to portray the PLO as a moderate organization working
through diplomatic channels for the establishment of an independent
Palestinian state.
   He told a news conference the PLO made contact with Bush after
his Jan. 20 inauguration and that it asked his administration to
``turn over a new leaf'' on Middle East policy.
   The United States agreed in December to meet with the PLO after
Arafat recognized Israel and renounced terrorism.
   Arafat, speaking in a mixture of Arabic and English with Spanish
translation, said the U.S. ambassador to Tunisia, Robert Pelletreau,
and a PLO representative in Tunis have had ``permanent contacts''
since their first meeting Dec. 16. He would not say how many
contacts they had or when the next meeting would take place.
   Arafat blamed former President Reagan's ational Council, the PLO's
parliament-in-exile, declared an independent Palestinian state in
the Israeli-occupied lands.
   Arafat reportedly put out feelers on EEC recognition for the
state during the meeting with Fernandez Ordonez, French Foreign
Minister Roland Dumas and Greek Foreign Minister Carolos Papoulias,
but did not make a formal request.
   Ordonez sidestepped the question of EEC recognition by saying it
was a matter for member states to decide individually.
   The Israeli Foreign Ministry said Friday it was ``gravely
disappointed'' by the meeting. Israel has a policy of refusing to
negotiate with the PLO.
   Arafat was asked Friday what he thought about municipal elections
in the occupied territories. He replied: ``Isn't one experience
enough? Have you forgotten what happened the last time when some
were assassinated and some had their legs blown off?''
   He said the PLO would back internationally supervised elections
when Israel ends its occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Since an uprising by Palestinians in the occupied territories
began 13 months ago, more than 360 Palestinians and 15 Israelis have
been killed.
