<FIRST>r w AM-Angola 1stLd-writethru a0794 01-27 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Angola, 1st Ld-writethru, a0794,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs lead to eliminate extraneous words</HEAD>
<HEAD>US Talking To Angola</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. government is talking about formally
improving communications with Angola and may establish a small
mission in Luanda, State Department spokesman Charles Redman said
Friday.
   Redman stressed the office would lack diplomatic status and would
be limited to attempts to bring peace to southwestern africa.
   Redman was responding to reports that the two nations had started
talks about creating low-level missions in Washington and Luanda.
   ``We have discussed with them how such an improvement in
communication might be achieved, and we would expect these
discussions to continue,'' Redman said.
   ``However, there's been no change in our policy of
non-recognition, and no diplomatic relations with the Angolan
government; and there is no plan to change that policy,'' he noted.
   He was asked whether that would rule out ``interest sections,'' a
level of diplomatic relations below embassies.
   ``It would rule out anything at the so-called `diplomatic
level,''' said Redman. ``The kind of thing that you are referring to
is a possible idea, which has been that you might have a couple of
Americans on the ground to help monitor the implementation of the
peace accords.''
   Redman said American and Angolan authorities had ``for many
years, had bilateral contacts in the context of the southwestern
African peace process. Those contacts will continue, especially
within the framework of the Joint Commission, whose first session
took place in New York this week.''
   He was referring to the commission established in connection with
South African agreement to grant independence to Namibia, or
South-West Africa, in exchange for a Cuban troop withdrawal from
neighboring Angola.
   ``U.S. participation in the Joint Commission and our overall
interest in monitoring compliance by all parties with the New York
accords point to the need for improved communication between the
U.S. and the Angolan regime,'' Redman said.
   He said the United States is standing by its two conditions for
establishing diplomatic relations with leftist-controlled Angola _
Cuban troop withdrawal and national reconciliation. The latter
phrase is diplomatic shorthand for the U.S. position seeking a
settlement between the Angolan government and U.S.-backed UNITA
guerrillas.
   ``The authorities in Luanda obviously have it in their power to
address both these issues in ways that could lead to positive
evolution of relations with the United States,'' Redman said.
``Those are the essential factors that would affect the future
evolution of contacts between the U.S. and Luanda.''
</TEXT>
