<FIRST>r i AM-Canada-Chess     01-27 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Chess,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yusupov-Spraggett Match Tied At 2.5 Each</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>QUEBEC (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fifth game of the World Chess Championship
Candidates quarterfinal between Artur Yusupov of the Soviet Union
and Canadian Grandmaster Kevin Spraggett ended in a 32-move draw
Friday.
   The score stands tied at 2.5-2.5 with only one game remaining.
   Yusupov, playing white against a Queens Indian defense, gained a
small spatial advantage from the opening, but failed to penetrate
Spraggett's rock-solid defenses.
   Canadian experts, bouyed by their man's return to form after a
loss and a lackluster draw in the third and fourth games, said
Spraggett has chances to defeat the 28-year-old prematch favorite
and become the first North American since Bobby Fischer to reach the
semifinal stage.
   ``It may be in the sixth game, it may be in the playoff, but
either way I think Spraggett is going to win,'' said Brian
Nickoloff, a Canadian international master.
   The winner of the candidates, a series of knockout matches, will
challenge world champion Garri Kasparov for his world title in 1990.
   If the sixth game, scheduled for Sunday with Spraggett playing
with the advantage of white, is drawn, two further games on Tuesday
and Thursday will be played, followed by sudden death tiebreakers at
increasingly high speeds.
   Spraggett, a 34-year-old from Montreal who is ranked only 35th in
the world, rose to prominence in the previous stage, when he knocked
out Soviet Grandmaster Andrei Sokolov in a hair-raising time
scramble in which each player was allowed only 15 minutes thinking
time for the whole game.
   British Grandmaster Jonathan Speelman is the only player so far
through to the semifinals.
   If the Spraggett-Yusupov match goes into extra time, all three
undecided contests will be in progress around the globe
simultaneously.
   The first game in the quarterfinal duel between former world
champion Anatoly Karpov of the Soviet Union, who is strongly
favored, and Icelandic Grandmaster Johann Hjartarson is scheduled
for Saturday in Seattle.
   In the fourth quarterfinal, Dutch Grandmaster Jan Timman will
face off against Lajos Portisch of Hungary beginning Wednesday.
</TEXT>
