<FIRST>r i AM-China-Movie     01-27 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Movie,0374</SECOND>
<HEAD>`China's First Sex Movie' Disappoints Audiences</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The director of what was billed in advance as
``China's first sex movie'' says the censors' knife has taken out
all the sex scenes, and viewers said Friday they are not pleased.
   ``It was boring,'' one viewer said after watching ``Widows'
Village,'' a 90-minute tale of love constricted by unusual marriage
taboos in a fishing village in the 1940s.
   Following what they believe to be their ancestors' commands, the
villagers bar married couples from making love for three years, and
then only three times a year until they have a child.
   The official China News Service said last month on the movie's
opening day in the southern city of Canton that ``Widows' Village''
contained ``special scenes showing couples' lovemaking'' and that it
was being called ``China's first sex movie.'' It quoted the
director, Wang Jin, as saying he hoped theaters would bar children.
   When the movie reached Beijing a week ago, the advance publicity
drew sell-out audiences. Ticket scalpers outside the Capital Theater
helped hype it. ``It's got naked people,'' one leered.
   Not true. The most daring scene shows a married couple from the
head up, panting as they lie in bed after having made love.
   ``We can see more than that in videos,'' a well-dressed young
woman said after viewing the movie. The acting and story-line got
``just so-so'' ratings from other viewers.
   Wang said in a telephone interview from the Pearl River Movie
Studio in Canton that some scenes showing sex were cut before the
movie was released for mainland use. He said the scenes would be
left in when it opens in nearby Hong Kong.
   The Ministry of Radio, Film and Television, which censors all
movies, denied knowledge of any cuts and suggested Wang may have
hyped his movie to attract crowds.
   The 47-year-old director, who won one of China's top awards for a
movie in 1986, said it wasn't hype.
   ``I still think the film is improper for children,'' he said.
``China is preparing to set up a system of classifying movies. ...
And I want my movie to be the first to be declared unsuitable for
children.''
</TEXT>
