<FIRST>r a AM-Trump-Jets     01-27 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trump-Jets,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trump, Palm Beachers Threaten To Sue Noisy Airport</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An organization founded by
millionaires Donald Trump and George Petty has announced it will sue
the county in 30 days unless it acts to lessen the noise from Palm
Beach International Airport.
   Jets from the airport pass over posh Palm Beach and many West
Palm Beach neighborhoods at low altitudes, causing a deafening roar
that residents say makes it impossible to carry on a conversation.
   In an open-air news conference interrupted periodically by jets
screaming toward the east, members of the Good Neighbor Council for
Aircraft Noise Control said Thursday that they had taken their first
legal steps to try to force Palm Beach County and the airport to
quiet down.
   They also advocate banning Stage 2 aircraft _ noisy, older planes
such as DC-9s and Boeing 727s.
   Trump's own private plane, a Boeing 727, might be banned from the
airport should the guidelines proposed by the anti-noise groups be
enacted.
   ``If that means Mr. Trump has to get a new airplane, he'll bloody
well have to get a new airplane,'' said Petty, a Canadian-born pulp
and paper executive who lives a few houses away from Trump's
Mar-a-Lago estate in Palm Beach.
   Airport spokesman Jerry Allen said about 65 percent of the
aircraft using the airport are of the quieter ``Stage 3'' type, such
as Boeing 757s _ up from 25 percent in 1982.
   At the anti-noise news conference, however, such arguments would
have fallen on deaf ears of the residents, many of whom wore
T-shirts emblazoned with the command, ``Shhhhhh!''
</TEXT>
