<FIRST>r a AM-NewspageStocks     01-27 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Newspage Stocks,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Rise Sharply, Capping Biggest Week Of Recent Rally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices jumped higher in heavy trading
Friday to cap the biggest week yet in Wall Street's 2-month-old
rally, which has pushed the market back to levels it held just
before the Black Monday crash.
   Analysts said investors continued scrambling to join the
unexpectedly sharp and durable rally, amid renewed optimism about
weak inflation.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed 31.79 to
2,322.86, bringing its gain for the week to 87.50 points.
   Broader market indicators also moved higher and trading volume
was the heaviest in seven months. On the New York Stock Exchange,
254.87 million shares changed hands, the busiest session since a
264.41 million-share day last June 27.
   Before the stock market opened, the Commerce Department estimated
U.S. gross national product grew at an inflation-adjusted annual
rate of 2 percent in fourth quarter 1988.
   The figure was slower than most advance estimates on Wall Street,
and provided fresh evidence that the economy was slowing to a
sustainable, not-very-inflationary pace, analysts said.
   Bond traders welcomed the news by bidding up prices of long-term
government bonds _ thereby pushing down interest rates _ which gave
fresh momentum to the rally in stocks.
