<FIRST>u a AM-McNamaraLetter 1stLd-Writethru a0807 01-27 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-McNamara Letter, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0807,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Demand McNamara Be Fired</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 5 grafs with comment from Dukakis, Barney Frank.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-eight federal prosecutors in Massachusetts
urged the resignation or removal of their boss, the embattled U.S.
Attorney Frank L. McNamara Jr., in a letter Friday to U.S. Attorney
General Richard Thornburgh.
   The letter's signers are among the 39 assistant U.S. attorneys in
the Boston and Springfield offices under McNamara's command.
   McNamara, 41, a Republican appointed by President Reagan in 1987,
has been under fire since November, when the Justice Department
reported that his allegations that he saw his predecessor, William
F. Weld, smoke marijuana at a party, could not be substantiated.
   ``Mr. McNamara's conduct and performance while United States
Attorney is resulting in a loss of confidence in the administration
of justice on the part of the courts, the bar, law enforcement
agencies and the public,'' the letter said.
   McNamamara did not return telephone calls to his office.
   ``Because Mr. McNamara will neither resign nor step aside
temporarily, the credibility and operations of this office will
continue to be damaged, perhaps irretrievably, unless he is
removed,'' the letter said.
   McNamara reportedly has been the subject of several federal
probes.
   Citing anonymous sources, The Boston Globe reported Friday that
the Justice Department is interested in whether any relationship
between McNamara and Senate President William Bulger may have
affected a probe into real estate development in Boston.
   The Boston Herald, also citing an unidentified source, said
McNamara's staff did not tell him about the case because they were
afraid he would use it to embarrass Gov. Michael S. Dukakis during
his Democratic presidential campaign.
   On Thursday, the Globe reported that assessments by two federal
agencies of McNamara's performance have led Thornburgh to conclude
McNamara should resign.
   Dukakis said Friday, ``The situation has been an embarrassment
for months and months and months. I don't think this appointment
should ever have been made.'' A day earlier Dukakis said flatly, ``I
think he should be fired.''
   Dukakis himself has been a target of McNamara.
   According to published reports, McNamara pressed an investigation
into potential conflict of interest in the state's purchase of land
in New Braintree for a state prison.
   McNamara allegedly continued pushing the investigation even after
his staff told him there was no evidence to support allegations of
conflict of interest.
   U.S. Rep. Barney Frank said if no action is forthcoming from the
Justice Department, ``then I think (congressional) hearings will be
necessary.''
</TEXT>
