<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0792)--officialssaynewjerseyishavingitswarmestjanuaryinthreeyears.
01-27 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0792,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow And Rain In The Southern High Plains</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 5-8, `Very cold ..., with 3 grafs to RECAST, fix
typos; picks up 9th graf: `In the national ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A low pressure system over southwest New Mexico spread snow, rain
and drizzle and thunderstorms across New Mexico on Friday, and
Alaska's cold snap continued with record lows and wind chills down
to 100 degrees below zero.
   Snow showers swung from the Great Lakes into northern New
England, but fair weather and seasonally mild temperatures prevailed
from the northern and central Plains to the mid-Atlantic states.
   In New Mexico, up to 6 inches of new snow was measured Friday at
Los Alamos, with additional accumulations up to 4 inches expected.
Showers and a few thunderstorms spread across west-central and
southern Texas.
   Snowshowers ranged across New York into Vermont.
   Very cold air continued to dominate much of central and northern
Alaska. For the eighth day, Fairbanks stayed colder than 40 degrees
below zero and three places set all-time record low temperatures
overnight.
   McGrath reported minus 74 degrees, breaking the old mark by 10
degrees; Tanana fell to minus 76 degrees and Galena had a low of 68
degrees below zero, while 10 to 15 mph winds put winds chills colder
than 100 degres below zero.
   The low in the nation Friday morning was 27 degrees below zero at
Gunnison, Colo. Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged
from zero at Lake Yellowstone, Wyo., to 80 degrees at Miami and Fort
Myers, Fla.
   In the national forecast for Saturday, rain and thunderstorms
will be likely across the central and southern Plains into the
middle Mississippi Valley. Showers will be scattered from central
and southeast Texas into the lower Mississippi Valley, and across
central and northern Illinois.
   Snow will be widespread from northwest Kansas and southwest
Nebraska into the eastern half of Colorado and northeast New Mexico.
Rain will change to snow across southwest Kansas and the western
Oklahoma Panhandle.
   High temperatures will be in the 30s and 40s across much of the
nation west of the Mississippi River and in the 50s and 60s east of
the Mississippi River; in the teens and 20s over southern Idaho and
northeast Nevada, and across northern Maine; in the 30s from the
northern Plains through the northern Great Lakes into southern New
England; in the 40s from the lower Great Lakes to the northern half
of the mid-Atlantic Coast; in the 50s and 60s from northern and
central California through the southern Rockies, and much of Texas
into the lower Mississippi Valley; in the 70s over the Los Angeles
basin, and from the central Gulf Coast through much of Florida.
</TEXT>
