<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 2214EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Panama-Bank     01-27 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-Bank,0270</SECOND>
<UNK>Panamanian Government Denies Post Report</UNK>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Panamanian government Friday
denied a report that strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega founded a
bank to strengthen military control over the economy and launder
drug money.
   A press release from the National Banking Commission said a story
in Thursday's Washington Post was ``a new disinformation and
destablization attempt _ with political ends _ against the
Panamanian finance system, discrediting ... Noreiga, the Defense
Forces and the country.''
   The Post quoted U.S. and Panamanian sources as saying the Banco
Institucional Patria opened on Jan. 16 in a move to expand military
control and to ``corner the market on money-laundering.''
   Noriega, chief of the Defense Forces, has been Panama's de facto
ruler since February, when the National Assembly ousted President
Eric Arturo Delvalle. Delvalle had tried to fire Noriega, who was
indicted on drug trafficking charges by a federal court in Florida.
   The Banking Comission said it gave the Defense Forces control
over the bank in December 1987.
   ``There is nothing abnormal nor strange is this type of military
banking institution,'' the statement said. It said the bank is made
up of 120 individual banks.
   Bank vice president Col. Angel Mina told journalists on Friday,
``The newspaper story is false, and whoever gave this version is a
ex-official of the Department of State who is trying to gain points
with false information and ingratiate himself with President Bush.''
   Mina said that the bank has operated for 35 years with the
savings of military personnel and now has about $21 million in
capital.
</TEXT>
