<FIRST>r w AM-US-Sudan     01-27 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Sudan,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Says Soviets Could Help in Sudan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. government said on Friday the Soviet
Union could play in role in ending the rebellion in the southern
Sudan.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said the Soviets were
involved because of their connections to the government of
neighboring Ethiopia.
   He declined to elaborate, but the Sudanese government has charged
repeatedly that Ethiopia provides arms and money to the rebel Sudan
People's Liberation Army, which is fighting Sudanese forces. Some
350,000 refugees from the fighting have fled to Ethiopia.
   ``We have, ourselves, been encouraging both Khartoum and the SPLA
to end the war, and we've offered our good offices in this effort,''
said Redman. ``We're willing to play any appropriate role in pursuit
of peace acceptable to both sides. The Soviets also have an
important potential role to play in light of their position in
Ethiopia.''
   The Soviets have been supporting the Ethiopian government against
insurgents in Eritrea and Tigray.
   Redman noted that American and Soviet officials have discussed
the Horn of Africa on several occasions over the past year.
   ``We urged the Soviets to consider seriously their
responsibilities to promote solutions to the humanitarian crises in
the Horn,'' Redman said. ``I think that basically captures it.''
</TEXT>
