<FIRST>r a AM-AleutianQuake     01-27 0201</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aleutian Quake,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earthquake Reported In Komandorsky Islands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A powerful earthquake, rated at 6.3 on the
Richter scale, shook the remote Komandorsky Islands west of Alaska
on Friday, the National Earthquake Information Center reported.
   The quake, which struck at 12:35 a.m. PST, was centered in the
the islands at the end of the Aleutian chain, which extends more
than 900 miles from the tip of the Alaskan Peninsula, separating the
Bering Sea from the Pacific Ocean.
   The center said there were no reports of damage because so few
people live in the area.
   The Richter scale gauges the energy released by an earthquake as
measured by the ground motion recorded on a seismograph. For every
increase of one number _ from 5.5 to 6.5 for example _ the ground
motion is 10 times greater.
   Readings of 8.9, the highest on record, were computed from
seismographic records of a quake off the coast of Ecuador in 1906
and from a quake off the coast of Japan in 1933.
   The San Francisco earthquake of 1906, which happened before the
Richter scale was in use, was computed at 8.3. The quake and
subsequent fire were blamed for 700 deaths.
</TEXT>
