<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 1334EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-Eritrea-Outlook Adv05-2Takes   01-27 0750</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Eritrea-Outlook, Adv 05-2 Takes,0770</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Feb. 5, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eritrean Rebels and Ethiopian Ready to Talk, But Obstacles Remain</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: A sidebar box is BC-Eritrea-Glance, b0733.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After 27 years of fighting, the Soviet-backed
Ethiopian government and separatist rebels in Eritrea province say
they're ready to negotiate a settlement of Africa's longest war.
   But many obstacles remain in the way, namely finding a suitable
mediator and overcoming the deep divisions among the rebel groups
themselves.
   The conflict has claimed hundreds of thousands of lives, driven
nearly a Eritrean million refugees westward into neighboring Sudan
and compounded the suffering from the region's devastating famine.
   The rebels, who scored major battlefield victories last spring
and reported new gains in late December, say they are tightening
their siege around a key government-held city while bracing for a
new Ethiopian offensive.
   The guerrillas, led by the dominant Eritrean People's Liberation
Front (EPLF), which along with other rebel factions has offices in
Rome, control about three-fourths of the territory. The government
holds most of the major cities.
   Eritrea is situated on the strategic Horn of Africa, which
overlooks the Red Sea approach to the Suez Canal as well a key water
route to the oil fields of Saudi Arabia. Slightly larger than
Pennsylvania, Eritrea has a 1,000-mile coastline along the Red Sea
across from southern Saudi Arabia.
   A former Italian colony, Eritrea was federated with Ethiopia in
1952 under a U.S.-sponsored resolution in the United Nations. The
Eritreans' battle for independence began in 1961. Emperor Haile
Selassie annexed the territory in 1962.
   (Selassie was overthrown in 1974 by the military that established
today's Marxist government; he died in detention in 1975.)
   As the conflict has worn one, the Eritreans have built a
self-reliant society. The rebels, who receive no significant outside
military or financial support, have built an array of schools,
hospitals and workshops _ some of them underground or in hillside
caverns to avoid detection from the air _ that contribute both to
the war effort and the needs of the general population.
   In March 1987, the main secessionist groups adopted a
constitution and a national program.
   In interviews in Rome, the Eritreans acknowledged that
differences in ideology and strategy have led to fighting among
themselves, but they all declared a willingness to negotiate with
Ethiopia. They contended, however, that President Mengistu Haile
Maniam of Ethiopia was not sincere in his expressed desire for a
settlement.
   In particular, the Eritreans condemned Mengistu's meeting in his
capital, Addis Ababa, in late December with what Ethiopia described
as a delegation of the Eritrean Liberation Front. The ELF, the
oldest of the rebel groups, has split into several rival factions
over the years.
   The delegation reportedly agreed to have the province of 3.5
million people divided into two autonomous regions, one for Moslems
and the other for Christians. According to Addis Ababa radio, the
Ethiopian Politburo accepted that idea and sent a proposal to
Parliament, or Shengo, for final approval in June.
   The Eritreans interviewed in Rome maintained that those who met
with Mengistu were former rebels who now live in Arab countries of
the Persian Gulf and do not represent any of the legitimate
organizations.
   ``They are traitors,'' said Asefau Bariamikael, vice president of
the ELF-National Council.
   ``This is just an attempt by Ethiopia to create divisions and
shows their lack of seriousness in confronting the problem,'' said
Solomon Kinfe, an EPLF fighter and representative here.
   ``Ethiopia has always tried to divide Eritrea on basis of
religion, but religion has always been an element of unification,''
said Taha Nur of the ELF-United Organization.
   Still, all three groups said they are willing to talk through a
mediator and that the United Nations should reopen the Eritrean
issue.
   ``We are ready to participate actively in solving the problem
politically and ready to negotiate with the Ethiopian government
without preconditions,'' Nur said.
   Previously, some of the groups had said they would negotiate only
on condition that independence would be discussed.
   ``Once we sit down, then we will make our proposal for complete
independence,'' Bariamikael of the ELF-National Council, said. ``If
they (Ethiopians) don't want to hear it beforehand, we'll just say
it later. But we won't change our mind about complete independence.''
   Kinfe said the EPLF continues to demand that the conflict be
settled by a referendum offering Eritreans three choices:
independence, regional autonomy or a return to federation.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890127-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 1335EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-Eritrea-Outlook Adv05-1stadd   01-27 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Eritrea-Outlook, Adv 05-1st add,0644</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Feb. 5, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>ROME: to federation.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Although ideology is one factor dividing the rebel groups, the
political outlook of each of them remains vague and none has set
forth any ideological platform on which they would govern Eritrea.
   The dominant EPLF is considered the most left-leaning and is
widely considered Marxist-oriented. The group itself rejects any
political identification tag, saying it is neither Marxist nor
imperialist and has no superpower backing.
   Margherita Boniver, a Socialist member of the Italian Parliament
who has been to Eritrea, said, ``Some of the groups consider the
EPLF fanatics. But the EPLF people are very well informed about the
international scene, and after 27 years of fighting, I doubt they
would opt for a Marxist society.''
   Bariamikael of the ELF-National Council said, ``We all want
Eritrea as a democratic nation, represented by parliament and
different parties.''
   The Ethiopian government has not recently stated its position on
negotiations with the rebels. Telephone calls by The Associated
Press to officials at the Ethiopian embassy in Rome were not
returned. However, in a document issued in July, the government said
it was ready to negotiate on the basis of the new constitution for
regional autonomy in Eritrea but ruled out independence.
   Sudan's ambassador in Rome, Ibrahim Ayoub, confirmed that
Ethiopia approached his government last year and asked for its
mediation. Sudan agreed as part of an effort to settle all conflicts
in the Horn of Africa and is seeking ``to clarify the position of
both parties,'' Ayoub said. Sudan shares the west shore of the Red
Sea with Eritrea and Egypt.
   While the ELF-United Organization has backed mediation by Sudan,
the EPLF has rejected the Sudanese because of their Moslem-dominated
government's war against Christian guerrillas in southern Sudan.
   ``The EPLF prefers that mediation efforts are better undertaken
by third parties that are not in any way involved in the conflicts
in the region,'' the EPLF said in a statement on Jan. 17.
   Italy has also been mentioned as a possible mediator, an issue
that came up during a visit to Ethiopia last fall by an Italian
Parliament delegation.
   ``Mengistu said that Italy could have a role in settling the
Eritrean question,'' said Mrs. Boniver, the Italian Parliament
member and president of Parliament's foreign affairs committee.
   ``Italy should take up this very serious offer and try to start
negotiations either trilaterally or involving other countries,''
said Mrs. Boniver, who visited Eritrea briefly last year and plans
to return with other Parliament members this year.
   On the military front, the Eritreans say they want to consolidate
their victories of last spring. In March, EPLF guerrillas broke
through a 10-year-old front south of their headquarters in Nacfa and
overran the government-held town of Afabet, capturing three Soviet
military advisers in the process.
   Since then, rebels have carried out hit-and-run raids on the
naval bases at Massawa and Masab. In a communique in mid-January,
the EPLF claimed to have killed more than 2,000 Ethiopian soldiers
along the state road connecting Asmara, the provincial capital, and
Massawa.
   Kinfe said the EPLF has been entrenched for months around the
Ethiopian-held city of Keren in north-central Eritrea and the group
is expecting the government to launch an offensive soon to try to
break the siege.
   According to the Military Balance, a survey published by the
London-based International Institute for Strategic Studies, the EPLF
has about 30,000 fighters. Ethiopia has a 315,000-member military,
not including Cuban, Soviet and East German advisers and technicians.
   While the Ethiopians have been armed by the Soviets, the rebels
rely mostly with captured government equipment, including T-54 and
T-55 tanks and heavy artillery. Ethiopia controls the skies, with
Soviet-supplied MiG warplanes and helicopters.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Feb. 5</NOTE>
