<DOCNO> AP890127-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 0213EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AirFares Bjt   01-27 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Air Fares, Bjt,0575</SECOND>
<BYLINE>American Raises Some Discount Fares; Other Airlines Follow Suit</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Increases in some discounted MaxSaver fares that
take effect today and next week have analysts wondering whether
passengers could be in for another round of fare hikes.
   American Airlines raised its so-called MaxSaver fares on flights
from its Dallas-Fort Worth hub to 40 U.S. cities, American
spokeswoman Mary O'Neill said Thursday. Several other big carriers
followed suit.
   The $40 round-trip hike will apply to 20 West Coast cities and a
number of East Coast destinations, while MaxSaver fares to several
cities in the central United States will be raised by $20 round
trip. The higher fares take effect today for the West Coast cities
and Feb. 1 for the other destinations.
   For example, American raised its round-trip MaxSaver fare between
Dallas-Fort Worth and Los Angeles from $258 off-peak to $298, and
from $298 peak to $338. MaxSavers between the Dallas hub and
Cincinnati will go from $238 off-peak to $258, and from $278 peak to
$298.
   Spokesmen for other major carriers _ including United Airlines
and Delta Air Lines _ said they were matching American's move in the
same markets.
   Continental Airlines, often a fare-cutting leader, said it
matched the West Coast increases but was still studying the others.
Pan Am Corp. was reviewing the situation.
   Fares normally are not lifted at this time of year, which usually
is a slack period for travel. But passenger traffic has been fairly
strong in recent weeks, analysts say.
   ``They (the airlines) evidently feel very confident that the
traffic is very strong and can sustain another fare increase,'' said
Kevin Murphy, an industry analyst for Morgan Stanley &amp; Co.
   The move is ``setting the tone for more (fare) increases this
summer,'' he said.
   All of the fares now being raised by American had been cut in
mid-November when the entire industry revamped its MaxSaver fares,
Ms. O'Neill said. At that time the major carriers, led by
Continental, lowered some of the popular discount fares but boosted
most of them.
   ``We couldn't justify that fare in those markets,'' Ms. O'Neill
said.
   MaxSaver tickets _ which are used mainly by vacation travelers _
must be purchased seven to 14 days in advance and require a Saturday
night stay. In the November revamp, the fares were based on the
length of a flight. Competition on individual routes, not mileage,
had determined MaxSaver rates in the past.
   The MaxSaver change came just days after Continental initiated an
industry move to drop discounts aimed at business travelers.
   As a result of the latest fare hikes, 27 of the 40 affected
MaxSaver fares will still be lower than they were before the
November restructuring, Ms. O'Neill said.
   American serves a total network of about 5,000 markets.
   ``It's coming at an unusual time of year for there to be fare
hikes,'' said Thomas Longman, who follows the industry for Bear
Stearns &amp; Co. ``They've seen stronger traffic in those markets than
they thought.''
   Andrew Geller, an airline analyst for Provident National Bank in
Philadelphia, estimates that passenger traffic currently is up 5
percent to 8 percent from its level a year ago.
   Robust passenger demand last year spurred the airlines to raise
fares an average 10 percent from 1987, he said.
</TEXT>
