<FIRST>r f PM-OilPrices     01-27 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Prices,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Sharply Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The energy futures market tumbled as traders
expressed disappointment in the outcome of a joint meeting between
OPEC and independent oil-producing nations in London.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the March contract for West
Texas Intermediate _ the benchmark grade of U.S. crude _ plunged 40
cents Thursday to settle at $17.72 a barrel, the lowest level of the
session. The contract had jumped 58 cents on Wednesday and hit a
high of $18.48 at one point Thursday.
   Among refined petroleum contracts traded on the exchange
Thursday, February home heating oil closed down 1.26 cents at 50.87
cents a gallon, after rising 1.43 cents on Wednesday.
   The February contract for unleaded gasoline, which rose 1.30
cents on Wednesday, settled off 1.65 cents at 49.87 cents a gallon.
   The seven non-OPEC countries, including Mexico and Egypt, said
after the daylong meeting in London Thursday that they'd support
OPEC's target price of $18 a barrel. But they didn't specify in a
joint statement with OPEC whether they would cut their oil
production to do so, and analysts said that troubled many traders.
   ``They didn't recommend any specific action,'' said Nauman
Barakat, vice president of energy investments at Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc. ``Their statement was so vague that it didn't really
mean anything.''
   Speculation that independent producers might offer to cut their
collective oil production by at least 5 percent had sent oil prices
sharply higher on Wednesday and early Thursday, following a selloff
on Tuesday.
   OPEC General Secretary Subroto said that the 5 percent cut ``is
an option.''
   Oil prices have risen sharply since early October, a month before
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries agreed to limit
its production to 18.5 million barrels a day. The agreement was
effective Jan. 1.
   OPEC members are now producing an estimated 19.5 million barrels
a day, down as much as 3.5 million barrels a day from the fourth
quarter.
</TEXT>
