<FIRST>r f PM-SundstrandSuspensions Bjt   01-27 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sundstrand Suspensions, Bjt,0649</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sundstrand Back Bidding on Government Contracts After Settling Differences</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCKFORD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sundstrand Corp., whian additional $62.3
million to the Pentagon, officials say.
   ``We're looking forward to returning to a normal relationship
with the government,'' company spokesman Claude Vernam said
Thursday, moments after the Defense Department lifted its ban on
Sundstrand's participation in the military procurement process.
   That move followed an announcement that the Rockford-based
aerospace manufacturing giant would make cost-saving concessions on
future contracts and pay $62.3 million to resolve differences
stemming from a lengthy investigation that resulted in criminal
charges against the company.
   Last October, a federal judge approved a plea agreement in which
Sundstrand admitted defrauding the government and paid $115 million
in fines as part of the largest contract fraud settlement in Defense
Department history.
   Spokesman Larry Wilson of the Defense Logistics Agency, which
administers contracts, said the new agreement would provide the
Pentagon, in effect, with some price guarantees on future contracts
by forcing the company to modify the way it allocates charges
between its commercial and military work.
   The agreement also called for Sundstrand to make an immediate
cash payment of $40 million; followed by a separate payment of $9.9
million ``on or before Sept. 1,'' and payments totaling $12.4
million to be made in equal annual installments of $2.48 million
over the next five years.
   Wilson said savings from the accounting changes could eventually
total another $34 million.
   The agreement and Sundstrand's return to the bidding process was
greeted with optimism Thursday on Wall Street. In trading on the New
York Stock Exchange, Sundstrand rose $1.62{ a share to $54.25.
   But in a statement, Sundstrand put the cost of the agreement at
$71.3 million over the next five years _ considerably more than the
$20 million reserved by the company for resolution of all of its
government contract disputes.
   The Defense Department accounts for 42 percent of Sundstrand's
$1.4 billion in annual sales. Asked how much the suspension may have
cost the company, Vernam said, ``I can't put a price on it. ... But
we're glad to be out from under this thing.''
   The Pentagon suspended Sundstrand from doing any new business
with the federal government on Oct. 19, saying it wasn't satisfied
with the company's response to being caught up in a fraud
investigation overseen by the U.S. attorney in Chicago.
   While the suspension did not affect existing contracts, it
prevented the corporation and six subsidiaries _ Sundstrand Data
Control Inc.; Falk Corp.; Sundstrand Heat Transfer Inc.; Sundstrand
Service Corp.; Sullair Corp., and Signatron Inc. _ from bidding on
or receiving any new contracts.
   At the same time Sundstrand Corp. pleaded guilty to four counts
of defrauding the Defense Department by overbilling on aircraft
parts, its Sundstrand Data Control subsidiary settled a separate
case by agreeing to pay $13 million. That case involved charges the
company had used unallowable costs to inflate its overhead rates.
   The U.S. attorney in Chicago, Anton Valukas, said a federal
investigation had determined that besides overbilling for aircraft
parts, the company had been submitting claims for such things as
babysitting expenses, country clubs and servants for its executives.
   Sundstrand employees gave an estimated $100,000 worth of liquor,
meals, motel rooms, golf outings and tickets to the theater, hockey,
football and baseball games, the government said. They then
submitted expense reports identifying the Defense Department workers
they entertained only as a ``customer'' or ``government employee,''
the complaint said.
   DLA spokesman Wilson said the $62.3 million figure announced
Thursday was based on the results of various audits dealing with how
Sundstrand had allocated production costs to military contracts in
the past.
</TEXT>
