<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose against most major currencies
in active European trading today as reported central bank
intervention failed to curb bullishness toward the U.S. currency.
   Gold prices were lower.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the central bank intervention was
small, and its effect short-lived. They said the West German central
bank may have sold a substantial amount of dollars early in the day
but most other banks sold token amounts.
   The dollar resumed rising soon after the intervention, and
dealers said they expected the markets to continue to test central
bank resolve.
   ``The arm wrestling match (between the central banks and markets)
will continue and the market seems rather robust,'' said a trader in
Milan.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7685 today, less expensive
for buyers than Thursday's late $1.7730.
   Other mid-morning rates for the dollar compared with Thursday's
late rates, included: 1.8525 West German marks, up from 1.8440;
1.5715 Swiss francs, up from 1.5671; 6.2885 French francs, up from
6.2705; 2.0835 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0815; 1,352.00 Italian
lire, up from 1,350.25; 1.1870 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1816.
   Earlier in Tokyo, where the business day ends before London's
begins, the dollar rose to 128.65 Japanese yen, up 1.13 yen. In
London today the dollar traded lower at 128.50 yen.
   Gold bullion prices in London opened at $402.60 a troy ounce,
down from the closing price of $405.75 Thursday. At mid-morning,
London bullion dealers fixed a recommended gold price this morning
of $402.05.
   Gold in Zurich was trading at a mid-morning price of $402.20,
down from a late bid price of $405.75 a troy ounce Thursday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at $403.99 bid, down from
$407.70.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at $6.07 bid a troy ounce,
down from $6.19.
