<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     01-27 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rebounds, Japan Stocks Set New Record</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rebounded sharply in Tokyo today,
reflecting the currency's overnight bullishness in New York and
London, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange soared to a
new record high close.
   The dollar opened at 128.42 yen and moved between 128.40-128.80
yen before closing at 128.65 yen, up a sharp 1.13 yen from
Thursday's close.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues rebounded 134.32 points, or 0.42 percent, to close
at 31,646.13. It was a record closing figure, surpassing the
previous record set on Wednesday.
   Exchange dealers said the U.S. currency firmed in Tokyo following
its bullish rise in New York overnight and in anticipation of
favorable results in the U.S. gross national product figure.
   ``Many players stepped aside today ahead of the release of the
important economic indicator in the United States,'' said an
exchange dealer at a Japanese commercial bank. ``But a strong
showing in overseas markets encouraged some buying of the dollar.''
   The U.S. Commerce Department is expected to release the December
gross national product figure later today as well as quarterly and
annual figures for 1988.
   In the stock market, dealers said the dollar's upturn encouraged
investors to buy export-related shares such as electronics and
automobiles, notably Sony, Toshiba, and Toyota.
   ``Investors were hesitant to make big investments today before
the U.S. GNP announcement,'' said a dealer at a major brokerage in
Tokyo. ``In general, the market seems still bullish and looking for
incentives to buy shares.''
   Volume traded on the first section of the exchange, where most
major shares are listed, was 1.1 billion shares.
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange will be open for a half-day trading
session Saturday but will be closed on Saturdays beginning Feb. 4.
</TEXT>
