<FIRST>r f PM-StoneContainer-Bathurst     01-27 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stone Container-Bathurst,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stone Container Announces Offer For Consolidated Bathurst</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shareholders who have a combined 65 percent stake
in Consolidated-Bathurst Inc. have agreed to tender their stock to
Stone Container Corp., which is making a $2.2 billion bid to buy the
Canadian company.
   Stone Container's offer, which amounts to $25 (Canadian) per
common share, includes approximately 102.4 million common shares of
Consolidated-Bathurst, and approximately 2 million preferred shares,
Stone Container said.
   The $2.2 billion price cited by Stone Container is in U.S.
dollars.
   ``We believe that Consolidated-Bathurst is an outstanding
company, with excellent management and personnel,'' said Roger W.
Stone, chairman, president and chief executive officer of Stone
Container.
   The purchase of one of Canada's leading forest products companies
would convert Stone into a $6 billion concern and make it one of the
world's leading producers of commodity paper and newsprint.
   ``The planned acquisition is totally consistent with our strategy
of commitment to the growth and profitability of our core
business,'' Stone said Thursday.
   Power Corp. of Montreal, which has controlling interest in
Consolidated-Bathurst, said it would tender its shares.
   Power, a holding company run by financier Paul Desmarais, owns 40
percent of Consolidated-Bathurst and controls another 10 percent
through an agreement with the Kuwait Investment Office.
   A third shareholder, Bouverie Investments Ltd., also has agreed
to tender. The three companies together control about 65 percent of
Consolidated-Bathurst shares.
   Stone Container expects to mail the offer and related materials
to all Consolidated-Bathurst shareholders within the next 10 days.
   An acquisition is subject to approval by Investment Canada, a
federal agency that reviews foreign takeovers.
   Stone Container, based in Chicago, is the world's largest
producer of unbleached containerboard and kraft paper, and converts
those products into containers and bags.
   Demarais told a crowded news conference he was disappointed he
did not achieve his goal of building Consolidated-Bathurst into a
worldwide concern, but he added: ``There comes a time to take a
profit.''
   Consolidated-Bathurst reported earnings of $239.6 million for
1988, on sales of $2.4 billion. Stone Container, in the same period,
earned $345 million Cdn on sales of $4.4 billion.
</TEXT>
