<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 1148EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-ToyotaInBritain     01-27 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Toyota In Britain,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Toyota Considering Major Production Facility In Britain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Toyota Motor Corp., Japan's largest automaker, is
studying the possibility of building a factory in Britain to produce
passenger cars by 1992, Toyota President Shoichiro Toyoda said
Friday.
   ``Toyota has been considering European car production for some
time,'' Toyoda said at a news conference. ``We are starting in-depth
feasibility studies with Britain as a strong candidate for a site
for our car production in Europe. It does not mean we have made a
final decision.''
   The study will examine plans for production of 1,800-cubic
centimeter cars at the rate of 200,000 per year, Toyoda said. The
factory would employ about 3,000 workers and represent an investment
of 140 billion yen, or about $1.1 billion, he said.
   Toyota Executive Vice President Tsutomu Ohshima said the company
``will consider the option in Britain first, before others we
have.'' He described the feasibility study as ``an assessment to
make it (production in Europe) possible, not just to see our chance
with the project.''
   Toyota, ranked third in worldwide auto production after General
Motors Corp. and Ford Motor Co., would be the second Japanese
automaker to produce cars on its own in Britain after Nissan Motor
Co., which started production in 1986. Honda Motor Co. sells Hondas
in Britain manufactured by the Austin Rover Group.
   Toyota reportedly also has been examining the possibility of
setting up operations in Belgium, Portugal or Spain. Asked why the
firm was focusing on Britain, Toyoda said, ``Britain is a leading
member of the European Economic Community and the government has
shown us that we would be welcome.''
   In London, British Secretary of State for Trade and Industry Lord
Young said in a statement, ``I have made it clear to Toyota that
they would receive a warm welcome from the government if they were
to decide to locate the project in the U.K., and I have invited them
to work closely with my department in pursuing their feasibility
studies.''
   The automaker has not discussed tax breaks or other incentives
with the British government, Managing Director Juji Numata told
reporters.
   Toyota's announcment ``is not unexpected and is consistent with
the existing trend of all Japanese automakers,'' said an auto
industry analyst at a major securities firm.
   ``Toyota is notable by its absence (from the EEC),'' said the
analyst, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``Toyota has been the
most laggard, but it certainly has the capability, with 2 trillion
yen, or $15.5 billion, in cash assets at its disposal.''
   Toyota's announcement comes amid concern in Japan over the
creation of the 12-nation European Economic Community's single
market in 1992.
   The single market aims through harmonization of tax laws and
other measures to establish a free flow of goods among EEC nations.
Many imports from non-EEC countries, including Japan, are expected
to be subject to new EEC restrictions from 1992.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
