<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   01-27 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grains, Soybeans Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grains and soybeans were mostly
lower in early trading today at the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Bearish weather forecasts in South America and across the U.S.
winter wheat belt pressured prices, and further selling occurred as
traders took profits after Thursday's big rally, analysts said.
   A strong dollar also discouraged buying in grain and soybeans,
said Victor Lespinasse, a trader for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   A forecast for more soybean-enhancing rain in Brazil kept the lid
on bean prices, he said, and recent gains in wheat due to dry
weather in U.S. growing regions evaporated as forecasters predicted
rain tonight and Saturday.
   In early trading, wheat was 2 cents to 3 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.41\ a bushel; corn was { cent
lower to \ cent higher with March at $2.71\; oats were 1{ cents to
3\ cents lower with March at $2.16}; and soybeans 3 cents lower to
1} cents higher, with March at $7.58{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures prices advanced and hogs opened mostly higher
today at the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   In early trading, live cattle were .28 cent to .72 cent higher,
with the contract for delivery in February at 72.70 cents a pound;
feeder cattle were .25 cent to .95 cent higher, with March at 82.70
cents a pound; live hogs were .15 cent lower to .40 cent higher,
with February at 42.55 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were
.03 cent to .13 cent higher, with February at 38.85 cents a pound.
   Pork futures fell sharply and cattle traded mostly lower on
Thursday.
</TEXT>
