<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Trade 1stLd-Writethru   01-27 0563</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Trade, 1st Ld-Writethru,0582</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trade Deficit Narrows More Sharply Than Expected</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 2nd and 3rd grafs to UPDATE with closing dollar, stock
quotes; picks up 4th graf, ``Despite the ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's merchandise deficit narrowed more sharply
than expected to 1.66 billion pounds, or $2.94 billion, in December,
the government said Friday, providing further evidence that the
country's overheated economy is slowing down.
   The news eased fears that British interest rates would be pushed
higher. The pound surprisingly rallied to $1.7688 following the
11:30 a.m. report, but finished the day lower at $1.7655, down from
$1.7730 late Thursday.
   Stock prices surged, and the Financial Times-Stock Exchange
100-share index rose 46.1 points, or 2.4 percent, to close at
2,005.9.
   Despite the December improvement, Britain's trade deficit for the
year more than doubled to 20.34 billion pounds, or $36 billion, and
the country's trade picture was much worse than the Conservative
government's Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson has forecast.
   The 1988 deficit was attacked by opposition Labor member of
Parliament Bryan Gould, who serves as his party's trade spokesman:
``These figures complete the worst year in our trading history. They
also show that any prospect of improvement in 1989 looks very
remote.''
   John Smith, who serves as the Labor party's spokesman on Treasury
matters, called the deficit the ``awful legacy'' of last year's
tax-cutting budget. He said it was being made worse by Lawson's
reliance on interest rates to head off inflationary pressure.
   The December narrowing came as exports rose 3 percent and imports
held steady, the Department of Trade and Industry said.
   The financial markets had been expecting a deficit of 1.49
billion pounds (?2.64 billion).
   The narrowing indicates a slowdown in economic growth and should
help to reduce the pressure on the government to signal the
commercial banks to raise their base lending rates from their
current 13 percent level, said Ian Harwood, a British economist at
the London investment firm Warburg Securities.
   The news should prove more bearish for the pound in the longer
run, Harwood said.
   ``This (pound rally) is just a knee-jerk reaction,'' he said.
   ``People are going to be increasingly saying that 13 percent is
the peak'' for base rates, he said.
   The seasonally adjusted deficit for December compared with a
revised deficit of 1.87 billion pounds in November and a deficit of
1.24 billion pounds in December 1987, the department said.
   With December's invisible trade, which covers services, overseas
investment earnings and official transfer payments, estimated to be
in surplus by 400 million pounds, Britain's current account showed a
deficit of 1.26 billion pounds in December, compared with a revised
deficit of 1.47 billion pounds in November and a deficit of 802
million pounds in December 1987.
   The markets had expected the current account deficit to come to
between 1.1 billion pounds and 1.8 billion pounds.
   Exports totaled 7.12 billion pounds in December, up from 6.91
billion pounds in November.
   Imports totaled 8.78 billion pounds in December, little changed
from 8.77 billion pounds in November.
   Britain's 1988 merchandise trade deficit of 20.34 billion pounds
compared with a deficit of 10.16 billion pounds in 1987.
   The 1988 current account was 14.27 billion pounds, compared with
a deficit of 2.69 billion pounds a year earlier.
   The 1988 current account deficit was well above Lawson's forecast
of 13 billion pounds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
