<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     01-27 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Surges In Europe, Gold Falls Sharply</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs version expected by 5:30 p.m. EST.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar surged against major foreign
currencies in European trading Friday, overcoming what dealers said
was repeated central bank intervention.
   Gold prices fell by about $7 an ounce, finishing below the
psychologically important level of $400 an ounce.
   Foreign exchange dealers said central banks intervened twice in
the day to sell dollars in an effort to keep exchange rates down.
But the selling only encouraged the markets to regard the American
currency as a good buy, dealers said.
   They said the U.S. Federal Reserve entered the market alone for a
third time, late in the day, but it failed to stem the dollar's
rally.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7655 late Friday, cheaper
for buyers than Thursday's late $1.7730.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with
Thursday's late rates: 1.8570 West German marks, up from 1.8440;
1.5743 Swiss francs, up from 1.5671; 6.2875 French francs, up from
6.2705; 2.0880 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0815; 1,352.37 Italian
lire, up from 1,350.25; 1.1853 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1816.
   Earlier in Tokyo, the dollar closed at 128.65 Japanese yen, up
from 127.52 yen. In London late Friday the dollar traded higher at
128.93 yen.
   Dealers said gold was hit by the dollar's strength. As long as
the dollar continues to rise strongly the market will have little
choice but to lower the gold price to attract buyers, they said.
   In London, gold closed at a bid $398.25 a troy ounce, down from
$405.75 late Thursday. The Zurich late bid price was $398.75, down
from $405.75.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at $403.99 bid, down from
$407.70.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at $6.02 bid a troy ounce,
down from $6.19.
</TEXT>
