<FIRST>r f BC-Switzerland-Insider     01-27 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Switzerland-Insider,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Swiss Lift Banking Secrecy In Probe With French, U.S. Links</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swiss authorities on Friday ordered bank
records linked to the unfolding insider trading scandal in France to
be turned over to U.S. investigators who uncovered the affair.
   The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission last Tuesday had
asked the Swiss Federal Office of Police Affairs to help in the
Pechiney-Triangle probe by ordering a suspension of strict banking
secrecy rules.
   Approval of the U.S. request also means that any assets frozen in
bank accounts in Switzerland could be turned over to the United
States once the investigators submit more detailed allegations on
the size and location of funds.
   Swiss justice ministry sources said the order applies to
documents on blocked accounts at five Swiss banks and two financial
services companies. The accounts were frozen after a preliminary
U.S. intervention with Bern last month.
   All parties concerned have 10 days to appeal the order.
   Friday's action was the first on a ``judicial help'' request
concerning insider trading since strengthened Swiss legislation took
effect last July 1. Part of the legislation's aim was to avoid past
tension with U.S. authorities in international probes.
   Under a Swiss-U.S. treaty, judicial assistance can only be
granted when alleged offenses are criminal in both countries.
   Friday's justice ministry statement noted that France to date has
not asked for Swiss judicial aid.
   The affair involves allegations that people with confidential,
advance information made huge illegal stock market profits when the
French state-owned aluminum company Pechiney bought out U.S.-based
Triangle Industries last November.
   Close associates of French President Francois Mitterrand have
been implicated in the affair, which has preoccupied the Socialist
government.
   Finance Minister Pierre Beregovoy called Thursday for a complete
criminal probe into the allegations.
   The SEC alerted French authorities after noticing abnormally
heavy purchases of Triangle shares in the week before Pechiney
publicly launched its successful takeover bid Nov. 21.
   Pechiney ultimately bought Triangle, the former parent of
American National Can Corp., for $56 a share, nearly six times their
value a week before.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
