<SECOND>BC-Satellite Merger,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wold, Bonneville TV Transmission Firms To Merge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two TV satellite transmission companies,
Bonneville Satellite Communications and Wold Communications Inc.,
have agreed to merge, the companies announced.
   The privately held firms declined to reveal financial terms of
the deal, other than to say that Salt Lake City-based Bonneville
would own 60 percent of the new entity and Wold, of Los Angeles,
would hold 40 percent.
   A name for the new company hasn't been chosen, they said in
announcing the deal Thursday. The companies said they had sought
approval for the combination from the Federal Communications
Commission, and would continue to operate separately pending a
decision, expected in 60 days.
   Bonneville is best known for transmitting news and sports,
including Cable News Network feeds and National Basketball
Association games to local stations. The company also serves
corporations seeking satellite links between headquarters and
outlying offices.
   Wold calls itself the nation's biggest distributor of syndicated
television programming to independent TV stations and transmits news
for Japanese companies.
   Bonneville Satellite is a partnership of Simmons Satellite Inc.
and Bonneville International Corp.
   Wold's biggest shareholder is Welsh, Carson, Anderson &amp; Stowe, a
New York investment firm. Other investors include Cox
Communications, Contel Corp. and LBS Communications.
</TEXT>
