<HEAD>Harveys Bristol Cream to Flow from Iberia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRISTOL, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harveys will keep Bristol in the brand
name of its sherry but the company said Friday it is moving most of
its operations to Spain and Portugal.
   Nearly 300 jobs, or about two-thirds of the company's British
workforce, will be lost when the factories that blend, bottle and
distribute sherry and port are closed in June.
   The company will keep its headquarters in Bristol, the city in
southwestern England where it began business in 1792.
   Ian Wilson-Smith, the company's managing director, said Harveys
had suffered from a year-long slump in sales and that the
reorganization would bring substantial savings.
   Two-thirds of Harveys' capital investment was already in Spain
where there were six production plants and more than 25,000 acres of
vineyards.
