<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-McDonnellDouglas     01-27 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-McDonnell Douglas,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>McDonnell Douglas' Quarterly Profit Up 60 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McDonnell Douglas Corp.'s fourth-quarter profit
jumped 60 percent chiefly due to lower costs and an improved
performance in its combat aircraft division, the company reported
Friday.
   The aerospace firm said after-tax earnings in the three months
ended Dec. 31 were $145 million, or $3.79 per share, on revenue of
$4.3 billion, compared with earnings of $93 million, or $2.32 per
share, and revenue of $3.6 billion in the same period in 1987.
   In a reversal of 1987's experience, earnings expanded robustly in
the combat aircraft segment largely because production costs were
lower.
   The division had difficulties in 1987 bringing out new models of
the F-15 and F@A-18.
   ``Most of these difficulties had been resolved by the fourth
quarter of 1988, with a strongly positive effect on earnings,'' the
company stated.
   For all of 1988, the company had a profit of $350 million, or
$9.13 per share, on revenue of $15 billion, up 11 percent from
1987's earnings of $313 million, or $7.75 per share. Revenue in 1987
was $13.7 billion.
   Earnings for the year increased in all segments except
information systems, the company said. Combat aircraft and space
systems and missiles recorded the largest gains.
   The manufacturer said earnings for both 1987 and 1988 were
adversely affected by production disruptions related to increased
transport aircraft production rates and introduction of new combat
aircraft, high research and development expenditures and increase
interest expense.
   Firm backlog at the end of 1988 was $26.3 billion, up from $18.9
billion in 1987. Total backlog was $40.5 billion, compared with $33
billion a year earlier.
   Firm backlog excludes government orders not yet funded, orders
being negotiated as continuations of authorized programs, and
commercial orders subject to contingencies.
</TEXT>
