<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     01-27 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0658</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economic Indicators Spark Plunge In Precious Metals Futures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Bullish U.S. economic indicators sent gold futures prices
plummeting in trading Friday at the New York Commodity Exchange, and
silver prices followed suit.
   On other markets, copper, cattle and heating oil futures prices
rallied; pork prices were mixed; grain, soybean and crude oil prices
were mostly lower; and unleaded gasoline prices declined.
   The government reported that the gross national product rose 3.8
percent last year, the best showing in four years.
   The GNP report, along with the ``tremendous strength of the
dollar ... defuses inflationary pressure, and that's what fuels
precious metals,'' said Bette Raptopoulous, a metals analyst with
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York.
   Gold prices settled $6.90 to $9.40 lower, with the contract for
delivery in February at $396.10 a troy ounce. Silver prices were
22.1 cents to 24.6 cents lower with the February contract at $5.88 a
troy ounce.
   Copper futures rallied on confirmation of a strike at a major
refinery in Mexico, Ms. Raptopoulous said.
   Traders bought copper futures contracts on expectations that the
walkout will result in a tightening of copper supplies.
   Copper prices were 3.40 cents lower to 3.10 cents higher, with
the contract for delivery in February at $1.51 a pound.
   Cattle futures rallied sharply, bolstered by Agriculture
Department cattle-on-feed figures released after the close of
trading Thursday.
   The quarterly report showed that the number of cattle on the
nation's feed lots _ those to be fattened for slaughter _ increased
only 5 percent in December 1988 over the same month in 1987.
   ``The market had factored in about a 10 percent increase,'' and
the lower figure reported by the USDA encouraged buying of cattle
futures, analysts said.
   Further support came from the approach of February, declared by
the industry as ``national meat month.''
   ``Retailers have a tendency to promote beef a little more
aggressively'' during the month, which tightens supplies and helps
account for the rise in futures prices, analysts said.
   Pork prices were mixed, under pressure from weak spot prices and
other negative fundamentals. But the strength in the cattle market
kept the pork complex from plunging, analysts noted.
   Live cattle settled .30 cent to 1.40 cents higher, with the
contract for delivery in February at 73.40 cents a pound; feeder
cattle were 1.22 cents to 1.50 cents higher, with March at 83.17
cents a pound; live hogs were .38 cent lower to .22 cent higher,
with February at 42.32 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were
1.20 cent lower to .20 cent higher, with February at 38.60 cents a
pound.
   Grain and soybean futures were mostly lower at the Chicago Board
of Trade.
   A flurry of selling on technical market factors by big brokerage
houses kept the lid on wheat and soybean prices, and further
pressure came from a weekend forecast for crop-enhancing rain in the
nation's winter-wheat growing regions, said Victor Lespinasse, a
trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Wheat settled 2{ cents to 4{ cents lower, with the contract for
delivery for March at $4.40{ a bushel; corn was unchanged to { cent
higher with March at $2.71} a bushel; oats were 2 cents to 8 cents
lower with March at $2.12 a bushel; and soybeans settled 7\ cents
lower to 1} cents higher, with March at $7.54 a bushel.
   Crude oil prices were mostly lower, heating oil prices rallied
and unleaded gasoline fell in trading at the New York Mercantile
Exchange.
   Crude oil settled 4 cents lower to 7 cents higher with the March
contract at $17.74 a barrel; heating oil was .58 cent to 1.11 cent
higher, with February at 51.98 cents a gallon; and unleaded gas was
.18 cent to .55 cent lower, with February at 49.59 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
