<FIRST>u f AM-Economy 1stLd-Writethru f0201 01-27 0921</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0201,0942</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economy Makes Best Growth Showing in Four Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Subs 5th graf pvs bgng, The stock ... to include closing stock
prices; Picks up 6th graf pvs bgng, Commenting on ...; Also moved on general
newswires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. economy grew a healthy 3.8 percent in
1988, the best showing in four years, as the country benefited from
a narrowing of the trade deficit and a big increase in business
investment, the government reported Friday.
   The increase in the gross national product, the broadest measure
of economic health, occurred despite the fact that growth slowed
sharply in the final three months of the year, with the GNP rising
at an annual rate of just 2.0 percent from October through December.
   The October-December increase was the slowest quarterly
performance in two years and followed increases of 3.4 percent, 3
percent and 2.5 percent, respectively, in the first three quarters
of 1988.
   While the fourth quarter performance came in below most advance
estimates, the figure was generally seen by economists and Wall
Street as a good sign that the economy was slowing to a more
sustainable pace.
   The stock market surged on the news, pushing the early-1989 rally
to new highs. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed 31.79
to 2,322.86, capping off the best week so far in a rally that began
more than two months ago.
   Commenting on the GNP report, the Bush administration said that
the fourth-quarter slowdown was not a warning that the six-year
record peacetime recovery was in danger of coming to an end and
should not overshadow the stellar performance the economy turned in
for all of 1988. Immediately following the October 1987 stock market
crash, there were widespread fears that a cutback in spending by
worried consumers could topple the country into a recession.
   ``During 1988, we had a numer of positive developments,'' said
Commerce Undersecretary Robert Ortner. ``We made significant
progress in reducing the trade deficit, the unemployment rate
dropped to a 14-year low and the stock market began a sustained
recovery from its plunge in late 1987.''
   Ortner predicted that economic growth would be slower in 1989,
but he said the economy should be able to reach the 3.2 percent GNP
projection contained in President Reagan's final budget.
   The Bush administration has said it will use that same estimate
when it submits its budget revisions to Congress next month despite
criticism from private economists that this growth forecast is
overly optimistic.
   David Wyss, an economist with Data Resources Inc., said he was
looking for the economy to expand by just 2.7 percent in 1989 as a
slowdown in the trade improvement and slower business investment
holds back overall growth.
   Trade and business capital spending accounted for one-half of
overall growth in 1988 as exports shot up by 17.7 percent,
reflecting increased demand as the weaker dollar made U.S. products
competitive again.
   The surge in exports triggered a boom in spending on new plants
and equipment as U.S. industry rushed to expand production
facilities. Business investment shot up by 9.5 percent, the best
showing since 1984, and a big improvement over a 2.8 percent rise in
1987.
   However, in both the third quarter and fourth quarter the trade
deficit, as measured in inflation-adjusted terms in the GNP,
widened. Analysts said the trade improvement is in danger of
stalling out in 1989, an occurrence which would raise the danger the
country could topple into a recession.
   ``The trade numbers are very worrisome,'' Wyss said. ``When we
are still averaging a trade deficit of about $11 billion a month, we
can't afford to see the improvement stall out.''
   The 3.8 percent GNP increase for the year followed a 3.4 percent
rise in 1987. The faster growth helped push unemployment down to a
14-year low of 5.3 percent in December while pushing the factory
operating rate to 84.2 percent of capacity at the end of the year,
the highest level in nine years.
   However, the GNP report showed that inflation picked up as well
with a price index tied to the GNP rising by 4.2 percent last year,
the fastest increase since a 6.2 percent rise in 1982.
   For the fourth quarter, the GNP fixed-weighted price index rose
just 4 percent, down from a 5.3 percent increase in the third
quarter. But analysts said the Fed will likely consider the
inflation level still too high and keep up the pressure on interest
rates into the new year. This will boost the government's cost of
borrowing to finance the $2.7 trillion national debt and make it
even harder for Bush to fulfill his campaign pledge of lowering the
budget deficit without increasing taxes.
   But Bush on Friday played down any differences between the
administration and Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan.
   ``He is more concerned about inflation pressures than I am right
now,'' Bush said at a news conference. ``It seems to me there is an
area of difference. But generally speaking, I think we are fairly
close together.''
   The effects of last summer's drought lowered GNP growth by 0.4
percent for all of 1988, the Commerce Department said.
   The various changes left the GNP at $3.995 trillion for all of
1988 after removing the effects of inflation.
   The 3.8 percent GNP increase reflects the year-over-year change
in the economy. A different measurement just comparing economic
activity in the fourth quarter of 1988 with the same quarter in 1987
showed an increase of 2.7 percent.
</TEXT>
