<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     01-27 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Surges Higher Despite Central Bank Sales</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar shot up Friday in foreign exchange
despite the intervention of central banks and the release of gross
national product figures that indicated a slowing U.S. economy,
currency traders said.
   Gold futures tumbled in reaction to the GNP figure, which reduced
inflationary fears, and to the dollar's strength.
   Traders said central banks intervened in the currency market at
least three times, but the dollar-selling did little to curb the
currency's upward price rise.
   ``After massive intervention there (still) was just too much
demand for the dollar,'' said Scott Horwitz, a currency trader for
Bank of Boston.
   Traders said the dollar dipped only briefly after the release of
the GNP figures, which showed the U.S. economy grew at an annual
rate of just 2.0 percent from October through December _ the slowest
quarterly GNP performance in two years.
   Horwitz said the lower-than-expected GNP figures and the
central-bank intervention ordinarily would dampen a rise in the
dollar, but they had little impact ``except to give those who buy
dollars the opportunity to buy dollars cheaper'' for a brief time.
   ``The foreign exchange market does not fully understand what's
going on,'' said Stephan Leach, a currency analyst with Chemical
Bank. ``I suspect that part of it may simply be that they (the
central banks) expected a different reaction to the GNP numbers.''
   He said many traders appeared to be waiting for the Bank of Japan
to enter the dollar-selling before they believed the central banks
were serious about their effort to halt the dollar's rise.
   In Tokyo, before the release of the GNP figure, the dollar closed
at 128.65 Japanese yen, up from 127.52 yen on Thursday. In London
late Friday the dollar traded at 128.93 yen, and later in New York
the dollar rose to 129.37 yen from 128.31 late Thursday.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.7655 late Friday from
Thursday's $1.7730. In New York, sterling fell to $1.759 from late
Thursday's $1.7672.
   Other late rates for the dollar in New York, compared with late
Thursday's rates, included: 1.8650 West German marks, up from
1.8475; 1.5875 Swiss francs, up from 1.5705; 1.1834 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.1849; 6.3357 French francs, up from 6.2832; and
1,364.5 Italian lire, up from 1,351.6.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with
Thursday's late rates included: 1.8570 West German marks, up from
1.8440; 1.5743 Swiss francs, up from 1.5671; 6.2875 French francs,
up from 6.2705; 2.0880 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0815; 1,352.37
Italian lire, up from 1,350.25; and 1.1853 Canadian dollars, up from
1.1816.
   In London, gold closed at a bid of $398.25 a troy ounce, down
from $405.75 late Thursday. The late bid for gold was $398.75 an
ounce in Zurich, down from $405.75. Earlier in Hong Kong, gold
closed at a bid of $403.99, down from $407.70.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $396.10 per troy ounce, down $6.90 in turbulent
trading from late Thursday.
   Republic National Bank of New York quoted gold bullion at $402.25
an ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, up slightly from $402 late Thursday.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at $6.02 bid a troy ounce,
down from $6.19. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current
delivery fell to $5.883 an ounce from $6.104 late Thursday.
</TEXT>
