<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 1850EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     01-27 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>Credit Markets Close Out Week With Price Gains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The credit markets wound up the week by making
further gains on Friday amid mounting confidence in the economy's
ability to grow at a non-inflationary pace.
   The benchmark issue, the Treasury's 30-year bond, rose 7-16
point, or $4.75 per $1,000 in face amount. Its yield, which moves
inversely to its price, fell to 8.75 percent from 8.79 percent late
Thursday.
   Early in the session, bond prices rallied in reaction to a
government report showing economic activity slowed sharply in the
fourth quarter. A bit of profit-taking late in the day trimmed the
gains in bond prices slightly.
   The news that the gross national product grew at a 2 percent
annual rate in the final three months of the year reduced concerns
that rapid economic growth might induce the Federal Reserve Board to
raise interest rates to keep inflation from flaring up.
   The fourth-quarter pace in the GNP, the broadest measure of U.S.
economic activity, was the slowest one in two years.
   Jay Goldinger, market strategist at the Beverly Hills,
Calif.-based brokerage Capital Insight Inc., said bond traders were
able to take comfort from an array of positive news Friday.
   The dollar's persistent strength despite intervention by central
banks lately has propped up the credit markets, he said.
   A comment by President Bush at a news conference Friday
indicating he shares Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan's views on the
economy and inflation also cheered bond traders who were worried
that the White House and the Fed may be at odds over policy,
Goldinger said.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, prices of short-term
government issues were up around [ point, intermediate maturities
rose about 7-32 point to 9-32 point, and long-term issues gained
7-16 point, according to Telerate Inc., a financial information
service.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, increased 2.22 to 1,141.88.
   In corporate bond trading, industrials rose slightly. Moody's
Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures price
movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or
longer, increased 0.39 to 299.76.
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds rose 5-32 point to 92 21-32. The average
yield to maturity declined to 7.63 percent from 7.64 percent late
Thursday.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills fell to 8.57 percent as the
discount dropped 5 basis points to 8.31 percent. Yields on six-month
bills were unchanged at 8.82 percent as the discount edged up to
8.35 percent. Yields on one-year bills fell to 8.93 percent as the
discount dropped 5 basis points to 8.28 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, was quoted late in the day at 9[ percent, compared with 93-16
percent late Thursday.
</TEXT>
