<DOCNO> AP890127-0303 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 1924EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Pepperell-Farley     01-27 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pepperell-Farley,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pepperell Says It Is Talking With Third Parties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST POINT, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Point-Pepperell Inc. said Friday it
is talking with third parties interested in buying the textile
company, the target of a $1.4 billion hostile takeover attempt by
Farley Inc. of Chicago.
   In an amendment of its response to the Farley offer filed with
the Securities and Exchange Commission, Pepperell said it continues
to maintain that the company is not for sale ``but is continuing to
review ... various financial alternatives to the offer.''
   ``The company has entered into preliminary negotiations with
various third parties who have expressed an interest in a
transaction involving the company ...,'' it said.
   West Point-based Pepperell, the nation's largest publicly held
textile company, is fighting Farley's takeover attempt in court.
   Today's announcement appears to be more than a simple search for
a ``white knight,'' or a buyer other than Farley, said Deborah
Bronston, a textile industry analyst with Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc. in New York.
   ``They have said this before, but not in such a concrete way,''
she said. ``It leaves open the option that if they win in the
courts, they may not do anything. I think they have to come to the
special shareholders meeting Feb. 25 with a financial alternative
(to the Farley attempt), and so far they don't have one.''
   Farley has succeeded in forcing a shareholders meeting Feb. 25 at
which it will seek to replace Pepperell's directors with a new board
that would approve the Farley takeover.
   Ms. Bronston said it is unclear who the other potential buyers
might be, but she said Sam Walton, the owner of Wal-Mart stores and
one of the richest people in the United States, has been mentioned.
   ``I heard he was (in Georgia) having a grilled cheese with
someone recently, but it could have been just a store opening,'' she
said.
   Farley announced this week that, in addition to the 9.8 percent
of Pepperell stock it owns, it has been tendered about 52 percent of
the outstanding shares by Pepperell shareholders.
   Farley has filed a federal lawsuit contending that Georgia's
anti-takeover law unfairly hinders corporate takeovers by making
them virtually impossible. The hostile takeover of Pepperell depends
on revocation of the law, among other things.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
