<FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 1939EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-IC-Prospect     01-27 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IC-Prospect,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>New York-Based Group Announces Tender Offer for IC Railroad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Prospect Group launched a $440 million tender
offer Friday for Illinois Central Transportation Co., less than a
month after the railroad was spun off by Whitman Corp.
   IC's immediate reaction to the $20-a-share offer was cautious.
   ``There's so much going on right now that we can't say anything
beyond we're looking at it and we'll decide in the next couple of
days how to proceed,'' said IC spokesman Joe Fidanza.
   IC jumped to $22.37{ a share on the New York Stock Exchange, up
from $14.50 at Thursday's close.
   New York-based Prospect, which operates in the railroad,
insurance, and consumer products and services businesses through
subsidiaries, already owns 4.7 percent of IC's 21.7 million
outstanding shares.
   Also Friday, grain giant Archer-Daniels-Midland Co. announced it
intended to increase its IC holdings _ for investment purposes only
_ from about 10 percent to at least 15 percent, and perhaps as high
as 25 percent.
   ``The railroad provides a good connection between Chicago and New
Orleans and it carries a lot of chemicals and grain,'' said Linda
Dunn, an analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in New York.
   IC Transportation Co., known formerly as the Illinois Central
Gulf Railroad, runs freight operations and leases track for some
passenger services over 2,850 miles in seven states _ Illinois,
Indiana, Kentucky, Tennessee, Mississippi, Alabama and Louisiana.
   The railroad was spun off Jan. 1 after an infusion of $180
million in equity by parent Whitman Corp., a Chicago-based
conglomerate previously known as IC Industries.
   IC last year had net income of $47.7 million on revenue of $556.4
million. Any acquirer would also inherit about $260 million in
long-term debt.
   Prospect bought 400 miles of track from the Illinois Central Gulf
Co. in May 1986 and renamed it MidSouth. After expanding to about
1,200 miles through other acquisitions, the line became one of the
nation's most profitable railroads.
   ``MidSouth was one of those successes that dazzles and that's
what encouraged us to go ahead on this one,'' said Prospect
spokesman Donald Dwight. ``MidSouth already has done a lot of
business with the IC, many of the customers are the same and
Prospect just feels it would like to take that experience and step
into a larger arena.''
   One of the customers in common is Decatur, Ill.-based ADM.
   ADM is one of IC's 10 largest customers. The company also owns a
fleet of more than 1,400 barges and 19 towboats, and its heightened
interest in the railroad may stem from the low water levels on the
Mississippi River caused by last summer's drought and the
possibility of continued problems on the commercial waterway.
</TEXT>
