<HEAD>London Shares Surge On Favorable Trade Report</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 4th graf to CORRECT December deficit to $2.23 billion sted
$2.94 billion; picks up 5th graf pvs bg'ng, The financial ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rose sharply in extremely heavy
trading Friday on London's Stock Exchange as a favorable British
trade report fueled already positive investor sentiment.
   At the close, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index
was up 46.1 points, or 2.4 percent, at 2,005.9.
   The high point came at midafternoon, when the index moved up 57.6
points.
   Britain's merchandise deficit narrowed to $2.23 billion in
December from a revised $3.31 billion in November, the government
said.
   The financial markets had expected the December deficit to total
$2.64 billion.
   The trade figures provided further evidence that Britain's
economic growth was slowing, helping to increase hopes that the next
move in interest rates might be downward, dealers said.
   ``The market has put in quite an exceptional performance,'' said
Bill Smith, an equity market strategist at Prudential-Bache Capital
Funding Ltd.
   As in recent sessions, trading opened on a tentative note, with
the 100-share index up just 5.5 points, amid near disbelief at the
market's virtually unhindered rise in recent weeks.
   Since the beginning of the year, the 100-share index has gained
11.9 percent.
   The narrower Financial Times 30-share index closed with a gain of
39.7 points at 1,641.0.
   The Financial Times 500 share index was at 1129.38, up 25.36.
   Volume surged to 1.17 billion shares from Thursday's volume of
624.5 million shares.
</TEXT>
